WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.360
[Amit Varma]: The world is a complex place, perhaps too complex for us to understand in its entirety.

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:15.980
[Amit Varma]: As a species, we cope by telling ourselves stories about the world so that we can explain

00:00:15.980 --> 00:00:16.980
[Amit Varma]: it to ourselves.

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:19.460
[Amit Varma]: That's how religion came about, in fact.

00:00:19.460 --> 00:00:24.680
[Amit Varma]: In an age before science, we needed to explain the baffling natural phenomena around us.

00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:26.280
[Amit Varma]: Where does the sun come from?

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:27.280
[Amit Varma]: Sun God.

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:28.280
[Amit Varma]: What explains thunder?

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:29.280
[Amit Varma]: Thunder God.

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:34.240
[Amit Varma]: Religions, of course, kept evolving, and with time, rationalism and science played a part

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:38.680
[Amit Varma]: in building truer narratives, a journey of discovery we are still on.

00:00:38.680 --> 00:00:44.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, I often say that we draw our pictures of the world by joining dots.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:49.280
[Amit Varma]: The more dots we have, the better the resolution, the clearer our picture.

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:50.480
[Amit Varma]: And what are these dots?

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:53.080
[Amit Varma]: At one level, these dots are knowledge.

00:00:53.080 --> 00:00:57.640
[Amit Varma]: Every data point about the world helps us understand it better, unless, of course, we

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:00.400
[Amit Varma]: are getting those data points from news television.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:05.640
[Amit Varma]: But as much as information, we also need to build frames of reference through which we

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:06.880
[Amit Varma]: look at the world.

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:11.320
[Amit Varma]: And we need multiple frames, because any one frame on its own will be simplistic.

00:01:11.320 --> 00:01:15.760
[Amit Varma]: Now, I know people who have one hammer for every nail, one lens through which they look

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:16.760
[Amit Varma]: at the world.

00:01:16.760 --> 00:01:22.360
[Amit Varma]: But the intellectuals I respect are those who have humility about how little they know,

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:27.320
[Amit Varma]: how little they understand, and who are trying to learn something new every day.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:32.400
[Amit Varma]: One way of doing this is by reading a lot, but quantity of reading is not enough.

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:33.520
[Amit Varma]: Quality matters.

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:39.320
[Amit Varma]: You also need to be able to read across disciplines, so you can think out of the box on any one

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:43.520
[Amit Varma]: issue, bringing multiple frames of reference into play.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:47.960
[Amit Varma]: You can bring insights from psychology into economics, or insights from probability theory

00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:49.440
[Amit Varma]: to cricket strategy.

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:54.640
[Amit Varma]: And ideally, you need to not just gather knowledge this way and sharpen your vision, but it would

00:01:54.640 --> 00:02:02.240
[Amit Varma]: help if you're a bloody good writer as well, so you can communicate your ideas to the world.

