00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:54.720
[Amit Varma]: So who is this Raghu Sanjay Lal Jaitley or you know, where does the name come from?

00:06:54.720 --> 00:07:02.480
[Guest]: Well, the name Amit comes from two Amir Khan films in 1991, Amir acted in a film called

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:07.040
[Guest]: Dil Hai Ki Manta Nahin, where his character was named Raghu Jaitley.

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:13.600
[Guest]: This was a, you know, our Indian version of it happened one night, the Frank Apra classic.

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:20.480
[Guest]: Mahesh Bhatt has either copied films or made films on his own life multiple times over.

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:28.160
[Guest]: So but Amir's name was Raghu Jaitley, and right in the next year in 92, Mansoor Khan

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:34.160
[Guest]: made Jo Jeeta Wahi Sikand, where Amir Khan's name was Sanjay Lal.

00:07:34.160 --> 00:07:39.480
[Guest]: So I sort of, you know, blended the two in to create Raghu Sanjay Lal Jaitley.

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:45.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, in your newsletter, you talk about how you were an 80s kid growing up in Bollywood.

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:50.120
[Amit Varma]: At one point, you say quote for the rare capitalist minded young boy growing up in the 80s Hindi

00:07:50.120 --> 00:07:55.360
[Amit Varma]: films presented two viable career options, a smuggler or an industrialist, stop quote.

00:07:55.360 --> 00:07:58.240
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you didn't go for the smuggler part of it.

00:07:58.240 --> 00:08:02.560
[Amit Varma]: But tell me a little bit about what kind of a kid were you growing up in the 80s?

00:08:02.560 --> 00:08:05.280
[Amit Varma]: I get the Bollywood obsession, because we had nothing else, right?

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:06.720
[Amit Varma]: We didn't have the internet.

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:10.720
[Amit Varma]: We had television, which would, you know, one state owned channel, which would, you

00:08:10.720 --> 00:08:12.080
[Amit Varma]: know, paucity of great programs.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:13.400
[Amit Varma]: So what do you do for entertainment?

00:08:13.400 --> 00:08:17.860
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you know, Indian should not be judged for being so passionate, and almost obsessive

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:20.320
[Amit Varma]: about Bollywood and cricket, because what else was there?

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:24.800
[Amit Varma]: Okay, that's for my generation, young people today should find other things as well.

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:26.640
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about that landscape.

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:28.400
[Guest]: What is it growing up in the 80s like?

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:29.400
[Guest]: Right.

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:35.760
[Guest]: So, you know, Amit, a lot of your guests actually share a very similar kind of a background,

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:36.760
[Guest]: right?

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:38.120
[Guest]: And that's possibly your background.

00:08:38.120 --> 00:08:39.120
[Guest]: That's my background.

00:08:39.120 --> 00:08:47.400
[Guest]: I grew up in a really small town, at the heart of which was a public sector unit, a factory.

00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:51.120
[Guest]: My father was a mid-level supervisor there.

00:08:51.120 --> 00:08:55.640
[Guest]: And really, there were three things that, you know, sort of my life revolved around

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:58.600
[Guest]: at that point in time, outside of school.

00:08:58.600 --> 00:09:02.720
[Guest]: So the first one was, you know, TV and radio.

00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:05.440
[Guest]: That was the window to the world outside.

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:10.480
[Guest]: Even if TV was just a single channel sort of a thing, but, you know, we got a lot out

00:09:10.480 --> 00:09:14.040
[Guest]: of it than what today's people get out of television.

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:15.320
[Guest]: Same with radio.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:16.760
[Guest]: The other one was Hindi films.

00:09:16.760 --> 00:09:20.760
[Guest]: So in some sense, Hindi films was a connect to the rest of India.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:27.720
[Guest]: I mean, I never went to a metropolis till I was 23, but, you know, I had my own views

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:33.160
[Guest]: about how Bombay looks like and what people do in Bombay and colleges of Bombay and things

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:34.160
[Guest]: of that kind.

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:36.080
[Guest]: So that was second.

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:42.720
[Guest]: And third, you know, the state, for all its greatness, had made sure that we had a good

00:09:42.720 --> 00:09:43.720
[Guest]: library.

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:47.880
[Guest]: So really, these three were the things around which my life revolved.

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:51.080
[Guest]: Of course, there were open playgrounds and I played a lot.

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:52.120
[Guest]: I'm keeping that aside.

00:09:52.120 --> 00:09:57.480
[Guest]: But these three were, in some sense, you know, fuel or food to my intellectual curiosity,

00:09:57.480 --> 00:09:58.480
[Guest]: in some sense.

00:09:58.480 --> 00:10:03.120
[Guest]: And I was and I am a very, very curious child.

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:08.920
[Guest]: And I would still call myself a curious child because there is nothing that I don't sort

00:10:08.920 --> 00:10:14.720
[Guest]: of read up and there is nothing that I don't feel, you know, more inquisitive about.

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:18.920
[Guest]: So I continued that particular passion right from the time I was a kid.

00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:22.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, one thing that I sometimes touch upon is that, you know, when we were growing

00:10:22.560 --> 00:10:25.200
[Amit Varma]: up, there were so few sources of information and knowledge, right?

00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:28.280
[Amit Varma]: So whatever we could get hold of, we read voraciously.

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:31.840
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, our reading was not confined to any particular genre or whatever, because

00:10:31.840 --> 00:10:32.840
[Amit Varma]: we didn't have a choice.

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:34.000
[Amit Varma]: We read whatever you get.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.320
[Amit Varma]: And I sometimes contrast that with today's kids growing up, maybe Gen Z, which essentially

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:43.120
[Amit Varma]: can access anything, listen to any song at any point in time, read any book.

00:10:43.120 --> 00:10:49.560
[Amit Varma]: But the flip side of that, it strikes me and is that it is often remarked that, you know,

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:53.320
[Amit Varma]: young people of today don't have that deep sense of history, which is why, you know,

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:56.840
[Amit Varma]: you, for example, you see communism making a comeback and it's become fashionable to

00:10:56.840 --> 00:11:02.120
[Amit Varma]: be a communist again, which after, you know, the horrors of the 20th century just blows

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:03.120
[Amit Varma]: my mind.

00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:07.880
[Amit Varma]: And one theory that's been put forward for that is that, listen, in this modern world

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:12.480
[Amit Varma]: of hyperconnected social media, where there is so much new content being generated every

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:17.200
[Amit Varma]: day, perhaps more content as it were generated in one day, then it would have happened 10

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:21.880
[Amit Varma]: years before in any 10 year span before the internet or possibly much longer than that,

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:26.400
[Amit Varma]: that people are all the time consuming one, they take knowledge for granted.

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:29.760
[Amit Varma]: It's always there at the fingertips, you can Google or Wikipedia it.

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:33.880
[Amit Varma]: And two, what they are consuming is essentially very often stuff that was produced in the

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:35.480
[Amit Varma]: last three or four days.

00:11:35.480 --> 00:11:38.960
[Amit Varma]: It's transient stuff, it is coming and going, it is floating.

00:11:38.960 --> 00:11:41.640
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that sense of history is not there.

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:47.560
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, these, you know, one can form these ideological tribes on the basis of sort

00:11:47.560 --> 00:11:51.920
[Amit Varma]: of all kinds of ideas, which, you know, if you had the slightest knowledge of history,

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:54.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, you would not quite do so.

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:56.680
[Amit Varma]: I've kind of rambled, so I won't elaborate on that.

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:58.760
[Amit Varma]: But what's your sense of this?

00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:02.600
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, I don't want to point to you and I being good readers and all of that,

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:06.240
[Amit Varma]: because I think even in our generation, we were obviously outliers, I keep saying in

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:11.880
[Amit Varma]: every generation, it's the same small sliver of people who are readers and who are who

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:15.960
[Amit Varma]: satisfy their curiosity per se to that extent.

00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:20.720
[Amit Varma]: But what do you make of all of this, this sort of, you know, history ceasing to matter

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:25.800
[Amit Varma]: and all these narratives forming all the time the transient nature of the information that

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:26.800
[Guest]: we take in?

00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:32.440
[Guest]: I think so, I mean, it's a fairly interesting point that you raise, Amit, you know, there

00:12:32.440 --> 00:12:39.360
[Guest]: is a certain level of shallowness, which pervades, you know, every sphere these days, and especially

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:41.360
[Guest]: the intellectual discourse.

00:12:41.360 --> 00:12:46.960
[Guest]: And that's because, you know, people are very keen on getting something in bullet forms

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:51.680
[Guest]: and, you know, in listicles and getting to know about it and going ahead and, you know,

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:55.280
[Guest]: making a point or, you know, informing their worldview.

00:12:55.280 --> 00:13:05.960
[Guest]: I think there is a space for curated content by experts, which brings balance and perspective.

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:11.720
[Guest]: And I think that we have reached that stage where, you know, gradually this, you know,

00:13:11.720 --> 00:13:17.280
[Guest]: this plethora of choices that you have now for all kinds of information, I mean, it's

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:22.200
[Guest]: reaching a point where people are, you know, starting to feel that there is no sense to

00:13:22.200 --> 00:13:23.480
[Guest]: this.

