[Guest]: you know, whatever little sort of fame I have got, because of which you've known me, is

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:45.800
[Guest]: an attempt to actually do something like that, to actually take a topic, you know, view it

00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:52.360
[Guest]: not just from today's immediate lens, but ask yourself whether, you know, there is history

00:13:52.360 --> 00:13:57.200
[Guest]: behind something of this kind, I mean, which will allow you to understand how similar things

00:13:57.200 --> 00:13:59.800
[Guest]: have actually happened in the past.

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:03.400
[Guest]: And you know, like Nietzsche said, I mean, it's, you know, we are, there is eternal recurrence.

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:07.680
[Guest]: We are in a, you know, eternal series of cycles.

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:08.680
[Guest]: And it is true.

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:14.240
[Guest]: And as I have, you know, discovered while writing this newsletter, every modern event

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:20.720
[Guest]: has an echo of it sometime in the past, where somebody has thought about that kind of an

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:22.680
[Guest]: event, somebody has written about it.

00:14:22.680 --> 00:14:28.320
[Guest]: And therefore, I believe that, you know, just having a transient view of a particular subject,

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:33.160
[Guest]: you know, forming a very strong view about it is absolutely the wrong way to go.

00:14:33.160 --> 00:14:38.040
[Guest]: And people can go deeper, must go deeper, if you really want to actually affect a change.

00:14:38.040 --> 00:14:42.480
[Guest]: If you truly believe that you should affect a change, the shallow views actually won't

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:43.480
[Guest]: help.

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:45.720
[Guest]: You will need to go deeper.

00:14:45.720 --> 00:14:48.040
[Guest]: So and I can give you multiple examples of it.

00:14:48.040 --> 00:14:54.160
[Guest]: I mean, you know, I was just going through, you know, this insurrection at the Capitol

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:55.160
[Guest]: Hill, right?

00:14:55.160 --> 00:14:58.200
[Guest]: I mean, whatever these jokers tried to do there.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:03.040
[Guest]: And my thought immediately went to, you know, the first of this storming of the parliament

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:05.240
[Guest]: that happened in 1642.

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:10.440
[Guest]: Not that I'm a history nerd of that kind, but listen, I mean, I've read history.

00:15:10.440 --> 00:15:16.520
[Guest]: Like you, as I figured out, I was also a quizzer of dubious merit, but I, you know, went all

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:20.000
[Guest]: around the world trying my luck with quizzes.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.640
[Guest]: But then you realize that, you know, in 1642, somebody tried to storm the parliament in

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:25.920
[Guest]: England and various things happened.

00:15:25.920 --> 00:15:30.380
[Guest]: And there was somebody called Thomas Hobbes at that point in time, who was sort of observing

00:15:30.380 --> 00:15:32.160
[Guest]: this from Paris.

00:15:32.160 --> 00:15:36.320
[Guest]: And you know, a whole political philosophy starts off from there because of that single

00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:37.320
[Guest]: storming of the parliament.

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:41.640
[Guest]: So, you know, there are things for people to actually go deeper and make sense of what's

00:15:41.640 --> 00:15:43.380
[Guest]: happening around them today.

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:47.480
[Amit Varma]: So you know, a number of different strands, which I'm going to touch upon, the first kind

00:15:47.480 --> 00:15:51.520
[Amit Varma]: of observation I'm going to make is that, yeah, of course, I agree with you that, you

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:56.920
[Amit Varma]: know, there are cycles and history if it doesn't repeat at least rhymes, as someone said, but

00:15:56.920 --> 00:16:00.960
[Amit Varma]: a counter view to that would comes from what Jonathan Haidt said somewhere when he sort

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:05.260
[Amit Varma]: of spoke about, you know, how there is, for example, imagine an equilibrium of the laws

00:16:05.260 --> 00:16:09.080
[Amit Varma]: of physics, everything is as it is, and that is why the world exists.

00:16:09.080 --> 00:16:12.600
[Amit Varma]: And gravity is exactly, you know, this is a force and everything, you know, it's almost

00:16:12.600 --> 00:16:17.800
[Amit Varma]: as if the perfect conditions for us existing as we are does and then suddenly, one of those

00:16:17.800 --> 00:16:22.240
[Amit Varma]: constant changes completely say the law of gravity changes completely, you know, which

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:26.520
[Amit Varma]: would obviously change the world completely change our lives completely, you know, depending

00:16:26.520 --> 00:16:29.480
[Amit Varma]: on how much gravity changed by whether we would exist or not.

00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:35.400
[Amit Varma]: And his point is that social media changed something fundamental around the year 2007,

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:36.400
[Amit Varma]: 2008.

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:42.640
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, very briefly, for the benefit of the listeners, the thesis is that, as the

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:48.120
[Amit Varma]: Twitter's retweet button and like button and Facebook's share button, essentially, with

00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:52.320
[Amit Varma]: the instant gratification of validation that they brought did two things.

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:55.880
[Amit Varma]: One is they made the discourse much shallower because of the nature of the form.

00:16:55.880 --> 00:17:01.240
[Amit Varma]: And B, they made it far more performative, where simultaneously you lose depth because

00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:06.640
[Amit Varma]: you're restricted to 140 characters, 280 characters, and secondly, you are getting validated for

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:07.840
[Amit Varma]: everything you say.

00:17:07.840 --> 00:17:11.080
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that validation becomes a question itself.

00:17:11.080 --> 00:17:18.440
[Amit Varma]: And there is even a notion that it is this kind of need to constantly be performative,

00:17:18.440 --> 00:17:23.400
[Amit Varma]: that has led to, you know, all kinds of mental health problems as well, where, you know,

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:28.040
[Amit Varma]: in America, he speaks about how, you know, teenage girls, instead of interacting with

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:32.760
[Amit Varma]: each other in a normal person to person social way, their social lives have been taken over

00:17:32.760 --> 00:17:37.800
[Amit Varma]: by social media, where it's brand management, they're having to do all the time, which,

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:39.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, has its consequences.

00:17:39.400 --> 00:17:45.460
[Amit Varma]: So my sort of question here is that, you know, don't you think that in this exacerbation

00:17:45.460 --> 00:17:50.300
[Amit Varma]: of these human traits, as it were, which is what social media has led to, it amplifies

00:17:50.300 --> 00:17:54.580
[Amit Varma]: everything about us, both the good and the bad, that that can be a problem?

00:17:54.580 --> 00:18:00.160
[Amit Varma]: And two, do you think that this form of this course matters, like, you know, it's a strong

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:04.440
[Amit Varma]: thesis of mine that whatever form you choose to write in will shape your content, and therefore,

00:18:04.440 --> 00:18:08.480
[Amit Varma]: it will shape your character, that if for example, if I do three hour podcasts, I am

00:18:08.480 --> 00:18:13.400
[Amit Varma]: delving deeply and having deeper conversations and thinking more deeply about those subjects.

00:18:13.400 --> 00:18:14.960
[Amit Varma]: And that shapes me as well.

00:18:14.960 --> 00:18:20.280
[Amit Varma]: Whereas if I was doing like five minute nuggets, and I was asking shallow questions, and I

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:24.400
[Amit Varma]: had to cater to the lowest common denominator as news television did, that would shape my

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:27.520
[Amit Varma]: content shape the discourse and shape me as well.

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:30.680
[Amit Varma]: So form can change, content can change people.

00:18:30.680 --> 00:18:32.280
[Amit Varma]: Your thoughts on this?

00:18:32.280 --> 00:18:37.160
[Guest]: So on the first point, which you mentioned about, you know, history repeating or sometimes

00:18:37.160 --> 00:18:38.720
[Guest]: actually being a discontinuity.

00:18:38.720 --> 00:18:40.160
[Guest]: Yeah, I agree.

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:46.000
[Guest]: I mean, I think there are events in history, there are platforms and there are things that

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
[Guest]: happen in history, which are clear discontinuity.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:54.560
[Guest]: And in some sense, I would agree, I mean, Gutenberg's press was a discontinuity for

00:18:54.560 --> 00:18:55.560
[Guest]: sure.

00:18:55.560 --> 00:18:58.640
[Guest]: And, you know, we saw what happened because of that, I mean, protestant movement would

00:18:58.640 --> 00:18:59.640
[Guest]: not have started.

00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:04.440
[Guest]: I mean, Martin Luther, everything that he wanted to say spread around because of Gutenberg's

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:06.240
[Guest]: printing press.

00:19:06.240 --> 00:19:10.240
[Guest]: And therefore, the protestant movement and the protestant work ethic and everything followed

00:19:10.240 --> 00:19:11.240
[Guest]: from there.

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:17.920
[Guest]: And in some ways, this ability to, you know, connect socially in a manner where you could

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:23.600
[Guest]: have, you know, a million people listen to what you have to say and your sound bite is

00:19:23.600 --> 00:19:24.600
[Guest]: a discontinuity.

00:19:24.600 --> 00:19:29.840
[Guest]: So I'm, I wouldn't say that some platforms of the kind that we see today in Twitter and

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:35.960
[Guest]: Facebook are in any way sort of repeat of a previous pattern, except for the fact that

00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:40.480
[Guest]: something like this has happened 500, 600 years back, but in a very different way and

00:19:40.480 --> 00:19:41.480
[Guest]: form.

00:19:41.480 --> 00:19:49.480
[Guest]: Now, you know, those platforms do change how we actually have the discourse because, you

00:19:49.480 --> 00:19:50.480
[Guest]: know, you are right.

00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:58.280
[Guest]: If you have to have, you know, a space of 140 or 280 characters, you will choose a form

00:19:58.280 --> 00:20:01.640
[Guest]: of communication that suits that medium.

00:20:01.640 --> 00:20:08.820
[Guest]: And Amit, you write and you teach writing, you know this and you teach people about this,

00:20:08.820 --> 00:20:14.840
[Guest]: that you have to fit your writing to the medium and you have to both optimize for the reader

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:18.280
[Guest]: as well as what, you know, the form that you're writing.

00:20:18.280 --> 00:20:21.240
[Guest]: So in that sense, I completely agree with you.

00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:30.040
[Guest]: Even in my case, you know, I do a lot of corporate writing and if you ever see my corporate writing,

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:32.240
[Guest]: you will like, listen, what is this?

00:20:32.240 --> 00:20:34.640
[Guest]: I mean, why are you writing this in this manner?

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:40.360
[Guest]: This is clearly written to obfuscate and my simple, I would plead guilty because that's

00:20:40.360 --> 00:20:46.200
[Guest]: the whole point of writing that particular, you know, note is to obfuscate, is to have,

00:20:46.200 --> 00:20:51.040
[Guest]: you know, plausible deniability one month down the line, is to sometimes say something

00:20:51.040 --> 00:20:54.860
[Guest]: which you don't often intend to say in indirect forms.

00:20:54.860 --> 00:21:01.000
[Guest]: So there is a form that, you know, that actually changes and alters the way you want to, you

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.000
[Guest]: know, communicate.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:06.720
[Guest]: And I fully understand and appreciate that even some other instance of mine, I used to

00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:11.360
[Guest]: dabble in stand-up comedy, I mean, about six, seven years back, and it had become a bit

00:21:11.360 --> 00:21:12.360
[Guest]: of a passion.

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:17.160
[Guest]: So, you know, Three Wise Monkeys or wherever I used to be hanging around in, at that time

00:21:17.160 --> 00:21:19.240
[Guest]: I was in Bombay for some time.

00:21:19.240 --> 00:21:25.240
[Guest]: And I realized that people are just absolute geniuses, you know, to be able to do the amount

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:32.320
[Guest]: of, you know, content, the wit, the, you know, the sarcasm in a, in a three minute piece.

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:33.320
[Guest]: It's just amazing.

00:21:33.320 --> 00:21:37.840
[Guest]: I mean, later you wouldn't even remember what was the joke, but at that point in time for

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:39.640
[Guest]: three minutes, they were just fantastic.

00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:44.840
[Guest]: When you contrast that with, you know, thousands of pages of Yes Minister and Yes Prime Minister,

00:21:44.840 --> 00:21:48.920
[Guest]: you know, it's very different, but both give you, at least to me, both gave the same level

00:21:48.920 --> 00:21:50.800
[Guest]: of, you know, humor and joy.

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:53.000
[Amit Varma]: So I agree with you on this.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:58.200
[Amit Varma]: I didn't realize that Rego Jetly was also a standup comedian.

00:21:58.200 --> 00:22:00.200
[Guest]: We discover new things every day.

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:04.160
[Guest]: That amount of filmy knowledge had to come in use somewhere.

00:22:04.160 --> 00:22:05.160
[Amit Varma]: Filmy knowledge.

00:22:05.160 --> 00:22:06.160
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:09.760
[Amit Varma]: So we spoke about discontinuities and we spoke about history repeating or rhyming.

00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:14.240
[Amit Varma]: And I want to go to one aspect in which it seems like we have seen all this before.

00:22:14.240 --> 00:22:17.440
[Amit Varma]: And that, you know, there's a book Walter Lippmann wrote called Public Opinion, where

00:22:17.440 --> 00:22:20.640
[Amit Varma]: the name of the first chapter is something like the world as it is in the picture in

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:26.360
[Amit Varma]: our heads, where he points out the difference, the impossibility of ever knowing the real

00:22:26.360 --> 00:22:27.880
[Amit Varma]: world because it's so complex.

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:32.480
[Amit Varma]: If I remember that first chapter starts out with the story about how after World War One

00:22:32.480 --> 00:22:37.240
[Amit Varma]: ended, you know, even after it had ended four days, five days later, fighting was going

00:22:37.240 --> 00:22:41.040
[Amit Varma]: on in some places and people were dying because the news hadn't reached them.

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:45.880
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, effectively the World War One had ended, but it hadn't kind of ended everywhere

00:22:45.880 --> 00:22:47.640
[Amit Varma]: in a manner of speaking.

00:22:47.640 --> 00:22:52.640
[Amit Varma]: And that sort of dichotomy between the real world as it is, which is complex and unknowable

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:57.720
[Amit Varma]: and the worlds that we construct individually in our heads, that's a feature of the modern

00:22:57.720 --> 00:23:00.200
[Amit Varma]: time as well, where narrative control is everything.

00:23:00.200 --> 00:23:04.880
[Amit Varma]: Now, in, you know, one of your newsletter editions, you spoke about demand and supply

00:23:04.880 --> 00:23:10.360
[Amit Varma]: in politics and ideas, where at one point when you were talking about the newsletter,

00:23:10.360 --> 00:23:14.600
[Amit Varma]: you wrote, quote, the focus of this newsletter is to make public policy accessible to the

00:23:14.600 --> 00:23:15.600
[Amit Varma]: public.

00:23:15.600 --> 00:23:17.680
[Amit Varma]: This is a claim we often make around here.

00:23:17.680 --> 00:23:21.800
[Amit Varma]: There are think tanks and public policy specialists to advise those who are in power.

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:25.280
[Amit Varma]: We are at the other end of the pipe, trying to influence the demand side of the market

00:23:25.280 --> 00:23:26.280
[Amit Varma]: of democracy.

00:23:26.280 --> 00:23:30.840
[Amit Varma]: The hope is that an aware and an enlightened public will demand better from their representatives.

00:23:30.840 --> 00:23:34.120
[Amit Varma]: Once a pattern of demand changes, supply will adjust itself.

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:35.120
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:23:35.120 --> 00:23:41.360
[Amit Varma]: And you refer to the Lipman versus Dewey debates as an example of the wisdom of doing this

00:23:41.360 --> 00:23:43.000
[Amit Varma]: or the futility of doing this.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:47.520
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit more about your thinking behind this and why you are more on Dewey's

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:49.080
[Amit Varma]: side than Lipman's.

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:50.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:55.800
[Guest]: So, I think firstly, you know, there are two ways of influencing public policy, like you

00:23:55.800 --> 00:23:57.960
[Guest]: just quoted what I had written there.

00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:04.560
[Guest]: And a lot of focus of the think tanks actually is on the, is on focusing on the supply side

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:05.560
[Guest]: of the equation.

00:24:05.560 --> 00:24:10.960
[Guest]: Our view is that you can do that thing on the demand side, it takes time and it requires

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:11.960
[Guest]: a lot of effort.

00:24:11.960 --> 00:24:18.280
[Guest]: We are over a hundred editions down and, you know, we will continue.

00:24:18.280 --> 00:24:23.600
[Guest]: And my, you know, small hope is that even if 10,000 people, you know, change their opinion

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:29.960
[Guest]: or I would not say change their opinion or are informed better, you know, that's a success

00:24:29.960 --> 00:24:35.480
[Guest]: because I really don't think I have the ability or the access to actually change the opinion

00:24:35.480 --> 00:24:41.120
[Guest]: of a lawmaker or someone who actually, you know, makes the public policy.

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:48.480
[Guest]: But coming back to, you know, the Lipman-Dewey debates and, you know, in some sense it was

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:54.040
[Guest]: at the back of my mind when I spoke to Pranay about this and Pranay wanted me to start writing

00:24:54.040 --> 00:25:00.240
[Guest]: as well because Pranay came at it with the same view that we should influence the demand

00:25:00.240 --> 00:25:01.240
[Guest]: side of the equation.

00:25:01.240 --> 00:25:04.880
[Guest]: But let's go back to Lipman and Dewey and the debate.

00:25:04.880 --> 00:25:08.960
[Guest]: You know, it's a fascinating book that it's a great book.

00:25:08.960 --> 00:25:13.880
[Guest]: And what Lipman says is that, you know, when democracy and he takes the American example

00:25:13.880 --> 00:25:18.880
[Guest]: and he says that when, you know, just when democracy was, you know, the American state

00:25:18.880 --> 00:25:24.920
[Guest]: was founded, most of the people who came representing their, you know, their provinces or their,

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:30.080
[Guest]: you know, constituencies, they knew their people really well because these were agrarian

00:25:30.080 --> 00:25:31.400
[Guest]: sort of setups.

00:25:31.400 --> 00:25:32.400
[Guest]: People came from there.

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:35.240
[Guest]: They had very clear idea about what their people wanted.

00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:39.000
[Guest]: And the people also had very limited sort of views about what they wanted, right?

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:43.120
[Guest]: I mean, their world was just the village, you know, and the farming they did or the

00:25:43.120 --> 00:25:44.720
[Guest]: cattle they kept.

00:25:44.720 --> 00:25:48.680
[Guest]: And this is in early 20th century, Lipman had already reached a conclusion that this

00:25:48.680 --> 00:25:55.360
[Guest]: original thesis no longer holds because people have, I mean, the cities have come up, people

00:25:55.360 --> 00:25:59.000
[Guest]: are so different, they are doing different kinds of occupation.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:04.400
[Guest]: And so his view was that firstly, people do not have a full picture of what the world

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:05.760
[Guest]: around them is like, right?

00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:10.600
[Guest]: They are only seeing, you know, some narrow sort of through their windows, they're seeing

00:26:10.600 --> 00:26:11.960
[Guest]: a part of the world.

00:26:11.960 --> 00:26:17.640
[Guest]: And because they're seeing a part of the world to have to depend on them to have a full view

00:26:17.640 --> 00:26:23.200
[Guest]: of what kind of a polity would they want to, what kind of laws would they want is almost

00:26:23.200 --> 00:26:24.560
[Guest]: futile.

00:26:24.560 --> 00:26:29.600
[Guest]: And because they carry this picture in their mind, you know, people can be, you know, narratives

00:26:29.600 --> 00:26:33.500
[Guest]: can be built around those images that they carry in their mind.

00:26:33.500 --> 00:26:40.080
[Guest]: And those narratives then can be used and is used by politicians to actually win elections.

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:44.040
[Guest]: And Lipman was worried that this is a fatal flaw of democracy.

00:26:44.040 --> 00:26:48.960
[Guest]: And so for him, the idea was that, listen, there has to be an intervention of experts

00:26:48.960 --> 00:26:55.120
[Guest]: somewhere and experts have to come in, experts have to actually intermediate between this,

00:26:55.120 --> 00:26:59.640
[Guest]: you know, masses of people who actually form the, you know, the electorate and who actually

00:26:59.640 --> 00:27:00.640
[Guest]: elect people.

00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:06.440
[Guest]: And, you know, the experts have to, in some sense, you know, filter the requirements and

00:27:06.440 --> 00:27:08.200
[Guest]: the needs of these people.

00:27:08.200 --> 00:27:12.400
[Guest]: And in some sense, mediate between the lawmakers and the public.

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:18.400
[Guest]: And you know, just that idea is not, is revolting to me that somebody should come in as a set

00:27:18.400 --> 00:27:19.400
[Guest]: of experts.

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:22.120
[Guest]: But Lipman was very convincing in this.

00:27:22.120 --> 00:27:26.080
[Guest]: And you know, the idea that we all have an imagined world in which, you know, around

00:27:26.080 --> 00:27:31.120
[Guest]: in our minds and all, it's very powerful out of that, it's true also.

00:27:31.120 --> 00:27:38.080
[Guest]: Do we, who actually, you know, was admired Lipman and he said this is, I mean, as a concept

00:27:38.080 --> 00:27:44.720
[Guest]: it's great, but his argument was, we should not be giving up this fight so easily.

00:27:44.720 --> 00:27:51.000
[Guest]: And his point was, listen, there is something which is the knowledge of the collective.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:57.520
[Guest]: And the collective often has a view, which actually, if you sort of, you know, if you

00:27:57.520 --> 00:28:03.840
[Guest]: are able to use it well, is, will give you much better results than the view of the experts

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:08.960
[Guest]: and will actually lead to much more sustainable change in the society if you know how to sort

00:28:08.960 --> 00:28:10.480
[Guest]: of harness it.

00:28:10.480 --> 00:28:13.040
[Guest]: And therefore, his point was, don't give up on it.

00:28:13.040 --> 00:28:18.160
[Guest]: And this is like that old, you know, debate, Amit, between methodological individualism

00:28:18.160 --> 00:28:20.720
[Guest]: versus methodological collectivism.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:25.320
[Guest]: It's like, you know, Durkheim, there is a collective conscience and that works.

00:28:25.320 --> 00:28:33.480
[Guest]: But Dewey's point was work on this side, make people aware, improve their sense of understanding

00:28:33.480 --> 00:28:35.480
[Guest]: of what's happening around it.

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:40.640
[Guest]: And then, you know, harness the collective knowledge and the collective sort of wisdom

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:46.160
[Guest]: of the people, and then feed it back into the political system for effecting a change.

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:51.320
[Guest]: And, you know, I fall on the Dewey side, and that's why the newsletter is aimed at, we

00:28:51.320 --> 00:28:56.280
[Guest]: never address any sort of political or any think tank or any sort of, you know, political

00:28:56.280 --> 00:29:03.200
[Guest]: party or anything, our audiences squarely, the people, India, outside India, wherever.

00:29:03.200 --> 00:29:08.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, and that resonates with me a lot, because I think when I won my last Bastia

00:29:08.600 --> 00:29:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Prize in the prize winning speech also, I referred to the same thing about how we need

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:16.240
[Amit Varma]: to think about the demand side of the political marketplace, not the supply side, because

00:29:16.240 --> 00:29:18.480
[Amit Varma]: everyone responds to incentives.

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:23.280
[Amit Varma]: Your supply side doesn't give a shit about, you know, what random experts may say they

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:27.640
[Amit Varma]: respond to either the special interest groups who are lobbying them on the one hand, or

00:29:27.640 --> 00:29:28.940
[Amit Varma]: to voters.

00:29:28.940 --> 00:29:33.000
[Amit Varma]: So the best way to make change happen is to actually change the mind of people at large,

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:37.680
[Amit Varma]: which is also, you know, a larger sort of foundational battle within the Indian Republic,

00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:39.500
[Amit Varma]: which we'll come back to later.

00:29:39.500 --> 00:29:46.340
[Amit Varma]: But my question sort of here is that, at some point, I felt that this might not be something

00:29:46.340 --> 00:29:50.200
[Amit Varma]: which is say, within the reach of somebody like me, and therefore, by extension, someone

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:52.800
[Amit Varma]: like you, because we're writing in English.

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:57.240
[Amit Varma]: And because in India, it's just a narrow sliver of people who will be reading this kind of

00:29:57.240 --> 00:29:58.240
[Amit Varma]: thing in English.

00:29:58.240 --> 00:30:02.280
[Amit Varma]: Now, obviously, one can argue and say that, listen, history is made by elites after all.

00:30:02.280 --> 00:30:07.400
[Amit Varma]: So if you can reach enough elites, and change their minds, that does make a difference.

00:30:07.400 --> 00:30:11.760
[Amit Varma]: You know, that's a different kind of influence of policymakers and bureaucrats of tomorrow,

00:30:11.760 --> 00:30:14.020
[Amit Varma]: perhaps even the politicians of tomorrow.

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:16.200
[Amit Varma]: But I'm not sure how far that goes.

00:30:16.200 --> 00:30:20.560
[Amit Varma]: And like, do you think it's like last week, I did an episode with the venture capitalist

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:25.440
[Amit Varma]: Sajid Bhai, who sort of in his mind divided India into India one, India two, India three,

00:30:25.440 --> 00:30:30.960
[Amit Varma]: where he said India one was about 100 million people had the per capita income of Mexico,

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:35.520
[Amit Varma]: and spoke functional English with one sliver of that speaking the kind of English which

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:38.600
[Amit Varma]: would allow them to read us and listen to us.

00:30:38.600 --> 00:30:42.800
[Amit Varma]: And then there are 100 million people who are in India two who are, you know, plumbers

00:30:42.800 --> 00:30:48.160
[Amit Varma]: and Uber drivers, and so on, who basically have the per capita income of Philippines.

00:30:48.160 --> 00:30:52.760
[Amit Varma]: And then you have 80% of the country in sub Saharan Africa.

00:30:52.760 --> 00:30:57.480
[Amit Varma]: And they are, of course, not reading your newsletter or listening to my podcast.

00:30:57.480 --> 00:31:01.600
[Amit Varma]: So you know, if we think deeper, where does the sort of the change come from?

00:31:01.600 --> 00:31:06.240
[Amit Varma]: Like, is there a second order thing happening where hopefully, somebody who listens to me

00:31:06.240 --> 00:31:11.000
[Amit Varma]: or reads you, you know, becomes a mass entertainer at some point, and those ideas percolate through

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:12.000
[Amit Varma]: that way.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:17.400
[Amit Varma]: And, I mean, I'm glad that you are optimistic, but what's what's your sense of this?

00:31:17.400 --> 00:31:22.720
[Guest]: So I mean, there are, I mean, when you frame it this way, I mean, it's like,

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:42.440
[Guest]: I'm saying, I see that, I mean, let me give you a few examples of what gives me hope,

00:31:42.440 --> 00:31:43.440
[Guest]: right?

00:31:43.440 --> 00:31:49.280
[Guest]: There are people who send us mail saying that, listen, I've just cleared the IAS exam.

00:31:49.280 --> 00:31:55.360
[Guest]: So, so, and I used to read your, you know, newsletter, I always found it very useful.

00:31:55.360 --> 00:32:01.800
[Guest]: I mean, so clearly somebody is going somewhere who might be in a position of actually affecting

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:04.880
[Guest]: real change because of reading this.

00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:11.840
[Guest]: And I mean, the other one is you wouldn't believe the number of.edu mail IDs we have

00:32:11.840 --> 00:32:12.840
[Guest]: as subscribers.

00:32:12.840 --> 00:32:14.680
[Guest]: It's just amazing.

00:32:14.680 --> 00:32:20.000
[Guest]: I almost think that every week when I look at the people who are subscribed, I think

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:27.120
[Guest]: a third of it is.edu IDs, you know, so there is clearly interest and these are not, you

00:32:27.120 --> 00:32:31.880
[Guest]: know, of course there is a usual, you know, public policy institutions of India from where

00:32:31.880 --> 00:32:38.400
[Guest]: people, but the number of people that come from, you know, technology institutes, and

00:32:38.400 --> 00:32:44.800
[Guest]: it's a very, very reassuring and very, I mean, it really gives me a lot of, you know, pleasure

00:32:44.800 --> 00:32:49.760
[Guest]: and, you know, happiness to see the number of students reading.

00:32:49.760 --> 00:32:54.920
[Guest]: So I would tend to believe that there is a second order impact.

00:32:54.920 --> 00:32:59.280
[Guest]: The second order impact could be people who, you know, even if they don't go into public

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:05.200
[Guest]: policy, they just might be, you know, working in a regular corporate world, talking to 10

00:33:05.200 --> 00:33:10.960
[Guest]: other people, employing three or four people at their homes, you know, or maybe influencing

00:33:10.960 --> 00:33:15.120
[Guest]: another five people because of what they do for them.

00:33:15.120 --> 00:33:19.560
[Guest]: So I believe that's one way to continue doing this.

00:33:19.560 --> 00:33:24.440
[Guest]: Of course, the other way is to start thinking about doing something more in vernacular.

00:33:24.440 --> 00:33:25.440
[Guest]: Pranay does that.

00:33:25.440 --> 00:33:32.120
[Guest]: He runs a podcast in Hindi, which I think does a lot more than our newsletter in terms

00:33:32.120 --> 00:33:34.960
[Guest]: of, you know, how many people actually download it.

00:33:34.960 --> 00:33:38.760
[Guest]: Maybe that's also, there is a medium benefit there.

00:33:38.760 --> 00:33:45.280
[Guest]: But I think I would still err on the side of optimism because that's the right thing

00:33:45.280 --> 00:33:46.280
[Guest]: to do.

00:33:46.280 --> 00:33:48.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, I agree with you.

00:33:48.160 --> 00:33:50.640
[Amit Varma]: And this is really, I think, in a sense, a long game.

00:33:50.640 --> 00:33:53.120
[Amit Varma]: And Pranay's podcast Bollyabazi is, of course, awesome.

00:33:53.120 --> 00:33:57.840
[Amit Varma]: I have actually been on it talking about Hayek in Hindi, which is possibly the first time

00:33:57.840 --> 00:33:59.680
[Guest]: anyone has spoken about Hayek in Hindi.

00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:00.680
[Guest]: I've heard that.

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:07.640
[Guest]: By the way, since we are rambling and you mentioned Bastia, let me tell you, I had no

00:34:07.640 --> 00:34:10.160
[Guest]: idea about who Bastia was, right?

00:34:10.160 --> 00:34:12.240
[Guest]: And I used to read India Uncut.

00:34:12.240 --> 00:34:17.760
[Guest]: And that is when I realized that a whole lot of economics that I had read and I had read

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:22.040
[Guest]: a lot of economics had completely bypassed the Austrian school in India.

00:34:22.040 --> 00:34:23.040
[Guest]: Totally.

00:34:23.040 --> 00:34:31.440
[Guest]: There was not a mention of Hayek or Bastia or anyone from the Austrian school.

00:34:31.440 --> 00:34:39.120
[Guest]: I remember distinctly the, you know, the Candlemaker's Plea, which you had written on India Uncut.

00:34:39.120 --> 00:34:40.840
[Guest]: And I was like, where is this coming from?

00:34:40.840 --> 00:34:46.040
[Guest]: I mean, because I was surprised that there is something completely different sort of

00:34:46.040 --> 00:34:53.240
[Guest]: school that I have been, you know, not been informed of at all while studying.

00:34:53.240 --> 00:34:55.480
[Guest]: And I have not been taught economics.

00:34:55.480 --> 00:34:58.920
[Guest]: I have not taken economics as a part of your curriculum.

00:34:58.920 --> 00:35:04.360
[Guest]: But I read up textbooks of economics that were prevalent in Indian schools and colleges

00:35:04.360 --> 00:35:08.800
[Guest]: and there was never a single mention of any Austrian school economics.

00:35:08.800 --> 00:35:11.680
[Guest]: So that also is an interesting sort of a side note.

00:35:11.680 --> 00:35:18.400
[Guest]: And also, you know, a bit of my gratitude for you to have introduced a whole generation.

00:35:18.400 --> 00:35:23.800
[Guest]: And that's, again, an important point going back to what you've made.

00:35:23.800 --> 00:35:28.000
[Guest]: Somebody is reading it and then somebody 10 years later is writing a newsletter.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:31.760
[Guest]: So, you know, who knows what are the second order implications of things?

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:32.760
[Amit Varma]: No, no.

00:35:32.760 --> 00:35:36.880
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you'd, you know, you'd earlier mentioned about the need for someone to curate all the

00:35:36.880 --> 00:35:38.920
[Amit Varma]: content and all of that, which is out there.

00:35:38.920 --> 00:35:43.440
[Amit Varma]: And I see us in a sense as curators of ideas, like I remember at one point when I was writing

00:35:43.440 --> 00:35:44.440
[Amit Varma]: India Uncut.

00:35:44.440 --> 00:35:47.720
[Amit Varma]: And for those of my listeners who are too young or who may not be aware, India Uncut

00:35:47.720 --> 00:35:50.520
[Amit Varma]: is a blog I wrote between 2003 and 2008.

00:35:50.520 --> 00:35:54.520
[Amit Varma]: I think in five years, I did about 8000 posts, I do five posts a day.

00:35:54.520 --> 00:35:55.840
[Amit Varma]: So I was incredibly prolific.

00:35:55.840 --> 00:36:00.760
[Amit Varma]: And then of course, I moved on to play poker professionally and blogging kind of died because

00:36:00.760 --> 00:36:03.440
[Amit Varma]: social media disaggregated all its functions.

00:36:03.440 --> 00:36:08.360
[Amit Varma]: But I remember receiving a letter from an NRI student, I think in New Zealand or somewhere,

00:36:08.360 --> 00:36:10.520
[Amit Varma]: where he said that, please keep doing what you're doing.

00:36:10.520 --> 00:36:14.240
[Amit Varma]: Because I don't read any Indian newspapers, I don't read anything every morning, the first

00:36:14.240 --> 00:36:18.640
[Amit Varma]: thing I do is I go to India Uncut and see, okay, what has Amit posted, because that's

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:21.800
[Amit Varma]: where I get a sense of the country from.

00:36:21.800 --> 00:36:26.360
[Amit Varma]: And that's one of the things that motivated me to post in the kind of volume that I did

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:31.280
[Amit Varma]: over the time that I did, because that was gratifying in and of itself.

00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:36.400
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the Candlemakers petition, by the way, is Bastia's famous satire against

00:36:36.400 --> 00:36:40.760
[Amit Varma]: protectionism, which is a letter from a Candlemaker to the government saying, please ban the sun

00:36:40.760 --> 00:36:46.280
[Amit Varma]: because my business is being affected, which is quite, you know, wonderful.

00:36:46.280 --> 00:36:50.260
[Amit Varma]: And you know, responding to your aside with an aside, that is one reason I'm glad that

00:36:50.260 --> 00:36:55.160
[Amit Varma]: like you, I didn't study economics in college, because, you know, my thinking may have gotten

00:36:55.160 --> 00:36:57.120
[Amit Varma]: fructified in certain ways.

00:36:57.120 --> 00:37:00.960
[Amit Varma]: And I may not have been open enough to be able to discover Bastia and the Austrians

00:37:00.960 --> 00:37:04.600
[Amit Varma]: who came after him, Mises Hayek and so on.

00:37:04.600 --> 00:37:08.620
[Amit Varma]: And of course, once you discover these people and, you know, read them, it's like a light

00:37:08.620 --> 00:37:11.280
[Amit Varma]: bulb goes on in your head, it never kind of goes off again.

00:37:11.280 --> 00:37:15.240
[Amit Varma]: And kind of flicking that switch is extremely important to me.

00:37:15.240 --> 00:37:20.880
[Amit Varma]: And speaking of flicking switches, I'm also sort of, I want to quote from, you know, another

00:37:20.880 --> 00:37:25.960
[Amit Varma]: of your newsletters where you've written a bit about yourself, where, and this is your

00:37:25.960 --> 00:37:31.960
[Amit Varma]: 108th edition, so it's fairly recent, you guys have done 110 so far at the time of recording.

00:37:31.960 --> 00:37:36.240
[Amit Varma]: And here you wrote, quote, I don't remember when I lost my faith in the ability of the

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:40.640
[Amit Varma]: state to improve the lives of its people, perhaps it wasn't an exact moment.

00:37:40.640 --> 00:37:42.480
[Amit Varma]: Growing up, the state was all around me.

00:37:42.480 --> 00:37:46.360
[Amit Varma]: I spent most of my childhood in what used to be called a colony, one of the many that

00:37:46.360 --> 00:37:50.920
[Amit Varma]: dotted the semi urban Indian landscape in the 80s, a small industrial township whose

00:37:50.920 --> 00:37:54.760
[Amit Varma]: heartbeat to the rhythm of the government owned factory at the center of it, my school,

00:37:54.760 --> 00:37:58.600
[Amit Varma]: my playground, the hospital, and even the temple were all run by the state.

00:37:58.600 --> 00:38:02.360
[Amit Varma]: The state then subsidized a world-class higher education program for me.

00:38:02.360 --> 00:38:04.800
[Amit Varma]: At the turn of the millennium, I entered the workforce.

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:08.160
[Amit Varma]: If you had cut me, then I would have bled state.

00:38:08.160 --> 00:38:10.680
[Amit Varma]: Over the next two decades, I lost my faith.

00:38:10.680 --> 00:38:11.680
[Amit Varma]: Stop good.

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:12.680
[Amit Varma]: Talk to me about this.

00:38:12.680 --> 00:38:14.560
[Guest]: Why did you lose your faith?

00:38:14.560 --> 00:38:21.000
[Guest]: So I mean, sometimes when you read your, I mean, some, you hear someone reading your

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:28.040
[Unknown]: lines, it's a bit, you're like, okay, what have you written?

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:30.400
[Amit Varma]: But, but I love that phrase.

00:38:30.400 --> 00:38:32.360
[Amit Varma]: If someone had cut me, I would have bled state.

00:38:32.360 --> 00:38:35.080
[Amit Varma]: That's such a beautiful, vivid way of putting it.

00:38:35.080 --> 00:38:40.400
[Guest]: So, Amit, I think there are a few things, see, when you are on the treadmill, right?

00:38:40.400 --> 00:38:45.440
[Guest]: You believe that everything that's happening is happening because of you.

00:38:45.440 --> 00:38:46.440
[Guest]: Right.

00:38:46.440 --> 00:38:50.880
[Guest]: And, and I was on that treadmill that a lot of Indian kids have, you know, gone on before

00:38:50.880 --> 00:38:52.400
[Guest]: me and everything.

00:38:52.400 --> 00:38:54.960
[Guest]: I ticked all the boxes, the right boxes.

00:38:54.960 --> 00:39:00.480
[Guest]: And for me, all of this was on account of me because I, in my mind, was a bit of an

00:39:00.480 --> 00:39:05.320
[Guest]: underdog everywhere, you know, and therefore I thought that, listen, for an underdog like

00:39:05.320 --> 00:39:09.600
[Guest]: me to have done all of this must be me.

00:39:09.600 --> 00:39:15.000
[Guest]: And then once I entered the workforce and, you know, you started earning, but you also,

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:19.400
[Guest]: and till you entered the workforce, you actually, you know, when you are growing up, you're

00:39:19.400 --> 00:39:25.240
[Guest]: seeing very similar people like you, right, especially if you grew up in a colony as it

00:39:25.240 --> 00:39:26.240
[Guest]: was called.

00:39:26.240 --> 00:39:29.560
[Guest]: And then you went to college and you saw fairly similar people and, you know, if you went

00:39:29.560 --> 00:39:33.120
[Guest]: to the right colleges and the right schools and things of that kind, you just saw people

00:39:33.120 --> 00:39:34.120
[Guest]: like you.

00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:39.720
[Guest]: In the workplace was the first time when I started seeing a little bit more diversity

00:39:39.720 --> 00:39:43.880
[Guest]: or whatever it is worth for the kind of places that I worked.

00:39:43.880 --> 00:39:48.400
[Guest]: And then, you know, I started hiring people, I mean, in large numbers.

00:39:48.400 --> 00:39:53.720
[Guest]: And then, you know, you started going to other places and, and gradually I started realizing

00:39:53.720 --> 00:40:00.320
[Guest]: that, listen, firstly, this is not all on account of you and, you know, just your talent

00:40:00.320 --> 00:40:01.320
[Guest]: and enterprise.

00:40:01.320 --> 00:40:04.640
[Guest]: There is a privilege that you are born to.

00:40:04.640 --> 00:40:10.340
[Guest]: And the realization was not just that there is a privilege that you are born to, but that

00:40:10.340 --> 00:40:16.060
[Guest]: privilege is of the kind where the state becomes a force multiplier in your life.

00:40:16.060 --> 00:40:21.040
[Guest]: If you are born in the right place, then the state is, you know, helping you like nobody's

00:40:21.040 --> 00:40:22.040
[Guest]: business.

00:40:22.040 --> 00:40:23.040
[Guest]: Right.

00:40:23.040 --> 00:40:29.160
[Guest]: And whereas if you are born by the lottery of your birth, if you are in the born at the

00:40:29.160 --> 00:40:34.360
[Guest]: wrong place, then there is no state there for you to be sort of, you know, for you to

00:40:34.360 --> 00:40:35.360
[Guest]: get anything.

00:40:35.360 --> 00:40:40.920
[Guest]: And I saw this contrast many times over in the, you know, just the first decade of my

00:40:40.920 --> 00:40:42.520
[Guest]: work.

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:48.080
[Guest]: And once you sort of like, like you were mentioning, you know, the Austrian school, once you have

00:40:48.080 --> 00:40:56.080
[Guest]: seen it, you can't unsee it, you know, to sort of make a pun on the, on your show.

00:40:56.080 --> 00:40:58.960
[Guest]: And then I just couldn't unsee it.

00:40:58.960 --> 00:41:03.440
[Guest]: It was all around me that, you know, why is this not here?

00:41:03.440 --> 00:41:07.480
[Guest]: I mean, in the sense of why is this guy not getting the right education?

00:41:07.480 --> 00:41:09.800
[Guest]: Why is there no proper hospital here?

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:17.240
[Guest]: You know, why doctors are not there in just, you know, 50 kilometers outside of a metropolis.

00:41:17.240 --> 00:41:22.240
[Guest]: You know, all of those questions started, you know, in some sense, gnawing at me.

00:41:22.240 --> 00:41:28.680
[Guest]: And if you are a bit sort of, I would say reflective, which I am both observant and

00:41:28.680 --> 00:41:33.680
[Guest]: reflective, then you can continue being on the treadmill and do all the stuff that you

00:41:33.680 --> 00:41:36.680
[Guest]: have to do in corporate life or wherever you're working.

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:41.680
[Guest]: But this thing keeps coming back to you, that, you know, this is a privilege and this is

00:41:41.680 --> 00:41:47.680
[Guest]: a privilege of a very specific kind where the state actually, you know, was benevolent

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:51.280
[Guest]: because of where, you know, because of the privilege that you are born with.

00:41:51.280 --> 00:41:56.960
[Guest]: And that's what I wrote in that episode that, in that edition, that the state was simultaneously

00:41:56.960 --> 00:42:00.580
[Guest]: for me omnipresent when I was growing up.

00:42:00.580 --> 00:42:05.020
[Guest]: And then I realized for many people, for a large swath of, you know, Indian populace,

00:42:05.020 --> 00:42:08.120
[Guest]: it was omniabsent, it was never there.

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:12.840
[Guest]: And this, you know, simultaneous omnipresence and omniabsence is what, you know, really

00:42:12.840 --> 00:42:13.840
[Guest]: riles me.

00:42:13.840 --> 00:42:16.400
[Guest]: And, you know, why does it have to be this way?

00:42:16.400 --> 00:42:22.160
[Guest]: I mean, you can do, and there is in some sense, there is both these strands of writing, this

00:42:22.160 --> 00:42:28.980
[Guest]: useless omnipresence, you know, place of the state and where it has to be there, the complete

00:42:28.980 --> 00:42:29.980
[Guest]: absence of the state.

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:30.980
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

00:42:30.980 --> 00:42:32.160
[Amit Varma]: I couldn't agree with you more.

00:42:32.160 --> 00:42:36.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you know, like I know both of us will agree, the Indian state is simultaneously

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:40.200
[Amit Varma]: too small and too large, it's too small in the sense that it doesn't fulfill its essential

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:44.720
[Amit Varma]: functions properly, like the rule of law, which I think for most poor people in this

00:42:44.720 --> 00:42:48.480
[Amit Varma]: country is absent, if not for almost everybody, in fact.

00:42:48.480 --> 00:42:52.960
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, it does too many things which it should not be doing and in many ways

00:42:52.960 --> 00:43:00.200
[Amit Varma]: is almost predatory and parasitic presence, like I like to say, suitably alliterative.

00:43:00.200 --> 00:43:06.160
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of, you know, now talk a little bit about the state, especially the Indian

00:43:06.160 --> 00:43:08.040
[Amit Varma]: conception of the state.

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:13.400
[Amit Varma]: And again, what I want to do here with you is a conception of the state has something

00:43:13.400 --> 00:43:19.640
[Amit Varma]: to do with our circumstances at the time that we gained independence, where again, I'll

00:43:19.640 --> 00:43:24.600
[Amit Varma]: quote from one of your pieces, which is from the newsletter number 28, in fact, where you

00:43:24.600 --> 00:43:29.640
[Amit Varma]: write, quote, that the newly independent India needed to change wasn't ever in doubt.

00:43:29.640 --> 00:43:32.320
[Amit Varma]: The colonial rule had drained it economically.

00:43:32.320 --> 00:43:35.960
[Amit Varma]: Its society was driven with ancient caste prejudices and practices.

00:43:35.960 --> 00:43:39.920
[Amit Varma]: The enlightenment values of liberty, freedom, and equality that philosophically underpin

00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:44.360
[Amit Varma]: the Western democracies were difficult to root in the Indian intellectual or social

00:43:44.360 --> 00:43:45.760
[Amit Varma]: context.

00:43:45.760 --> 00:43:49.600
[Amit Varma]: Democracy with equal rights to all citizens was therefore an audacious gamble, but we

00:43:49.600 --> 00:43:51.440
[Amit Varma]: chose that radical end.

00:43:51.440 --> 00:43:58.000
[Amit Varma]: All that remained was what means we should adopt to change India, a stop quote.

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:01.960
[Amit Varma]: And here, of course, as you go on to point out that there were people who said that,

00:44:01.960 --> 00:44:06.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, the state needs to change society in a top down way and Nehru and Ambedkar were

00:44:06.080 --> 00:44:07.160
[Amit Varma]: for that.

00:44:07.160 --> 00:44:11.560
[Amit Varma]: And there were others like Gandhi, Shyamaprasad Mukherjee, Kripalani, who said that, no, you

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:15.720
[Amit Varma]: got to change society first, otherwise, it's not going to work.

00:44:15.720 --> 00:44:19.480
[Amit Varma]: And in hindsight, though, I think, you know, one could have come at this from the first

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:24.280
[Amit Varma]: principles which we both hold where, you know, top down interventions don't necessarily work.

00:44:24.280 --> 00:44:28.080
[Amit Varma]: It could be argued that, you know, the top down vision was flawed.

00:44:28.080 --> 00:44:32.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I have often asked, and I think in one of your newsletters, you cited it as well,

00:44:32.360 --> 00:44:37.680
[Amit Varma]: that eternal question of was our constitution, a liberal document imposed on an illiberal

00:44:37.680 --> 00:44:38.680
[Amit Varma]: society?

00:44:38.680 --> 00:44:40.480
[Amit Varma]: And if so, how can the imposition be liberal?

00:44:40.480 --> 00:44:44.040
[Amit Varma]: So I've asked that question to so many people, I'd be, you know, actually interested in your

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:45.480
[Amit Varma]: answer as well.

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:50.320
[Amit Varma]: But tell me a little bit about this, after answering this question, tell me a little

00:44:50.320 --> 00:44:57.000
[Amit Varma]: bit about this tussle at the founding moment of our republic, and how that led to the conception

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:58.320
[Amit Varma]: of the state that we have.

00:44:58.320 --> 00:45:04.560
[Guest]: So, Amit, you know, there are sort of two kind of lenses to take on this one, right?

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:11.160
[Guest]: One is this Benedict Anderson's, you know, imagined community, you know, idea of a nation.

00:45:11.160 --> 00:45:16.560
[Guest]: And you know, Anderson says that when a new nation is formed, they have, you know, these

00:45:16.560 --> 00:45:19.320
[Guest]: three things that they should ideally be doing.

00:45:19.320 --> 00:45:25.120
[Guest]: One is they should be showing that this is, in some sense, a break from continuity, what

00:45:25.120 --> 00:45:27.560
[Guest]: we are doing right now.

00:45:27.560 --> 00:45:32.200
[Guest]: You know, and that break from continuity is sort of important, because it's important

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:35.160
[Guest]: that you show that there is something new that is getting formed.

00:45:35.160 --> 00:45:40.920
[Guest]: Second, especially for those, you know, I would call it notion of a country which actually

00:45:40.920 --> 00:45:45.680
[Guest]: had some history, you have to still show some continuum you are still going.

00:45:45.680 --> 00:45:48.040
[Guest]: And this is not just something a complete new conception.

00:45:48.040 --> 00:45:54.920
[Guest]: So often the European states used a reawakening kind of a construct for this, which is the

00:45:54.920 --> 00:46:00.000
[Guest]: second one that you have to show that it is break, but it is in some sense a reawakening.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:05.800
[Guest]: And third, then you have to bring historians to construct this sort of story, which sort

00:46:05.800 --> 00:46:11.720
[Guest]: of fits all our past events into this sort of, you know, this kind of ideas.

00:46:11.720 --> 00:46:16.440
[Guest]: And I'll ramble a little bit, so just give me a minute, I'll come to your point.

00:46:16.440 --> 00:46:18.040
[Guest]: So that's one way of looking at it.

00:46:18.040 --> 00:46:22.520
[Guest]: And I think we followed it to the T. We said this is, you know, I mean, this is absolutely

00:46:22.520 --> 00:46:23.520
[Guest]: a new thing.

00:46:23.520 --> 00:46:29.040
[Guest]: He, like Nehru said in the, you know, Trust with Destiny, he actually used India awakens

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:34.080
[Guest]: when the whole world is asleep, India awakens to freedom.

00:46:34.080 --> 00:46:37.360
[Guest]: And therefore, you know, there was an absolute sort of right there.

00:46:37.360 --> 00:46:40.540
[Guest]: He uses exact words that Andersen mentioned.

00:46:40.540 --> 00:46:45.520
[Guest]: And then the historians, which is what today we complain about, of a certain kind went

00:46:45.520 --> 00:46:50.320
[Guest]: back and created all of these, I would say created all this, served that narrative.

00:46:50.320 --> 00:46:53.720
[Guest]: I think a lot of the narrative is possibly true as well.

00:46:53.720 --> 00:46:58.760
[Guest]: But maybe there were a few places where they sort of went a little overboard in order to

00:46:58.760 --> 00:47:01.140
[Guest]: make sure that this is a bit of a continuity.

00:47:01.140 --> 00:47:06.560
[Guest]: And that's where all of this, you know, whether Tipu is a freedom fighter or Ganga's Omni

00:47:06.560 --> 00:47:10.120
[Guest]: Tehzeeb, whether it is real or not, you know, you could argue it till cows come home, but

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:11.120
[Guest]: that was how it was done.

00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:19.520
[Guest]: Now, there is a very important line that Andersen makes there where he says that, and I'm possibly

00:47:19.520 --> 00:47:28.440
[Guest]: paraphrasing here, that the, you know, the modern concept of this nation has to contend.

00:47:28.440 --> 00:47:33.680
[Guest]: I mean, so the it's that the historians view of this modern concept of the nation has to

00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:39.640
[Guest]: contend with the, you know, the notion of the antiquity that is there in the minds of

00:47:39.640 --> 00:47:41.880
[Guest]: the society, right?

00:47:41.880 --> 00:47:46.760
[Guest]: This is what is happening there, that there is a modern concept of this nation which historians

00:47:46.760 --> 00:47:52.120
[Guest]: are trying to sort of now create, but it has to contend with the, you know, the deeply

00:47:52.120 --> 00:47:59.200
[Guest]: felt belief that this is a more ancient, you know, sort of a land than what it was.

00:47:59.200 --> 00:48:05.360
[Guest]: And that is, you know, that is the fault line, if you were to ask me, right?

00:48:05.360 --> 00:48:11.320
[Guest]: How much should we have gone, you know, on this spectrum?

00:48:11.320 --> 00:48:16.440
[Guest]: And I think in that sense, and a lot of people, other people have also mentioned, I think

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:21.640
[Guest]: the assassination of Mahatma Gandhi was a very, very pivotal sort of a, you know, thing

00:48:21.640 --> 00:48:30.480
[Guest]: in this entire thing, because when he was there, I think there was a strong force that

00:48:30.480 --> 00:48:38.800
[Guest]: maintained some amount of, you know, you know, got a lot of both political as well as moral

00:48:38.800 --> 00:48:44.160
[Guest]: force on the other side, that we need to maintain a certain sense of continuity.

00:48:44.160 --> 00:48:50.520
[Guest]: And the idea that ours is an antique land, whereas, you know, Nehru and Ambedkar coming

00:48:50.520 --> 00:48:55.600
[Guest]: at it very differently, Nehru coming at it from his Fabian socialist, you know, background

00:48:55.600 --> 00:48:59.960
[Guest]: and you know, whatever he had seen, and, you know, in Europe and the enlightenment values

00:48:59.960 --> 00:49:07.520
[Guest]: and things of that kind, his view was that, listen, this, if you go into the society,

00:49:07.520 --> 00:49:12.520
[Guest]: you will realize that this society stands no chance in terms of modernizing itself,

00:49:12.520 --> 00:49:13.520
[Guest]: right?

00:49:13.520 --> 00:49:20.000
[Guest]: Because it is so riven with so many prejudices and so many, you know, is that it is not possible.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:25.320
[Guest]: And Ambedkar, nobody need to tell Ambedkar about that, you know, he knew it, he felt

00:49:25.320 --> 00:49:27.800
[Guest]: it from within, he had seen it.

00:49:27.800 --> 00:49:33.240
[Guest]: So from both of them, this was clear, you know, opportunity for the state to affect

00:49:33.240 --> 00:49:36.280
[Guest]: social revolution, right?

00:49:36.280 --> 00:49:42.680
[Guest]: And I think the assassination of Mahatma Gandhi really, really crippled that other sort of,

00:49:42.680 --> 00:49:47.120
[Guest]: you know, movement totally, because in some sense, when Gandhi said that Congress had

00:49:47.120 --> 00:49:51.440
[Guest]: to be disbanded, which often today we get in WhatsApp as if, you know, Gandhi was saying

00:49:51.440 --> 00:49:56.360
[Guest]: that this Congress is a bad Congress or whatever, his idea was that, listen, we have not completed

00:49:56.360 --> 00:49:58.760
[Guest]: the task of independence.

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:03.520
[Guest]: What we have completed is the task of getting, you know, over the colonial rule, but it would

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:08.360
[Guest]: be an absolute disaster if you just replace one set of colonial masters without changing

00:50:08.360 --> 00:50:13.400
[Guest]: anything dramatically within the society and replace it with another state, which exactly

00:50:13.400 --> 00:50:18.160
[Guest]: takes over the entire apparatus and continues to do the same thing with a different name,

00:50:18.160 --> 00:50:19.160
[Guest]: right?

00:50:19.160 --> 00:50:23.320
[Guest]: But that assassination crippled it and then what happened is whoever were the true Gandhians,

00:50:23.320 --> 00:50:25.200
[Guest]: they had to make a choice.

00:50:25.200 --> 00:50:30.320
[Guest]: Some of them like Kriplani, you know, Acharya, Vinoba Bhave, all these guys, you know, went

00:50:30.320 --> 00:50:36.400
[Guest]: into the sort of the Gandhian way into the villages and try to do some, you know, Navnirman,

00:50:36.400 --> 00:50:39.440
[Guest]: not Navnirman, whatever, Sargodaya and things of that kind.

00:50:39.440 --> 00:50:45.840
[Guest]: Whereas the others were like, listen, we have to, you know, we have to be where the state

00:50:45.840 --> 00:50:49.200
[Guest]: is and we'll try and do this particular change.

00:50:49.200 --> 00:50:58.600
[Guest]: And I think that, you know, that balance or whatever, I mean, that adequate rigorous debate

00:50:58.600 --> 00:51:05.480
[Guest]: at that point in time that we missed because two, you know, titans, Nehru and Ambedkar

00:51:05.480 --> 00:51:12.120
[Guest]: were both on this side, meant that we in some sense thought that we will get over this problem

00:51:12.120 --> 00:51:17.000
[Guest]: and that, you know, if the state continues for a period of 50 years of running its agenda

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:23.360
[Guest]: of social revolution from outside, we will never again, you know, need to, I mean, we'll

00:51:23.360 --> 00:51:24.360
[Guest]: get over that hump.

00:51:24.360 --> 00:51:26.520
[Guest]: I mean, the society will change.

00:51:26.520 --> 00:51:32.840
[Guest]: But like now we are discovering, it doesn't change, you know, it's top down, centrally

00:51:32.840 --> 00:51:36.120
[Guest]: planned things just don't happen that way.

00:51:36.120 --> 00:51:40.400
[Guest]: And this is where again, again, this is that old Rousseau and, you know, a whole lot of

00:51:40.400 --> 00:51:47.600
[Guest]: these guys who believed in society as a sort of a, you know, place where everything starts

00:51:47.600 --> 00:51:48.600
[Guest]: from.

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:53.400
[Guest]: I think again, you can ask that question, whether these, I mean, these guys are right.

00:51:53.400 --> 00:51:57.240
[Guest]: And this is what one of my points is that, you know, methodological individualism is

00:51:57.240 --> 00:52:03.320
[Guest]: good in economics sphere, but when you have to run the state, you have to bring collectivism

00:52:03.320 --> 00:52:10.280
[Guest]: into it, not as a notion of economic sort of, you know, means, but definitely as a collectivism

00:52:10.280 --> 00:52:15.800
[Guest]: in the sense of how you change the society, right, it can't be just a top down idea that

00:52:15.800 --> 00:52:20.920
[Guest]: some one guy does, you know, and we then change the, you know, school curriculum and everything

00:52:20.920 --> 00:52:22.880
[Guest]: to say, this is what we are.

00:52:22.880 --> 00:52:26.680
[Guest]: But when the guy comes back home, his parents say, this is not what we are, right?

00:52:26.680 --> 00:52:29.680
[Guest]: You go study in school, all of us are equal.

00:52:29.680 --> 00:52:32.040
[Guest]: There is no casteism, untouchability is a sin.

00:52:32.040 --> 00:52:35.360
[Guest]: You come back home and exactly the opposite is happening at your home.

00:52:35.360 --> 00:52:41.160
[Guest]: And it's happening, you know, with while having the pictures of Nehru and Gandhi in your drawing

00:52:41.160 --> 00:52:42.160
[Guest]: room.

00:52:42.160 --> 00:52:48.240
[Guest]: I mean, that sort of dissonance we lived with, and those chickens have come home to roost.

00:52:48.240 --> 00:52:49.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:52:49.240 --> 00:52:52.320
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it sort of strikes me that, you know, now when we look back with the benefit

00:52:52.320 --> 00:52:57.640
[Amit Varma]: of hindsight, the sort of top down status thinking that came from Nehru, where it failed

00:52:57.640 --> 00:53:03.160
[Amit Varma]: is obvious in the domain of economics, where it is pretty much seen and I think there is

00:53:03.160 --> 00:53:08.200
[Amit Varma]: consensus on that, that it failed utterly and kept India poor for many decades.

00:53:08.200 --> 00:53:14.080
[Amit Varma]: But where it is not so evident is in terms of social change, because you don't know counterfactuals

00:53:14.080 --> 00:53:18.900
[Amit Varma]: and there can be arguments made that we would have been worse off if not for this and so

00:53:18.900 --> 00:53:20.160
[Amit Varma]: on and so forth.

00:53:20.160 --> 00:53:25.840
[Amit Varma]: But a lot of this is sort of striking because that fear of replacing one set of rulers with

00:53:25.840 --> 00:53:28.040
[Amit Varma]: another is essentially what happened.

00:53:28.040 --> 00:53:31.880
[Amit Varma]: We took over the entire colonial apparatus that the British left behind.

00:53:31.880 --> 00:53:37.440
[Amit Varma]: We kept the Indian Penal Code, which was put in place to govern the natives as it were.

00:53:37.440 --> 00:53:42.680
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and I did an episode with Tripur Dhaman Singh, where he spoke about the First

00:53:42.680 --> 00:53:44.560
[Amit Varma]: Amendment to our Constitution.

00:53:44.560 --> 00:53:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And when you read it, you realize that, you know, you spoke of Nehru's enlightenment values,

00:53:48.320 --> 00:53:50.800
[Amit Varma]: but Nehru is incredibly illiberal in that.

00:53:50.800 --> 00:53:54.240
[Amit Varma]: And Shyama Prasad Mukherjee comes across as a great liberal in that.

00:53:54.240 --> 00:53:58.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, today we speak about all these activists arrested under the sedition law.

00:53:58.360 --> 00:54:04.280
[Amit Varma]: Listen, the sedition law was made unconstitutional in 1950, Nehru brought it back with the First

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Amendment.

00:54:05.280 --> 00:54:08.960
[Amit Varma]: So this is something that, you know, people need to pay attention to that, which is not

00:54:08.960 --> 00:54:14.240
[Amit Varma]: to necessarily demonize Nehru or, you know, agree with the current dispensation that everything

00:54:14.240 --> 00:54:15.240
[Amit Varma]: is Nehru's fault.

00:54:15.240 --> 00:54:16.240
[Amit Varma]: Nehru was a great man.

00:54:16.240 --> 00:54:19.640
[Amit Varma]: He did a number of great things, but people contain multitudes.

00:54:19.640 --> 00:54:21.320
[Amit Varma]: And this shit really went down.

00:54:21.320 --> 00:54:26.040
[Amit Varma]: And the importance of looking back on it is kind of identifying, you know, instead of

00:54:26.040 --> 00:54:32.760
[Amit Varma]: identifying individuals as heroes and villains, but to talk about what structures of the state

00:54:32.760 --> 00:54:35.000
[Amit Varma]: have sort of let us down.

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:38.480
[Amit Varma]: And again, you mentioned sort of the project of shaping our history.

00:54:38.480 --> 00:54:42.840
[Amit Varma]: And I did an episode with Kapil Gomireddy where he spoke about this at length as well,

00:54:42.840 --> 00:54:48.040
[Amit Varma]: where he spoke about how you had all these historians sort of presenting a particular

00:54:48.040 --> 00:54:53.920
[Amit Varma]: vision of history, you know, with noble intent or whatever, but it backfired because society

00:54:53.920 --> 00:54:59.880
[Amit Varma]: remembers and what seems to have happened today in a manner of speaking is that, you

00:54:59.880 --> 00:55:02.840
[Amit Varma]: know, your politics has caught up with society.

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:03.840
[Amit Varma]: Society didn't change.

00:55:03.840 --> 00:55:08.720
[Amit Varma]: Eventually, once society got empowered enough, it is a politics that's changed and that's

00:55:08.720 --> 00:55:11.820
[Amit Varma]: sort of brought us to where we are.

00:55:11.820 --> 00:55:14.080
[Amit Varma]: You also had, you know, an interesting

00:55:14.080 --> 00:55:19.360
[Guest]: Sir, I mean, one, if I were to ramble a little bit and ask you a question, right.

00:55:19.360 --> 00:55:26.400
[Guest]: So, you mentioned that, you know, did we fail or not as part of Nehru's sort of social agenda

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:32.480
[Guest]: and the idea of what his social sort of views were and, you know, everything that we spoke

00:55:32.480 --> 00:55:33.480
[Guest]: about.

00:55:33.480 --> 00:55:37.640
[Guest]: And your point was, we don't know what are the counterfactuals, right.

00:55:37.640 --> 00:55:43.120
[Guest]: One way to sort of argue about this is how did others make this transition, right.

00:55:43.120 --> 00:55:50.120
[Guest]: So, if I were to sort of put this point or this sort of, you know, hypothesis that, for

00:55:50.120 --> 00:55:57.920
[Guest]: instance, the transition of England from, you know, agrarian traditional feudal society

00:55:57.920 --> 00:56:02.440
[Guest]: into a modern state, you know, how did the social change happen there?

00:56:02.440 --> 00:56:07.640
[Guest]: And somewhere, maybe, I don't know what's your view about this, but this whole thing

00:56:07.640 --> 00:56:16.360
[Guest]: about the protestant movement, you know, coming along with what Locke was saying at that point

00:56:16.360 --> 00:56:23.240
[Guest]: of time about inalienable rights, about the primacy of the individual, protestantism saying

00:56:23.240 --> 00:56:30.480
[Guest]: that was the God will only, you know, be happy with you because it's already predestined,

00:56:30.480 --> 00:56:35.520
[Guest]: you know, and that's the big sort of message of protestant Calvinism was predestined.

00:56:35.520 --> 00:56:36.520
[Guest]: Then what do you do?

00:56:36.520 --> 00:56:41.240
[Guest]: This is the moral sort of thing that you have to follow, that everything is predestined.

00:56:41.240 --> 00:56:45.880
[Guest]: And then the idea with Locke and others brought into play was, listen, it is predestined,

00:56:45.880 --> 00:56:52.100
[Guest]: but if you do well in your life and you succeed and the success is God's sign that your predestination

00:56:52.100 --> 00:56:53.100
[Guest]: is good.

00:56:53.100 --> 00:56:56.560
[Guest]: You know, some such, you know, broad kind of a notion.

00:56:56.560 --> 00:57:03.480
[Guest]: And that's how the society sort of took the idea of individual liberty and things of that

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:04.480
[Guest]: kind strongly.

00:57:04.480 --> 00:57:06.600
[Guest]: Is that, I mean, what's your view on this?

00:57:06.600 --> 00:57:12.520
[Guest]: I mean, did that happen through an organic social process rather than a top-down process?

00:57:12.520 --> 00:57:17.920
[Guest]: And did we just not have, we have just missed that boat altogether or that bus altogether

00:57:17.920 --> 00:57:24.120
[Guest]: because there is no reconciliation between some of our, you know, really core held beliefs

00:57:24.120 --> 00:57:30.240
[Guest]: versus what political philosophy we want actually to espouse for a country like ours?

00:57:30.240 --> 00:57:33.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a difficult question for me to answer.

00:57:33.120 --> 00:57:37.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, first of all, in the context of England, I simply don't know English history well enough

00:57:37.400 --> 00:57:41.800
[Amit Varma]: to be able to comment on that with any degree of knowledge.

00:57:41.800 --> 00:57:45.880
[Amit Varma]: So I don't want to wing it, but just sort of speculating on the core question within

00:57:45.880 --> 00:57:50.960
[Amit Varma]: that, that if you believe in certain values, if you believe in Lockean values, as say,

00:57:50.960 --> 00:57:55.120
[Amit Varma]: I do, and I'm sure you do as well, where, you know, the individual rights really matter

00:57:55.120 --> 00:57:56.960
[Amit Varma]: and are at the center of everything.

00:57:56.960 --> 00:58:00.680
[Amit Varma]: And we'll speak later about the Rawls-Nozick debate, but they would both have agreed on

00:58:00.680 --> 00:58:03.040
[Amit Varma]: this central point as well.

00:58:03.040 --> 00:58:09.020
[Amit Varma]: Then the question comes up is that say you are in the position of your founders in 1947,

00:58:09.020 --> 00:58:10.020
[Amit Varma]: what are you doing?

00:58:10.020 --> 00:58:12.920
[Amit Varma]: You can't just leave it to society and whatever, what are you doing?

00:58:12.920 --> 00:58:19.000
[Amit Varma]: So my tendency there would be, is to have a bare bones framework, which protects negative

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:23.560
[Amit Varma]: rights in the sense, which protects the right to life, which is against coercion, which

00:58:23.560 --> 00:58:28.160
[Amit Varma]: sort of tries to respect the consent of the citizens and treat them as citizens and not

00:58:28.160 --> 00:58:29.420
[Amit Varma]: as subjects.

00:58:29.420 --> 00:58:35.120
[Amit Varma]: But beyond that, not try to do deeper social transformation, because I think social engineering

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:39.320
[Amit Varma]: can have unintended consequences, which may not work out.

00:58:39.320 --> 00:58:41.360
[Amit Varma]: What's your response?

00:58:41.360 --> 00:58:49.600
[Guest]: The idea that somebody, it's the same notion of Adam Smith in social science, right?

00:58:49.600 --> 00:58:56.960
[Guest]: How can you imagine that you will know the preferences of millions of people and doing

00:58:56.960 --> 00:59:02.760
[Guest]: millions of transactions every day, you know, to be able to then arrive at this, you know,

00:59:02.760 --> 00:59:05.480
[Guest]: planned thing that this is how I will change.

00:59:05.480 --> 00:59:09.680
[Guest]: And listen, economic transactions, you can still believe that there is rationality in

00:59:09.680 --> 00:59:10.680
[Guest]: that.

00:59:10.680 --> 00:59:15.320
[Guest]: You can still take some, you know, solace that maybe in the economic sphere, people

00:59:15.320 --> 00:59:16.320
[Guest]: are rational.

00:59:16.320 --> 00:59:19.280
[Guest]: In social sphere, people, it's, they're not rational.

00:59:19.280 --> 00:59:23.280
[Guest]: I mean, they do not act rationally for sure in social sphere, because, you know, it's

00:59:23.280 --> 00:59:27.800
[Guest]: your children, your friends, your relatives, these are the people that are involved.

00:59:27.800 --> 00:59:35.520
[Guest]: So and, you know, you had mentioned Jonathan Haidt at the, at the beginning of the episode.

00:59:35.520 --> 00:59:40.240
[Guest]: And I, I find that's one of the reasons why I find him very, very interesting to read,

00:59:40.240 --> 00:59:48.040
[Guest]: because actually what, you know, Taylor or Kahneman and Tversky did with economics, Haidt

00:59:48.040 --> 00:59:50.120
[Guest]: actually did that with social science.

00:59:50.120 --> 00:59:56.680
[Guest]: He said, yeah, it's not so rational, this, you know, how you decide on things and how

00:59:56.680 --> 00:59:58.800
[Guest]: you arrive at social judgment.

00:59:58.800 --> 01:00:03.560
[Guest]: You know, that's why he then came out with this whole idea that the, it's a social intuition

01:00:03.560 --> 01:00:08.320
[Guest]: that actually drives a lot of our judgment rather than some rational way of thinking

01:00:08.320 --> 01:00:09.320
[Guest]: about it.

01:00:09.320 --> 01:00:16.080
[Guest]: And I think I link it back to that, you know, that famous Haidt article called the emotional

01:00:16.080 --> 01:00:22.720
[Guest]: dog and a rational tail, and the idea is that the tail doesn't wag the dog.

01:00:22.720 --> 01:00:28.080
[Guest]: The dog will wag the tail and, you know, it's you, the rider on the elephant metaphor that

01:00:28.080 --> 01:00:29.080
[Guest]: he gives.

01:00:29.080 --> 01:00:33.960
[Guest]: The rider thinks he's controlling the elephant, the rider has no, the elephant is just going

01:00:33.960 --> 01:00:34.960
[Guest]: in its way.

01:00:34.960 --> 01:00:35.960
[Guest]: The rider is sitting.

01:00:35.960 --> 01:00:40.800
[Guest]: Hopefully they will both align in terms of where they will get as they're going.

01:00:40.800 --> 01:00:46.440
[Guest]: So I mean, some of these things are quite, you know, in that sense, intuitive, that you

01:00:46.440 --> 01:00:52.920
[Guest]: should not attempt some of these things at a macro, you know, large programmatic level,

01:00:52.920 --> 01:00:57.520
[Guest]: sitting somewhere in the center and planning for it down the line that this is how we will

01:00:57.520 --> 01:00:58.520
[Guest]: change the society.

01:00:58.520 --> 01:00:59.520
[Guest]: Fairly dangerous.

01:00:59.520 --> 01:01:02.960
[Guest]: I mean, it's, that's where you eventually get into totalitarian instincts.

01:01:02.960 --> 01:01:03.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:01:03.960 --> 01:01:06.080
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, question there is where do you draw the line?

01:01:06.080 --> 01:01:10.080
[Amit Varma]: For example, someone could easily ask a counter question that, hey, what about something like

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:11.080
[Amit Varma]: Sati?

01:01:11.080 --> 01:01:12.080
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:01:12.080 --> 01:01:13.360
[Amit Varma]: You can't say, let society sort it out.

01:01:13.360 --> 01:01:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, you know, the state needs to sort it out before women are burnt.

01:01:17.320 --> 01:01:20.880
[Amit Varma]: And which is why I would say that I would draw the line at protecting negative rights,

01:01:20.880 --> 01:01:24.800
[Amit Varma]: protect individuals, protect their, you know, their right to life, their right to speech,

01:01:24.800 --> 01:01:28.260
[Amit Varma]: all of that, you know, remove all coercion.

01:01:28.260 --> 01:01:33.360
[Amit Varma]: But beyond that, how far do you want to go to, I mean, do you even have the capacity

01:01:33.360 --> 01:01:34.640
[Amit Varma]: to solve social ills?

01:01:34.640 --> 01:01:38.040
[Amit Varma]: If you could solve social ills, I would say you must.

01:01:38.040 --> 01:01:41.560
[Amit Varma]: But then the point is, you know, that is again what Hayek would have called the fatal conceit

01:01:41.560 --> 01:01:45.560
[Amit Varma]: of the state to imagine that it can do everything from the center.

01:01:45.560 --> 01:01:49.280
[Amit Varma]: Do you even have the capacity to solve for it anymore?

01:01:49.280 --> 01:01:54.240
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, that's the same kind of thought that I'll come to later when we talk about

01:01:54.240 --> 01:01:58.360
[Amit Varma]: sort of digital colonialism, as it were, and the power of, you know, Twitter, Facebook,

01:01:58.360 --> 01:01:59.360
[Amit Varma]: and all of these people.

01:01:59.360 --> 01:02:03.560
[Amit Varma]: And people, you know, often put forward regulation as a solution for all of these guys.

01:02:03.560 --> 01:02:09.080
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not certain social problems can be so easily solved through state coercion.

01:02:09.080 --> 01:02:12.200
[Amit Varma]: But we'll kind of come to that a little later.

01:02:12.200 --> 01:02:17.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, and you mentioned Hayek and you've written about him in your 102nd newsletter.

01:02:17.560 --> 01:02:20.040
[Amit Varma]: And this sentence from that struck me as very interesting.

01:02:20.040 --> 01:02:24.560
[Amit Varma]: So before we get back to the state, I'll sort of ask you about this as well, where you write

01:02:24.560 --> 01:02:29.120
[Amit Varma]: quote, regardless of how we define political access in India, left versus right, liberal

01:02:29.120 --> 01:02:33.840
[Amit Varma]: versus conservative status versus free marketer, each side arrives at the ideology based on

01:02:33.840 --> 01:02:36.920
[Amit Varma]: what they believe is morally right for the society.

01:02:36.920 --> 01:02:39.960
[Amit Varma]: What's the basis for our inherent self righteousness?

01:02:39.960 --> 01:02:42.080
[Amit Varma]: And why does it differ among people?

01:02:42.080 --> 01:02:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote, and then you talk about, you know, hate saying that we reach a moral judgment

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:50.280
[Amit Varma]: based on our intuitions, which are shaped by, you know, moral and cultural factors and

01:02:50.280 --> 01:02:51.280
[Amit Varma]: all of that.

01:02:51.280 --> 01:02:55.960
[Amit Varma]: And I'm reminded here of, you know, before we go on to talking about hate, one lovely

01:02:55.960 --> 01:02:59.840
[Amit Varma]: book I'd like to recommend to my listeners is called The Three Languages of Politics

01:02:59.840 --> 01:03:06.000
[Amit Varma]: by Arnold Kling, where Kling writes about, and he's writing in an American context.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:10.300
[Amit Varma]: And he's saying that a lot of political discourse becomes people talking past each other and

01:03:10.300 --> 01:03:14.720
[Amit Varma]: not to each other, because their priors are different.

01:03:14.720 --> 01:03:21.880
[Amit Varma]: So he talks about how progressives will come at everything from a first principle of equality.

01:03:21.880 --> 01:03:25.280
[Amit Varma]: Libertarians will come at everything from the first principle of freedom, and conservatives

01:03:25.280 --> 01:03:28.200
[Amit Varma]: will come at everything from the first principle of tradition.

01:03:28.200 --> 01:03:31.880
[Amit Varma]: And they're all coherent and logical when they come from that first principle.

01:03:31.880 --> 01:03:35.840
[Amit Varma]: So you could have two people who are having a completely coherent logical conversation

01:03:35.840 --> 01:03:39.280
[Amit Varma]: with each other, but it's not really with each other, because they're starting from

01:03:39.280 --> 01:03:40.280
[Amit Varma]: different priors.

01:03:40.280 --> 01:03:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And if you really want to have dialogue, you have to address the other person's concerns,

01:03:46.200 --> 01:03:48.120
[Amit Varma]: and then talk on the basis of that.

01:03:48.120 --> 01:03:52.160
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, it's just pointless, it's just noise, it's just echo chambers, which is something

01:03:52.160 --> 01:03:55.520
[Amit Varma]: that of course, social media exacerbates.

01:03:55.520 --> 01:03:59.320
[Amit Varma]: And he has a sort of similar point where he talks about the five foundations of morality

01:03:59.320 --> 01:04:06.080
[Amit Varma]: and how liberals only sort of take two of them into account.

01:04:06.080 --> 01:04:12.160
[Amit Varma]: How do you sort of place all this in a context of India, like what sort of the bedrock of

01:04:12.160 --> 01:04:19.360
[Amit Varma]: our moral instincts, so to say, and where does it become a problem for, say, a particular

01:04:19.360 --> 01:04:26.600
[Amit Varma]: idea of India, which is the liberal inclusive idea of India that privileges individual rights?

01:04:26.600 --> 01:04:28.480
[Guest]: It's a difficult one.

01:04:28.480 --> 01:04:34.200
[Guest]: Let's take an example, and then try and see if maybe we can take two and two sort of very

01:04:34.200 --> 01:04:35.200
[Guest]: different ones.

01:04:35.200 --> 01:04:38.920
[Guest]: And let's try and see if I can make any sense of this.

01:04:38.920 --> 01:04:46.120
[Guest]: Sometimes, like Amit you say, when you write, you really deeply think about a topic, when

01:04:46.120 --> 01:04:51.760
[Guest]: you talk, then you are not, I mean, you have to be really, really good, really fast thinker

01:04:51.760 --> 01:04:55.920
[Guest]: to be able to talk with the same level of clarity as you can write, and maybe it's never

01:04:55.920 --> 01:04:59.000
[Guest]: possible, at least it's difficult for me.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:00.520
[Guest]: But let's take this.

01:05:00.520 --> 01:05:03.320
[Guest]: So for instance, let's take this real example.

01:05:03.320 --> 01:05:09.120
[Guest]: We had a whole lot of articles come out in recent past, Oxfam report and stuff, that

01:05:09.120 --> 01:05:12.480
[Guest]: you know, billionaires made a whole lot of money during the pandemic.

01:05:12.480 --> 01:05:16.880
[Guest]: And you know, poor people were, you know, given a short shift.

01:05:16.880 --> 01:05:24.280
[Guest]: And some, you know, if Jeff Bezos just distributed the wealth that he made during the pandemic,

01:05:24.280 --> 01:05:28.080
[Guest]: each Amazon worker would get $80,000 or something, right?

01:05:28.080 --> 01:05:32.200
[Guest]: Now let's understand this from this ITN framework, right?

01:05:32.200 --> 01:05:37.600
[Guest]: So in India, because of maybe the last 70 years of whatever we have been trained and

01:05:37.600 --> 01:05:45.520
[Guest]: maybe before that as well, we view a few things, I mean, that these are our social intuitions.

01:05:45.520 --> 01:05:49.920
[Guest]: And one of them is that, you know, that too much of wealth is bad.

01:05:49.920 --> 01:05:55.080
[Guest]: We have some, you know, beliefs in moderation and not showing wealth off and things of that

01:05:55.080 --> 01:05:56.400
[Guest]: kind.

01:05:56.400 --> 01:06:00.920
[Guest]: And also we believe that, you know, people should be somewhat equal and, you know, and

01:06:00.920 --> 01:06:04.560
[Guest]: that's the general humanitarian sort of, you know, instinct that, you know, people should

01:06:04.560 --> 01:06:06.600
[Guest]: not be dying of hunger, et cetera.

01:06:06.600 --> 01:06:10.920
[Guest]: Now you get two trigger events, you know, you get one event that, you know, all these

01:06:10.920 --> 01:06:14.920
[Guest]: migrants have walked all the way back and they are not getting jobs and things of that

01:06:14.920 --> 01:06:15.920
[Guest]: kind.

01:06:15.920 --> 01:06:20.440
[Guest]: And you get this sort of trigger event that, you know, the top three billionaires in India

01:06:20.440 --> 01:06:23.480
[Guest]: have added so much of wealth during this time.

01:06:23.480 --> 01:06:31.760
[Guest]: Now your social intuition immediately, which informs your judgment is, oh, this is wrong.

01:06:31.760 --> 01:06:35.200
[Guest]: You know, how is, how are these guys making all this money when so many people are, you

01:06:35.200 --> 01:06:40.840
[Guest]: know, suffering and because of the intuition that you already have, you made the judgment.

01:06:40.840 --> 01:06:45.000
[Guest]: And then after that, now, now you are a, you know, privileged guy, you are driving a car,

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:48.800
[Guest]: you are living a life, you've had a good life during the pandemic, but it doesn't strike

01:06:48.800 --> 01:06:50.080
[Guest]: to you that, you know, what are you saying?

01:06:50.080 --> 01:06:54.600
[Guest]: It is the same thing for that guy who's made, he's not gone out and done something illegal

01:06:54.600 --> 01:06:58.080
[Guest]: and without, I mean, with coercion and things of that kind.

01:06:58.080 --> 01:07:01.280
[Guest]: If there were no Amazon, the lockdown would have been terrible.

01:07:01.280 --> 01:07:02.280
[Guest]: More people would have died.

01:07:02.280 --> 01:07:04.840
[Guest]: There was no Amazon, you know.

01:07:04.840 --> 01:07:10.440
[Guest]: But you then build a moral scaffolding of reasoning around this judgment of yours, right?

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:14.160
[Guest]: And that scaffolding is in India, very, very easy to build.

01:07:14.160 --> 01:07:20.000
[Guest]: It's, you know, we've been trained by our films, books, and politicians, speeches, Garibiya

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:24.600
[Guest]: Dao, all kinds of things to say that was, this is wrong.

01:07:24.600 --> 01:07:28.960
[Guest]: Now the problem in what happens is in that framework.

01:07:28.960 --> 01:07:35.080
[Guest]: Now this is sort of, you know, intuition, you know, whatever, and then reasoning.

01:07:35.080 --> 01:07:39.920
[Guest]: And then we make this reason, persuasion to other people, social persuasion to other people.

01:07:39.920 --> 01:07:43.000
[Guest]: We tell these things to others and, you know, all of us sort of gang up and say that this

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:44.000
[Guest]: is a bad idea.

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:46.440
[Guest]: And, you know, that's how you get the Twitter mobs.

01:07:46.440 --> 01:07:50.720
[Guest]: The two things that Haidt says actually should happen if you were to be somewhat think deeper

01:07:50.720 --> 01:07:58.240
[Guest]: about a topic is what is called private reflection and, you know, and rational sort of reasoning,

01:07:58.240 --> 01:08:04.880
[Guest]: you know, the reasoning, your judgment should now be informed by the reasoning.

01:08:04.880 --> 01:08:07.780
[Guest]: And those two things don't happen enough.

01:08:07.780 --> 01:08:10.080
[Guest]: And it doesn't happen in most parts of the world.

01:08:10.080 --> 01:08:16.160
[Guest]: But one of the problems of our sort of, you know, education system and others is that

01:08:16.160 --> 01:08:20.480
[Guest]: this private reflection, this idea that we teach you something, you go back and think

01:08:20.480 --> 01:08:24.540
[Guest]: about it, and then you don't come back and write exactly what I have told you to sort

01:08:24.540 --> 01:08:25.540
[Guest]: of write.

01:08:25.540 --> 01:08:28.280
[Guest]: I'll give you a question, you think about it and then write it.

01:08:28.280 --> 01:08:31.080
[Guest]: These are all sort of, you know, largely missing.

01:08:31.080 --> 01:08:38.880
[Guest]: So, you know, so to your point, I think this, this loop, which comes back around private

01:08:38.880 --> 01:08:45.280
[Guest]: reflection or, you know, or a more informed reasoning is a problem and we don't have that.

01:08:45.280 --> 01:08:48.120
[Guest]: And you can take the same lens to any other problem.

01:08:48.120 --> 01:08:52.160
[Guest]: I mean, you can take that lens to, you know, love jihad.

01:08:52.160 --> 01:08:57.160
[Guest]: But you'll find almost the same sort of thing because there is not enough and there is also

01:08:57.160 --> 01:09:01.600
[Guest]: not enough discourse in the media, in, you know, these talking head debates that we see

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:02.600
[Guest]: in TV.

01:09:02.600 --> 01:09:08.000
[Guest]: There is nowhere this kind of conversation happening where three people are deeply, you

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:12.600
[Guest]: know, having a conversation about, can you think a little deeper that it's not a zero

01:09:12.600 --> 01:09:18.160
[Guest]: sum game, like in that sort of, you know, that Oxfam kind of thing, that it is not about,

01:09:18.160 --> 01:09:25.640
[Guest]: you know, that somebody's made money by coercing others, that it is fine, that we need growth

01:09:25.640 --> 01:09:29.920
[Guest]: for everyone and then we will redistribute, you know, you don't get to that point of conversation.

01:09:29.920 --> 01:09:34.800
[Guest]: So I don't know if I've sort of given you some answer, but something of that kind is

01:09:34.800 --> 01:09:36.080
[Guest]: just not there anywhere.

01:09:36.080 --> 01:09:37.720
[Guest]: It's not there in the way we are taught.

01:09:37.720 --> 01:09:41.420
[Guest]: It's not there in the way we have grown up to sort of reflect on things.

01:09:41.420 --> 01:09:46.160
[Guest]: And it's not there all around us today in terms of any of the, you know, public forums

01:09:46.160 --> 01:09:48.600
[Guest]: where people are debating or discussing issues.

01:09:48.600 --> 01:09:53.200
[Guest]: Maybe except a few podcasts like this, there is some time to do this conversation.

01:09:53.200 --> 01:09:54.200
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:09:54.200 --> 01:09:55.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:09:55.200 --> 01:09:57.240
[Amit Varma]: You've actually made a couple of separate good points.

01:09:57.240 --> 01:10:00.960
[Amit Varma]: One is of course about pedagogy where, you know, the way that we are taught, you know,

01:10:00.960 --> 01:10:06.000
[Amit Varma]: we are not taught to think independently enough, though I'm not sure that that alone is, you

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:10.040
[Amit Varma]: know, a sufficient condition for not falling for flawed thinking.

01:10:10.040 --> 01:10:13.080
[Amit Varma]: And the other part of it is that a lot of this is just counterintuitive stuff.

01:10:13.080 --> 01:10:17.200
[Amit Varma]: Like, obviously, I hardly need to say to my listeners that, listen, number one, a lot

01:10:17.200 --> 01:10:21.520
[Amit Varma]: of the wealth that these billionaires gained during the pandemic was notional wealth, you

01:10:21.520 --> 01:10:23.240
[Amit Varma]: know, in their stocks or whatever.

01:10:23.240 --> 01:10:25.400
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't really translate to real liquid money.

01:10:25.400 --> 01:10:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And the other point is that, you know, in a free market, the only way that you make

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:31.600
[Amit Varma]: money is by making somebody better off.

01:10:31.600 --> 01:10:33.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's a positive sum game.

01:10:33.520 --> 01:10:38.000
[Amit Varma]: If all these people made so much money without state coercion being there, it means they

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:39.720
[Amit Varma]: made that many people better off.

01:10:39.720 --> 01:10:43.600
[Amit Varma]: And like you said, in different ways, perhaps more people would have died if that didn't

01:10:43.600 --> 01:10:44.600
[Amit Varma]: happen.

01:10:44.600 --> 01:10:48.520
[Amit Varma]: I'm not saying all of the wealth gains are necessarily through, you know, legit free

01:10:48.520 --> 01:10:50.680
[Amit Varma]: market ways and positive sum games.

01:10:50.680 --> 01:10:54.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, we don't know what kind of cronyism there might have been at the back of that,

01:10:54.920 --> 01:10:58.800
[Amit Varma]: but a significant chunk of that and certainly, you know, Jeff Bezos's wealth going up is

01:10:58.800 --> 01:11:03.800
[Amit Varma]: clearly because, you know, Amazon was so incredibly essential during this time.

01:11:03.800 --> 01:11:08.760
[Amit Varma]: Bezos is one of the sort of the great visionaries and heroes of our time and to demonize him

01:11:08.760 --> 01:11:12.760
[Amit Varma]: the way some people do is kind of absurd.

01:11:12.760 --> 01:11:16.480
[Amit Varma]: And you know, before we take a break on the show, let's take a Bollywood break.

01:11:16.480 --> 01:11:21.840
[Amit Varma]: You have, you know, we were discussing this sort of conflict between state, society and

01:11:21.840 --> 01:11:26.960
[Amit Varma]: markets, you know, the balance between them and you've written eloquently in your newsletters

01:11:26.960 --> 01:11:32.840
[Amit Varma]: about how markets were always out because we associated markets with what the East India

01:11:32.840 --> 01:11:35.480
[Amit Varma]: Company had done to us with colonialism and all that.

01:11:35.480 --> 01:11:40.120
[Amit Varma]: So the fashion of the times when the Soviet Union seemed to be doing well and was admired

01:11:40.120 --> 01:11:42.840
[Amit Varma]: by Nehru was that kind of Fabian socialism.

01:11:42.840 --> 01:11:47.120
[Amit Varma]: So markets were demonized anyway, and it came down to society and the state.

01:11:47.120 --> 01:11:51.560
[Amit Varma]: And obviously the way it panned out, the state took the sort of the bigger role.

01:11:51.560 --> 01:11:56.880
[Amit Varma]: But there was a film in the 1940s by B. R. Chopra, which sort of shows that battle playing

01:11:56.880 --> 01:11:59.520
[Amit Varma]: out and comes down on the side of society.

01:11:59.520 --> 01:12:02.000
[Guest]: So tell me a little bit about that.

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:11.560
[Guest]: So this is a 57 film, one of the great films of the 50s, B. R. Chopra's Naya Daur.

01:12:11.560 --> 01:12:19.080
[Guest]: And Naya Daur means New Age, headlined Dilip Kumar and Vaijanthi Mala along with Ajit,

01:12:19.080 --> 01:12:24.440
[Guest]: who played his friend who later turns a foe and an absolutely fantastic turn by a guy

01:12:24.440 --> 01:12:32.120
[Guest]: called Jeevan, who used to often act in 70s and 60s film as a villain.

01:12:32.120 --> 01:12:36.600
[Guest]: Now, you know, I have always been fascinated by this movie for various reasons.

01:12:36.600 --> 01:12:42.000
[Guest]: One is this movie is often quoted as, you know, the movie that truly represented Nehru's

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:45.280
[Guest]: view of what India was like.

01:12:45.280 --> 01:12:50.360
[Guest]: And my view was either you haven't read Nehru or you haven't seen this film, because this

01:12:50.360 --> 01:12:54.080
[Guest]: film cannot be about Nehru.

01:12:54.080 --> 01:12:59.120
[Guest]: And people, you know, as great as I think Meghna Desai, when he wrote his Dilip Kumar

01:12:59.120 --> 01:13:05.680
[Guest]: biography, he also alludes to, because his biography of Dilip Kumar, if I'm not, you

01:13:05.680 --> 01:13:11.640
[Guest]: know, misremembering it, I think it's about, it's called Nehru's hero Dilip Kumar or something

01:13:11.640 --> 01:13:12.640
[Guest]: like that.

01:13:12.640 --> 01:13:16.800
[Guest]: I mean, you know, it's, he believes that Dilip Kumar was a complete manifestation of the,

01:13:16.800 --> 01:13:19.760
[Guest]: you know, the Nehruvian sort of liberal image.

01:13:19.760 --> 01:13:25.200
[Guest]: Now, in this film, at the heart, and the film starts with a Gandhi quote, by the way, which

01:13:25.200 --> 01:13:28.160
[Guest]: in one of the newsletters where I have written, I have actually put that quote.

01:13:28.160 --> 01:13:30.880
[Guest]: I mean, I've taken a screen grab of that quote.

01:13:30.880 --> 01:13:37.840
[Guest]: Now, at the heart of this film is that there is a small village, there is a temple in the

01:13:37.840 --> 01:13:39.760
[Guest]: village, which is very famous.

01:13:39.760 --> 01:13:46.280
[Guest]: So and there are Tonga Walas and Dilip Kumar and, you know, his friend Ajit are both Tonga

01:13:46.280 --> 01:13:47.280
[Guest]: Walas.

01:13:47.280 --> 01:13:51.800
[Guest]: And, you know, people come from different places to visit this village because of the

01:13:51.800 --> 01:13:56.840
[Guest]: temple and the local economy largely is built on this, you know, this particular temple

01:13:56.840 --> 01:14:00.360
[Guest]: and the business around it, apart from the fact that there are farmers and things of

01:14:00.360 --> 01:14:01.360
[Guest]: that kind.

01:14:01.360 --> 01:14:07.440
[Guest]: Now, there is a guy in the village who's like the local money lender.

01:14:07.440 --> 01:14:11.400
[Guest]: And at the beginning, he goes off to Kashi or somewhere and, you know, leaving behind

01:14:11.400 --> 01:14:15.320
[Guest]: his sort of money lending business to his son, who's Jeevan.

01:14:15.320 --> 01:14:18.680
[Guest]: Now, Jeevan is shown actually as a Nehruvian elite.

01:14:18.680 --> 01:14:24.760
[Guest]: He's studied in the city, had college education, comes back to village.

01:14:24.760 --> 01:14:30.280
[Guest]: And he says that, listen, for this village to actually develop, we need a bus to come

01:14:30.280 --> 01:14:31.280
[Guest]: into the village.

01:14:31.280 --> 01:14:32.280
[Guest]: More business will come.

01:14:32.280 --> 01:14:37.960
[Guest]: Now, this is a complete Nehruvian idea that there is a society, you know, these are all

01:14:37.960 --> 01:14:42.280
[Guest]: Russian sort of an ideal of farmers under an oak tree doing their business.

01:14:42.280 --> 01:14:45.480
[Guest]: Here is a guy who comes and says, let's go by bus.

01:14:45.480 --> 01:14:49.040
[Guest]: Now, obviously, this is modernity versus traditionalism.

01:14:49.040 --> 01:14:53.200
[Guest]: So these Tonga people say, boss, you can't bring the bus because our business will be

01:14:53.200 --> 01:14:54.200
[Guest]: impacted.

01:14:54.200 --> 01:14:59.640
[Guest]: And, you know, I mean, had the axis of debate been only this, it was fine.

01:14:59.640 --> 01:15:03.760
[Guest]: But that Jeevan is shown to have other, you know, unfortunate sort of, you know, habits

01:15:03.760 --> 01:15:08.880
[Guest]: and vices for you to completely not believe in whatever he's saying.

01:15:08.880 --> 01:15:13.440
[Guest]: But then what, I mean, eventually there is a fight between Ajit and Dilip Kumar because

01:15:13.440 --> 01:15:16.960
[Guest]: of the girl and then Ajit goes into the enemy camp.

01:15:16.960 --> 01:15:26.040
[Guest]: And the climax of the film is that, you know, there is a race between the bus and the Tonga.

01:15:26.040 --> 01:15:29.440
[Guest]: So this is very similar to a Lagaan kind of a thing.

01:15:29.440 --> 01:15:35.520
[Guest]: And the point is, whoever wins the race, they will continue as the primary mode of transport.

01:15:35.520 --> 01:15:37.440
[Guest]: The other guy will have to go.

01:15:37.440 --> 01:15:41.680
[Guest]: And you know, there is a bridge that has to be built for the Tonga to actually beat the

01:15:41.680 --> 01:15:45.400
[Guest]: bus or to have any chance of beating the bus.

01:15:45.400 --> 01:15:48.040
[Guest]: And so what happens is then, you know, all kinds of things.

01:15:48.040 --> 01:15:52.120
[Guest]: I mean, there are great songs in the film, Ude Jab Jab Zulfe Teri, Opi Nair, and it

01:15:52.120 --> 01:15:56.800
[Guest]: will speak, I mean, you know, and, you know, that famous song, Saathi Haath Badhana Saathi

01:15:56.800 --> 01:15:59.840
[Guest]: Re, that's when they're building the, you know, the bridge.

01:15:59.840 --> 01:16:06.320
[Guest]: So and in the climax, the horse and the man, you know, beat the bus with, you know, all

01:16:06.320 --> 01:16:11.680
[Guest]: kinds of hijinks of Ajit, you know, actually putting his body on the line to keep the bridge

01:16:11.680 --> 01:16:17.480
[Guest]: from falling down and, you know, the horse going past it, so the society wins.

01:16:17.480 --> 01:16:21.560
[Guest]: And my point always is, this is actually an indictment, I mean, this is a complete indictment

01:16:21.560 --> 01:16:28.320
[Guest]: of the Nehruvian idea that I will build temples of modern India and I'll bring modernization

01:16:28.320 --> 01:16:29.320
[Guest]: into the village.

01:16:29.320 --> 01:16:30.320
[Guest]: This is Gandhi.

01:16:30.320 --> 01:16:32.000
[Guest]: Gandhi was saying, this is what will happen.

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:36.600
[Guest]: People within the village have to decide for themselves if they believe the Tonga can beat

01:16:36.600 --> 01:16:40.120
[Guest]: it, they will build their own bridge and let them beat that, beat the bus.

01:16:40.120 --> 01:16:42.160
[Guest]: When they are ready for the bus, they'll be ready for the bus.

01:16:42.160 --> 01:16:45.200
[Guest]: In fact, that's what he ends the film with.

01:16:45.200 --> 01:16:49.480
[Guest]: Actually the film has a dialogue of Dilip Kumar saying, we are not saying we are against

01:16:49.480 --> 01:16:53.400
[Guest]: modernity, but it has to be on our terms when we are ready for it.

01:16:53.400 --> 01:16:58.520
[Guest]: So it's a fascinating film, I mean, it captures the debate of that time.

01:16:58.520 --> 01:17:03.080
[Guest]: But I think it's the most misunderstood film, if you ask me.

01:17:03.080 --> 01:17:04.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:17:04.080 --> 01:17:05.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:17:05.080 --> 01:17:06.080
[Amit Varma]: No, totally.

01:17:06.080 --> 01:17:07.080
[Amit Varma]: I totally kind of get that.

01:17:07.080 --> 01:17:11.600
[Amit Varma]: And I get the sentiment about someone who says that it represents Nehruvian thinking

01:17:11.600 --> 01:17:16.160
[Amit Varma]: has either not understood Nehruvian thinking or hasn't seen the film.

01:17:16.160 --> 01:17:20.180
[Amit Varma]: Quick aside, by the way, since we, and tell me what you think about this, because I seem

01:17:20.180 --> 01:17:24.740
[Amit Varma]: to be in a little bit of a minority here as far as this particular quibble is concerned,

01:17:24.740 --> 01:17:29.480
[Amit Varma]: but when people talk about these three prongs of state, society and market, and I don't

01:17:29.480 --> 01:17:31.940
[Amit Varma]: think there are three, I think in a sense there are two.

01:17:31.940 --> 01:17:35.920
[Amit Varma]: Because the way I look at it is that on the one hand, you have voluntary action within

01:17:35.920 --> 01:17:40.480
[Amit Varma]: society and the market is one of the forms that it takes.

01:17:40.480 --> 01:17:44.880
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, you have the coercive hand of the state.

01:17:44.880 --> 01:17:48.860
[Amit Varma]: And yes, that can sometimes involve controlling a market as well.

01:17:48.860 --> 01:17:53.420
[Amit Varma]: But ideally the way you and I think of free markets, for example, it would all be voluntary

01:17:53.420 --> 01:17:57.380
[Amit Varma]: action and therefore a part of society itself.

01:17:57.380 --> 01:18:02.360
[Amit Varma]: And that, you know, therefore morally virtuous to begin with for that reason, that it is

01:18:02.360 --> 01:18:04.380
[Amit Varma]: voluntary and there is no coercion involved.

01:18:04.380 --> 01:18:09.620
[Amit Varma]: Like I like to keep saying that, you know, that two people should be free to engage with

01:18:09.620 --> 01:18:13.980
[Amit Varma]: each other in any way they deem fit, if they're not harming anyone else, whether it is in

01:18:13.980 --> 01:18:15.980
[Amit Varma]: the bedroom or the marketplace.

01:18:15.980 --> 01:18:17.860
[Amit Varma]: And because they're both positive sum games.

01:18:17.860 --> 01:18:23.460
[Amit Varma]: And the irony is that, you know, voluntary action in one domain is frowned upon by one

01:18:23.460 --> 01:18:28.420
[Amit Varma]: kind of ideology and by the other in the other domain, which is kind of, and in India, perhaps

01:18:28.420 --> 01:18:31.880
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, both domains is frowned upon.

01:18:31.880 --> 01:18:36.580
[Amit Varma]: So what's your sense of this, that this distinction of state market society, where to me a market

01:18:36.580 --> 01:18:40.820
[Amit Varma]: is just a mechanism for voluntary action and therefore is a subset of society?

01:18:40.820 --> 01:18:47.260
[Guest]: See Amit, one of the problems right now is that, I mean, we are just agreeing on everything.

01:18:47.260 --> 01:18:54.860
[Unknown]: It's like one of those Bhajjatiya movies, you know, everything is sweet and saccharine

01:18:54.860 --> 01:18:58.260
[Unknown]: and you know, nobody seems to have any difference of opinion.

01:18:58.260 --> 01:19:02.580
[Guest]: I just hope that the audience or the listeners are not sort of getting tired of this, but

01:19:02.580 --> 01:19:04.100
[Amit Varma]: I think many of them will disagree.

01:19:04.100 --> 01:19:05.900
[Amit Varma]: So at least there's new things to think about.

01:19:05.900 --> 01:19:06.900
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:19:06.900 --> 01:19:10.060
[Amit Varma]: So, and I didn't know if you'd agree with me because no one else seems to.

01:19:10.060 --> 01:19:11.060
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:19:11.060 --> 01:19:17.100
[Guest]: I'm hoping that they're finding things interesting, despite some fairly strong overlaps in terms

01:19:17.100 --> 01:19:19.820
[Guest]: of some of our world views.

01:19:19.820 --> 01:19:25.540
[Guest]: But you know, the reason why I would agree with you, apart from just intuitively, what

01:19:25.540 --> 01:19:29.900
[Guest]: you're saying is absolutely right, is also, let's think of people who sort of first wrote

01:19:29.900 --> 01:19:31.260
[Guest]: about many of these things, right?

01:19:31.260 --> 01:19:32.260
[Guest]: Like Adam Smith.

01:19:32.260 --> 01:19:38.060
[Guest]: Was Adam Smith writing about market when he was writing theory of social, of moral sentiments?

01:19:38.060 --> 01:19:39.060
[Guest]: No.

01:19:39.060 --> 01:19:40.060
[Guest]: He was writing about society.

01:19:40.060 --> 01:19:44.260
[Guest]: I mean, he was like saying, well, what is, you know, how should society be doing things?

01:19:44.260 --> 01:19:51.220
[Guest]: And, you know, we have gleaned the idea of an invisible hand for the market from it is

01:19:51.220 --> 01:19:53.860
[Guest]: our sort of, you know, what we are extracting out of it.

01:19:53.860 --> 01:19:56.980
[Guest]: And we are making this artificial sort of, you know, distinction there.

01:19:56.980 --> 01:20:05.100
[Guest]: But a lot of these folks, whether it is Adam Smith or, you know, whether it is Hayek or

01:20:05.100 --> 01:20:10.660
[Guest]: even Marx, these guys were not writing economics text or market based text.

01:20:10.660 --> 01:20:14.620
[Guest]: They were just writing, you know, society, class, struggle, you know, power and, you

01:20:14.620 --> 01:20:17.220
[Guest]: know, things of that kind of what is moral about this.

01:20:17.220 --> 01:20:23.940
[Guest]: So I would agree with you that that this distinction is a bit artificial at the heart of it, you

01:20:23.940 --> 01:20:24.940
[Guest]: know.

01:20:24.940 --> 01:20:29.660
[Guest]: And when you go back into some of the prototypes for some of these things, they are all, you

01:20:29.660 --> 01:20:34.580
[Guest]: know, fairly, they just look at society and they just view society and the interactions

01:20:34.580 --> 01:20:35.740
[Guest]: that people are doing.

01:20:35.740 --> 01:20:41.860
[Guest]: And, you know, economics or market is one sort of branch or whatever, one element of

01:20:41.860 --> 01:20:42.860
[Amit Varma]: that.

01:20:42.860 --> 01:20:43.860
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

01:20:43.860 --> 01:20:46.100
[Amit Varma]: And on that note of agreement, let's take a quick commercial break.

01:20:46.100 --> 01:20:49.940
[Amit Varma]: Hopefully we'll find things to disagree about after this is over.

01:20:49.940 --> 01:20:56.460
[Amit Varma]: So see you on the other side of a break.

01:20:56.460 --> 01:20:59.380
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer but never quite gotten down to it?

01:20:59.380 --> 01:21:00.860
[Amit Varma]: Well, I'd love to help you.

01:21:00.860 --> 01:21:05.140
[Amit Varma]: One of the great joys of this lockdown for me was discovering how much I enjoy teaching

01:21:05.140 --> 01:21:07.060
[Amit Varma]: what I've learned over the years.

01:21:07.060 --> 01:21:11.800
[Amit Varma]: And my online course, The Art of Clear Writing, is now open for registration.

01:21:11.800 --> 01:21:17.180
[Amit Varma]: In this course, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know about

01:21:17.180 --> 01:21:18.980
[Amit Varma]: the craft and practice of clear writing.

01:21:18.980 --> 01:21:22.320
[Amit Varma]: There are many exercises, much interaction.

01:21:22.320 --> 01:21:26.980
[Amit Varma]: And over the 10 months that I have taught this course, a lively writing community has

01:21:26.980 --> 01:21:28.020
[Amit Varma]: formed itself.

01:21:28.020 --> 01:21:32.900
[Amit Varma]: The course costs rupees 10,000 plus GST, or about $150.

01:21:32.900 --> 01:21:36.100
[Amit Varma]: And the March classes begin on March 6.

01:21:36.100 --> 01:21:41.340
[Amit Varma]: So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiancut.com slash clear writing.

01:21:41.340 --> 01:21:44.780
[Amit Varma]: That's indiancut.com slash clear writing.

01:21:44.780 --> 01:21:49.540
[Amit Varma]: Being a good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard

01:21:49.540 --> 01:21:53.260
[Amit Varma]: and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

01:21:53.260 --> 01:21:58.660
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

01:21:58.660 --> 01:21:59.980
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

01:21:59.980 --> 01:22:04.580
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Raghu Sanjay Lal Jaitley, co-author of the brilliant newsletter, Anticipating

01:22:04.580 --> 01:22:06.500
[Amit Varma]: the Unintended.

01:22:06.500 --> 01:22:12.300
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not sure if you dear listeners anticipated the unintended, which is that I will now start

01:22:12.300 --> 01:22:18.140
[Amit Varma]: the second half off by disagreeing with something that Raghu said before the break, though in

01:22:18.140 --> 01:22:23.300
[Amit Varma]: a gentle way, where he referred to Dilip Kumar being called Nehru's hero.

01:22:23.300 --> 01:22:27.140
[Amit Varma]: And Raghu's opinion was that no, Dilip Kumar was not Nehru's hero, but okay, maybe not

01:22:27.140 --> 01:22:28.500
[Amit Varma]: in this film.

01:22:28.500 --> 01:22:33.660
[Amit Varma]: But in general, you have written about Dilip Kumar, you know, elsewhere and spoken about

01:22:33.660 --> 01:22:39.660
[Amit Varma]: how he almost embodied the concept of farz, you know, the classic example being the famous

01:22:39.660 --> 01:22:44.460
[Amit Varma]: early 80s film Shakti, where he is the honest police officer who ends up shooting his own

01:22:44.460 --> 01:22:48.780
[Amit Varma]: son played by Amitabh Bachchan, because he is doing his duty.

01:22:48.780 --> 01:22:54.740
[Amit Varma]: And this in a sense, would qualify him to be Nehru's hero for the specific reason that

01:22:54.740 --> 01:22:58.780
[Amit Varma]: Nehru's conception of the state and the conception of some of the other founders who believed

01:22:58.780 --> 01:23:03.500
[Amit Varma]: in the status vision was, listen, it's true, we are giving the state a lot of power, but

01:23:03.500 --> 01:23:07.820
[Amit Varma]: it will be exercised by good people who will do the right thing in general.

01:23:07.820 --> 01:23:11.940
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you and I know that, listen, power always corrupts and, you know, that's

01:23:11.940 --> 01:23:14.260
[Amit Varma]: never quite going to be the case.

01:23:14.260 --> 01:23:21.580
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about sort of this concept of farz and Dilip Kumar and, you know,

01:23:21.580 --> 01:23:27.100
[Amit Varma]: where you went on with this narrative and you wrote about it in your newsletter.

01:23:27.100 --> 01:23:33.260
[Guest]: So this is a point that I was sort of wondering about when I was writing that newsletter,

01:23:33.260 --> 01:23:38.420
[Guest]: the thing that sort of triggered that was, you know, I just started finding and this

01:23:38.420 --> 01:23:45.220
[Guest]: has happened over the last four or five years, that people that we often gave a lot of, you

01:23:45.220 --> 01:23:51.780
[Guest]: know, we had a lot of admiration for in society, the judges or the, you know, the IAS officers

01:23:51.780 --> 01:24:00.620
[Guest]: and things of that kind, I started noticing that a strange sort of illiberal streak was,

01:24:00.620 --> 01:24:06.100
[Guest]: you know, starting to become prominent in many of their, you know, public statements,

01:24:06.100 --> 01:24:08.140
[Guest]: judgments and things of that kind.

01:24:08.140 --> 01:24:11.020
[Guest]: And I was wondering what is the reason for this?

01:24:11.020 --> 01:24:16.700
[Guest]: And, you know, through some kind of convoluted logic, I reached the conclusion that there

01:24:16.700 --> 01:24:22.340
[Guest]: was a time when firstly, the people who came into many of these positions, whether you

01:24:22.340 --> 01:24:27.860
[Guest]: like it or not, were possibly of a certain state of society, which had a very different

01:24:27.860 --> 01:24:29.860
[Guest]: kind of education, etc. for them.

01:24:29.860 --> 01:24:34.540
[Guest]: I mean, they were exposed to very different things than the ordinary Indian.

01:24:34.540 --> 01:24:39.180
[Guest]: Now that was not necessarily a great thing because people have to come from the real

01:24:39.180 --> 01:24:42.100
[Guest]: India in order to solve the problems of real India.

01:24:42.100 --> 01:24:45.900
[Guest]: But for a moment, let's assume that these are people who came from these places and,

01:24:45.900 --> 01:24:50.820
[Guest]: you know, many times they also appreciated real India.

01:24:50.820 --> 01:24:58.620
[Guest]: And then what happened was the state, through its various forms and machinery and everything,

01:24:58.620 --> 01:25:07.500
[Guest]: consistently gave them this incentive to do the thing that the state was sort of, you

01:25:07.500 --> 01:25:12.780
[Guest]: know, using the constitution for in terms of, you know, effecting a social revolution.

01:25:12.780 --> 01:25:15.420
[Guest]: And you saw that all around.

01:25:15.420 --> 01:25:17.440
[Guest]: So you would find a very pious man.

01:25:17.440 --> 01:25:24.340
[Guest]: And I know many sort of pious IAS officers, judges, extremely pious, extremely religious,

01:25:24.340 --> 01:25:29.740
[Guest]: but then they would give judgments, you know, which would sometimes make you question, you

01:25:29.740 --> 01:25:34.980
[Guest]: know, I mean, they would really give judgments where their personal sort of, you know, convictions

01:25:34.980 --> 01:25:39.900
[Guest]: never got in the way of making those judgments of, you know, giving statements in the press

01:25:39.900 --> 01:25:41.900
[Guest]: and things of that kind.

01:25:41.900 --> 01:25:47.900
[Guest]: And this always fascinated me and, you know, this movie Shakti where Dilip Kumar was the

01:25:47.900 --> 01:25:53.340
[Guest]: father was a good sort of an example of that, where the guy, you know, does what is to be

01:25:53.340 --> 01:25:54.660
[Guest]: done.

01:25:54.660 --> 01:25:59.740
[Guest]: Some of it is first, some of it is also an overlay of the thing that the state has, you

01:25:59.740 --> 01:26:02.660
[Guest]: know, completely trained this person.

01:26:02.660 --> 01:26:06.620
[Guest]: You just have to follow what we have told you, because that's the right thing in the

01:26:06.620 --> 01:26:09.420
[Guest]: greater sort of interest of the society.

01:26:09.420 --> 01:26:14.780
[Guest]: And I then started, you know, noticing that what's happening of late, and again, this

01:26:14.780 --> 01:26:19.060
[Guest]: is nothing to do with the specific government, but it's the point that we made earlier, you

01:26:19.060 --> 01:26:24.660
[Guest]: know, that other sort of, you know, experiment, if you might call so, of trying to change

01:26:24.660 --> 01:26:30.140
[Guest]: the society from top down is fraying completely at the edges.

01:26:30.140 --> 01:26:35.060
[Guest]: And therefore, you know, the state has also figured this out, and they are also pandering

01:26:35.060 --> 01:26:39.300
[Guest]: to that sort of, you know, that kind of instinct within the society.

01:26:39.300 --> 01:26:46.180
[Guest]: And now all of these are in sync, you know, the state also is okay with people, you know,

01:26:46.180 --> 01:26:50.940
[Guest]: giving when to their original or whatever their real thoughts are.

01:26:50.940 --> 01:26:55.180
[Guest]: Some of those thoughts we might believe are illiberal, are different from what the constitution

01:26:55.180 --> 01:27:00.740
[Guest]: or what we thought some of these positions have to possibly take in terms of stand.

01:27:00.740 --> 01:27:04.860
[Guest]: And that's, you know, so the incentive now has changed, that's flipped.

01:27:04.860 --> 01:27:08.780
[Guest]: And you know, that if it has flipped, then we will get to see more of this kind, you

01:27:08.780 --> 01:27:13.900
[Guest]: will get to see more of the kind of judgments where somebody will say that, you know, if

01:27:13.900 --> 01:27:18.300
[Guest]: you are molesting someone and the woman still has their clothes on, that's not molestation.

01:27:18.300 --> 01:27:24.220
[Guest]: This was a judgment of a couple of months back, or that other one where women's feeble

01:27:24.220 --> 01:27:29.180
[Guest]: no cannot be, you know, cannot be construed as no.

01:27:29.180 --> 01:27:35.460
[Guest]: So I think somewhere, that's really what sort of animated my thought at that point in time.

01:27:35.460 --> 01:27:40.900
[Guest]: And you know, then Shakti was a good vehicle to use as an example of what used to happen

01:27:40.900 --> 01:27:43.660
[Guest]: in the past and contrasted with where we are today.

01:27:43.660 --> 01:27:44.660
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:27:44.660 --> 01:27:48.380
[Amit Varma]: And I'll take a quick aside because you mentioned the feeble no judgment and that gets my blood

01:27:48.380 --> 01:27:52.340
[Amit Varma]: boiling and that was obviously in the case of Mahmood Faruqi, who was first convicted

01:27:52.340 --> 01:27:56.300
[Amit Varma]: of rape and then he was acquitted by a higher court, which basically said he had done what

01:27:56.300 --> 01:28:01.060
[Amit Varma]: he had done and the woman had said no, but it said a feeble no can sometimes mean a yes.

01:28:01.060 --> 01:28:03.060
[Amit Varma]: And it acquitted him on this basis.

01:28:03.060 --> 01:28:07.460
[Amit Varma]: And it's incredible how so many hypocritical Delhi liberals, so to say, have immediately

01:28:07.460 --> 01:28:13.500
[Amit Varma]: rehabilitated him, like they, you know, partially did in the case of Tarun Tejpal and all of

01:28:13.500 --> 01:28:17.900
[Amit Varma]: that, where, you know, on the day that we are recording, in fact, the 23rd, he was scheduled

01:28:17.900 --> 01:28:20.460
[Amit Varma]: to have performed today at the Jaipur Lit Fest.

01:28:20.460 --> 01:28:25.820
[Amit Varma]: And I just want to say in no unequivocal terms that the organizers of the Jaipur Lit Fest

01:28:25.820 --> 01:28:29.140
[Amit Varma]: who made this decision, you know, should be ashamed of themselves.

01:28:29.140 --> 01:28:31.500
[Amit Varma]: It's a slap on the face of all women.

01:28:31.500 --> 01:28:35.860
[Amit Varma]: It's a message to all the women at the Jaipur Lit Fest that your no doesn't mean a no.

01:28:35.860 --> 01:28:36.860
[Amit Varma]: It's just disgraceful.

01:28:36.860 --> 01:28:41.820
[Amit Varma]: But I'm sorry, this sort of a side of anger apart, because it really gets me going.

01:28:41.820 --> 01:28:45.940
[Amit Varma]: And I had an episode also on, you know, how the laws are so weighted against women in

01:28:45.940 --> 01:28:46.940
[Amit Varma]: India.

01:28:46.940 --> 01:28:47.940
[Amit Varma]: I'll link that from the show notes.

01:28:47.940 --> 01:28:50.660
[Amit Varma]: I think it was with Hamsini Hariharan was one of the guests.

01:28:50.660 --> 01:28:55.020
[Amit Varma]: But you know, the reason I asked you about, to get back to our topic, before I get carried

01:28:55.020 --> 01:29:00.100
[Amit Varma]: away, the reason I asked you about Dilip Kumar and Farzin Shakti and that particular edition

01:29:00.100 --> 01:29:04.440
[Amit Varma]: of the newsletter, which was edition number 30, which I'll link, is that I think it makes

01:29:04.440 --> 01:29:09.340
[Amit Varma]: an incredibly profound point, which, you know, made me think about this whole issue in a

01:29:09.340 --> 01:29:10.340
[Amit Varma]: different way.

01:29:10.340 --> 01:29:12.760
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to quote you a little bit at length, because I think it'll be of great

01:29:12.760 --> 01:29:18.540
[Amit Varma]: interest to my listeners, where you talk about how one quote, the foundational premise of

01:29:18.540 --> 01:29:23.820
[Amit Varma]: modern India is that the state is ontologically prior to the society, stop quote.

01:29:23.820 --> 01:29:29.020
[Amit Varma]: And then you write, quote, this created an unstable yet desirable equilibrium in India.

01:29:29.020 --> 01:29:33.260
[Amit Varma]: The state was founded on values of equality, redistribution, secularism, fairness and social

01:29:33.260 --> 01:29:34.260
[Amit Varma]: welfare.

01:29:34.260 --> 01:29:39.500
[Amit Varma]: The society from where agents were drawn hadn't fully accepted and internalize these values.

01:29:39.500 --> 01:29:43.680
[Amit Varma]: So you had free market economists drafting socialist policies, or an enlightened district

01:29:43.680 --> 01:29:47.940
[Amit Varma]: magistrate who preach social equality at work, but practice discrimination at home, stop

01:29:47.940 --> 01:29:48.940
[Amit Varma]: quote.

01:29:48.940 --> 01:29:52.220
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, they are following their incentives, because there is nothing else to do.

01:29:52.220 --> 01:29:54.860
[Amit Varma]: The state is the Maibab, as it were.

01:29:54.860 --> 01:29:59.700
[Amit Varma]: Now you talk about how liberalization changed this and what happened when liberalization

01:29:59.700 --> 01:30:03.580
[Amit Varma]: hit, where you write, quote, the free market incentives aren't the same as that of the

01:30:03.580 --> 01:30:04.580
[Amit Varma]: state.

01:30:04.580 --> 01:30:06.820
[Amit Varma]: It rewards efficiency and value creation.

01:30:06.820 --> 01:30:10.580
[Amit Varma]: For the middle class now, there was no need to live the dichotomous life their parents

01:30:10.580 --> 01:30:14.940
[Amit Varma]: led of having a professional code that was different from the personal code.

01:30:14.940 --> 01:30:18.500
[Amit Varma]: Liberals are often surprised how well educated professionals working for MNCs turn out to

01:30:18.500 --> 01:30:19.500
[Amit Varma]: be bigots.

01:30:19.500 --> 01:30:20.500
[Amit Varma]: The answer is simple.

01:30:20.500 --> 01:30:23.580
[Amit Varma]: The state couldn't change the society as it had expected.

01:30:23.580 --> 01:30:29.300
[Amit Varma]: And once the incentives stop mattering to the citizens, the mask dropped, stop quote.

01:30:29.300 --> 01:30:33.160
[Amit Varma]: And you later go on to talk about how the democratic mandate has now changed.

01:30:33.160 --> 01:30:37.180
[Amit Varma]: And you go on to write, quote, you can argue the democratic mandate now is for the idea

01:30:37.180 --> 01:30:43.740
[Amit Varma]: that society is ontologically prior to the state, stop quote, which is all of which is

01:30:43.740 --> 01:30:45.460
[Amit Varma]: kind of fascinating to me.

01:30:45.460 --> 01:30:49.140
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, it doesn't mean that, you know, I think both of us would agree liberalization

01:30:49.140 --> 01:30:52.580
[Amit Varma]: was largely, you know, drastically for the better.

01:30:52.580 --> 01:30:59.460
[Amit Varma]: But with the state not being the only source of sort of obedience and adherence, and, you

01:30:59.460 --> 01:31:03.260
[Amit Varma]: know, people were empowered in many different ways, which is always a good thing.

01:31:03.260 --> 01:31:08.260
[Amit Varma]: But one of those ways was to express their bigotry and to rail against values which they

01:31:08.260 --> 01:31:13.380
[Amit Varma]: might have felt were imposed upon them in sort of the national debate.

01:31:13.380 --> 01:31:21.860
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of go back to more sort of, I'm very curious as to what lenses you apply

01:31:21.860 --> 01:31:26.220
[Amit Varma]: to look at all of this in a historical sense that fine, I can understand that in an economic

01:31:26.220 --> 01:31:27.220
[Amit Varma]: sense, fine.

01:31:27.220 --> 01:31:31.340
[Amit Varma]: All the thinking you've done out of it, that forms a lens in the political philosophy sense

01:31:31.340 --> 01:31:32.500
[Amit Varma]: that happens.

01:31:32.500 --> 01:31:39.060
[Amit Varma]: But in a historical sense, when you look at phenomena like this happening, you know, this

01:31:39.060 --> 01:31:43.860
[Amit Varma]: sort of tussle between the state and the society going from one to the other, you know, can

01:31:43.860 --> 01:31:49.060
[Amit Varma]: you look because I am really only familiar of this tussle in intimate terms in an Indian

01:31:49.060 --> 01:31:50.060
[Amit Varma]: context.

01:31:50.060 --> 01:31:55.220
[Amit Varma]: But looking outside, are there lessons that we can take from elsewhere in the world?

01:31:55.220 --> 01:32:00.620
[Amit Varma]: And is it something that is, you know, bound to go in particular directions?

01:32:00.620 --> 01:32:02.380
[Amit Varma]: What are your thoughts on this?

01:32:02.380 --> 01:32:10.300
[Guest]: So this will be some really random ramble, I mean, because this, again, the point of

01:32:10.300 --> 01:32:15.780
[Guest]: trying to frame this while speaking sometimes is a bit difficult, but let me take a shot

01:32:15.780 --> 01:32:16.780
[Guest]: at it.

01:32:16.780 --> 01:32:20.540
[Guest]: I think firstly, see this ontologically prior, whether it's state or the society, I think

01:32:20.540 --> 01:32:25.900
[Guest]: it's a deep sort of a point, not that I'm making, people have made before it.

01:32:25.900 --> 01:32:30.620
[Guest]: And I think there is a view, which is that, listen, the state cannot be ontologically

01:32:30.620 --> 01:32:31.620
[Guest]: prior to society.

01:32:31.620 --> 01:32:37.980
[Guest]: The society is always there, but what are you trying to do by putting that ontologically

01:32:37.980 --> 01:32:39.460
[Guest]: prior to it, right?

01:32:39.460 --> 01:32:43.460
[Guest]: And in some sense, you know, Hobbes and others were almost like, you know, it's like a big

01:32:43.460 --> 01:32:44.460
[Guest]: bang.

01:32:44.460 --> 01:32:47.460
[Guest]: I mean, the society comes together, there is a covenant, and then, you know, they start

01:32:47.460 --> 01:32:52.900
[Guest]: forming the sovereign and you know, whatever, but since you asked the historical context,

01:32:52.900 --> 01:33:02.660
[Guest]: I think in India, even till 1947, it was very clear that the state had very limited things

01:33:02.660 --> 01:33:04.500
[Guest]: to do with society.

01:33:04.500 --> 01:33:11.220
[Guest]: I mean, the English did something about it, largely because, you know, their enlightenment

01:33:11.220 --> 01:33:15.580
[Guest]: values were so strong that they just could not believe that they will lord over a people

01:33:15.580 --> 01:33:18.820
[Guest]: and not bring that enlightenment value to them.

01:33:18.820 --> 01:33:26.500
[Guest]: But even then, the idea that what you did at your home, how you conducted your social

01:33:26.500 --> 01:33:31.340
[Guest]: life, there was very limited sort of interference from the state.

01:33:31.340 --> 01:33:38.660
[Guest]: And if you went just prior to the colonialism, the colonial era, then the state had nothing

01:33:38.660 --> 01:33:42.540
[Guest]: to do with how you led your life, right?

01:33:42.540 --> 01:33:47.660
[Guest]: And this is actually how India has sort of, you know, lived for a long period of time.

01:33:47.660 --> 01:33:51.980
[Guest]: That's why 1947 was a huge aberration.

01:33:51.980 --> 01:33:58.780
[Guest]: So you know, even in Arthashastra and you know, Kautilya and Chanakya, when they were

01:33:58.780 --> 01:34:06.020
[Guest]: writing, you never found that they were writing about anything where the king's duty extended

01:34:06.020 --> 01:34:11.140
[Guest]: to changing the lives of the subjects in how they lead their lives.

01:34:11.140 --> 01:34:17.620
[Guest]: And you know, if you have sort of gone through some, I mean, our written history is often

01:34:17.620 --> 01:34:19.500
[Guest]: quite poor.

01:34:19.500 --> 01:34:24.820
[Guest]: But if you just read a little bit of say, you know, Bhan Bhatta's Harsh Charita, and

01:34:24.820 --> 01:34:28.140
[Guest]: you know, this Murthy classic library has actually helped a lot.

01:34:28.140 --> 01:34:34.580
[Guest]: And I would recommend people to read a few somewhat dense prose, I mean, you would throw

01:34:34.580 --> 01:34:41.700
[Guest]: the book out as part of your writing course as to what is this, even the translations

01:34:41.700 --> 01:34:43.420
[Guest]: are so dense.

01:34:43.420 --> 01:34:49.540
[Guest]: But one thing that you would notice there is the absolute divorce of the state from

01:34:49.540 --> 01:34:50.540
[Guest]: the society.

01:34:50.540 --> 01:34:54.860
[Guest]: And the only thing they were interested in was actually some tax collection and going

01:34:54.860 --> 01:35:00.860
[Guest]: to war and things of that kind and some very broad civil laws, criminal laws, sorry, around,

01:35:00.860 --> 01:35:04.500
[Unknown]: you know, theft and robbery and, you know, all of that.

01:35:04.500 --> 01:35:09.660
[Guest]: And, but if you take and that's true of India, now, it's this is true of most feudal societies

01:35:09.660 --> 01:35:14.940
[Guest]: and I can take England and we can even take the United States.

01:35:14.940 --> 01:35:18.020
[Guest]: And maybe let's take the United States for a moment.

01:35:18.020 --> 01:35:23.700
[Guest]: The United States example, the American example was that, you know, there were all these folks

01:35:23.700 --> 01:35:29.260
[Guest]: who had come who, you know, one leg was still in the England and they would often go back

01:35:29.260 --> 01:35:33.460
[Guest]: and forth, like Washington and all of them.

01:35:33.460 --> 01:35:41.420
[Guest]: Where the, you know, the idea that what we are doing as a society was completely driven

01:35:41.420 --> 01:35:44.140
[Guest]: by the religion.

01:35:44.140 --> 01:35:49.100
[Guest]: The idea that we have to pay taxes was an idea that was an assault on their individual

01:35:49.100 --> 01:35:51.940
[Guest]: liberty from a Lockean perspective.

01:35:51.940 --> 01:35:54.860
[Guest]: And they fought against it and then they created a state.

01:35:54.860 --> 01:36:02.500
[Guest]: Now, when they created that state, then they asked the questions, what should be the, I

01:36:02.500 --> 01:36:05.140
[Guest]: mean, you know, how should we create the state?

01:36:05.140 --> 01:36:07.540
[Guest]: What should be the ways we should think about it?

01:36:07.540 --> 01:36:13.180
[Guest]: The entire constitution is written, not from a perspective of what we should do for the

01:36:13.180 --> 01:36:20.020
[Guest]: society, but just how we should make sure that we avoid the trauma that we went through,

01:36:20.020 --> 01:36:25.020
[Guest]: where the state was starting to do things that are, you know, completely unjustified.

01:36:25.020 --> 01:36:32.340
[Guest]: Now, over a period of time, that constitutional document has been interpreted for all kinds

01:36:32.340 --> 01:36:39.300
[Guest]: of social, you know, issues, but that was not the original purpose of that particular

01:36:39.300 --> 01:36:40.300
[Guest]: document.

01:36:40.300 --> 01:36:44.980
[Guest]: England doesn't have a written constitution, but broadly it's the same sort of a construct.

01:36:44.980 --> 01:36:46.620
[Guest]: They didn't write it.

01:36:46.620 --> 01:36:51.340
[Guest]: The idea of, you know, creating some kind of a parliament and some kind of a, you know,

01:36:51.340 --> 01:36:56.260
[Guest]: constitution, which is not written, but understood is just the idea of making sure that the king

01:36:56.260 --> 01:37:00.460
[Guest]: is under the parliament and the parliament is sovereign and takes decisions on many of

01:37:00.460 --> 01:37:02.780
[Guest]: these things, but not anything about society.

01:37:02.780 --> 01:37:07.820
[Guest]: Now over a period of time, the things, you know, you, you would ask whether gay rights

01:37:07.820 --> 01:37:10.500
[Guest]: are right or not, and then you would go back to constitution.

01:37:10.500 --> 01:37:13.860
[Guest]: And then you would say that, listen, since they're saying everybody's equal or something

01:37:13.860 --> 01:37:19.180
[Guest]: of that kind, therefore, and pursuit of liberty and life and happiness is right.

01:37:19.180 --> 01:37:22.620
[Guest]: And therefore these guys also must be given the same thing.

01:37:22.620 --> 01:37:28.540
[Guest]: But that's the reason for some of the schisms in those society, because the one section

01:37:28.540 --> 01:37:33.340
[Guest]: of the society feels this is not the reason, this is not how the constitution was originally

01:37:33.340 --> 01:37:34.340
[Guest]: written.

01:37:34.340 --> 01:37:38.380
[Guest]: And, you know, this whole business of trying to back the Supreme court in the U S with

01:37:38.380 --> 01:37:39.380
[Guest]: your people.

01:37:39.380 --> 01:37:44.900
[Guest]: I mean, a lot of conservatives use this idea called originalism or whatever the idea that

01:37:44.900 --> 01:37:49.340
[Guest]: what is the original purpose of a point of what, how it was written.

01:37:49.340 --> 01:37:53.740
[Guest]: And they use it to actually say that it was not written for social points, right?

01:37:53.740 --> 01:37:56.380
[Guest]: It was written for a very different sort of a reason.

01:37:56.380 --> 01:38:00.340
[Guest]: You can't be using that to sort of start sorting out some of the current social points.

01:38:00.340 --> 01:38:02.660
[Guest]: Let society solve that in that sense.

01:38:02.660 --> 01:38:11.780
[Guest]: So I think large democracies have used, you know, state as a, as a very sort of a, you

01:38:11.780 --> 01:38:17.660
[Guest]: know, limited instrument to make sure that we run in a certain way, rather than actually

01:38:17.660 --> 01:38:20.660
[Guest]: go out and change society on the back of it.

01:38:20.660 --> 01:38:22.140
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

01:38:22.140 --> 01:38:26.260
[Amit Varma]: Another sort of question that then comes up looking at what is happening now, where if

01:38:26.260 --> 01:38:30.340
[Amit Varma]: you are looking at the world through, say the sort of classical liberal perspective

01:38:30.340 --> 01:38:36.500
[Amit Varma]: that I'm guessing we share, which makes us inevitably agree on so many things.

01:38:36.500 --> 01:38:40.180
[Amit Varma]: It would seem that in some ways we are going backwards, like, you know, Martin Luther King,

01:38:40.180 --> 01:38:44.220
[Amit Varma]: of course, had said that the arc of history always bends in, you know, a particular good

01:38:44.220 --> 01:38:45.220
[Amit Varma]: direction.

01:38:45.220 --> 01:38:49.900
[Amit Varma]: But, and you know, when Fukuyama spoke about the end of history, it was almost as if fine,

01:38:49.900 --> 01:38:54.100
[Amit Varma]: you know, liberal values have won, democracies have won, you know, there's a certain set

01:38:54.100 --> 01:38:59.380
[Amit Varma]: of values which is now accepted and all of those, all the strife and conflict is behind

01:38:59.380 --> 01:39:00.380
[Amit Varma]: us.

01:39:00.380 --> 01:39:04.020
[Amit Varma]: And yet you've written recently about, you know, why that end of history never came.

01:39:04.020 --> 01:39:10.020
[Amit Varma]: This was in, you know, edition 99, where you referred to a book that I just picked up,

01:39:10.020 --> 01:39:11.700
[Amit Varma]: but I haven't read yet.

01:39:11.700 --> 01:39:15.860
[Amit Varma]: But you were raving about it called The Light That Failed by Ivan Krastev and Stephen Holmes.

01:39:15.860 --> 01:39:19.340
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about, you know, what really happened.

01:39:19.340 --> 01:39:21.740
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, Fukuyama is misinterpreted.

01:39:21.740 --> 01:39:25.800
[Amit Varma]: He didn't, it wasn't like, you know, he was saying that we won, it's over.

01:39:25.800 --> 01:39:31.620
[Amit Varma]: It wasn't that kind of complacent, whatever his point was much subtler than that.

01:39:31.620 --> 01:39:38.380
[Amit Varma]: But, but clearly, even there, you know, there were issues and across the world, we see authoritarianism

01:39:38.380 --> 01:39:42.700
[Amit Varma]: on the rise, statism on the rise, instead of getting more globalized, the world is getting

01:39:42.700 --> 01:39:47.140
[Amit Varma]: more insular in different ways at the level of how states behave with each other.

01:39:47.140 --> 01:39:54.380
[Amit Varma]: So give me a sense of what has happened, what's going wrong, and why are we to believe that

01:39:54.380 --> 01:40:01.340
[Amit Varma]: this is that, you know, that what King said about the arc of history was just not true.

01:40:01.340 --> 01:40:07.340
[Guest]: So I think, I mean, Amit, you make a very important point.

01:40:07.340 --> 01:40:12.380
[Guest]: Very few people get the idea, get the, you know, the fact that Fukuyama didn't mean end

01:40:12.380 --> 01:40:18.220
[Guest]: of history, the way people interpret it, what the poor fellow was trying to say, and he

01:40:18.220 --> 01:40:23.260
[Guest]: has spent the rest of his life defending or whatever, clarifying what he was saying was

01:40:23.260 --> 01:40:31.780
[Guest]: that the idea that a liberal democratic order is the final sort of frontier is established.

01:40:31.780 --> 01:40:37.580
[Guest]: Now, you might want, some people will go up to there, some people will regress.

01:40:37.580 --> 01:40:43.060
[Guest]: He had no sort of, you know, illusions about that everybody will eventually reach there

01:40:43.060 --> 01:40:44.540
[Guest]: or we have already reached there.

01:40:44.540 --> 01:40:47.620
[Guest]: His point is, it is now established.

01:40:47.620 --> 01:40:51.580
[Guest]: Then there was a contestation between this order versus the, you know, whatever the communist

01:40:51.580 --> 01:40:55.500
[Guest]: totalitarian, whatever you might call it, that this order is the final one, not the

01:40:55.500 --> 01:40:56.500
[Guest]: other one.

01:40:56.500 --> 01:41:00.660
[Guest]: Now you might want to, you know, on that scale, you might want to go from zero to 10 and back

01:41:00.660 --> 01:41:01.660
[Guest]: again to zero.

01:41:01.660 --> 01:41:03.380
[Guest]: It's your choice.

01:41:03.380 --> 01:41:09.660
[Guest]: Now what is the reason for what happened, at least according to this book and, you know,

01:41:09.660 --> 01:41:16.500
[Guest]: some of it sort of resonated with some of the earlier editions as well that I've written.

01:41:16.500 --> 01:41:21.740
[Guest]: And this is a bit of a, you know, a subject that sort of has been in my mind and there

01:41:21.740 --> 01:41:26.060
[Guest]: are multiple different ways I've come to this point in various editions.

01:41:26.060 --> 01:41:31.100
[Guest]: I think one thing that these guys make a very important point is that they call it cheap

01:41:31.100 --> 01:41:32.100
[Guest]: imitation.

01:41:32.100 --> 01:41:33.420
[Guest]: Right.

01:41:33.420 --> 01:41:42.260
[Guest]: And that is to say that you came to this, you know, you concluded that liberal democratic

01:41:42.260 --> 01:41:43.540
[Guest]: order is the final one.

01:41:43.540 --> 01:41:48.540
[Guest]: And then to many other places, and especially they take Eastern and Central European countries

01:41:48.540 --> 01:41:54.180
[Guest]: that came out of the Soviet bloc and then adopted some of these forms of government.

01:41:54.180 --> 01:42:00.500
[Guest]: There, there was no real sort of grassroots, you know, sort of understanding of these things

01:42:00.500 --> 01:42:05.940
[Guest]: and, you know, grassroots, you know, sort of intellectual tradition, which actually

01:42:05.940 --> 01:42:07.660
[Guest]: built this up.

01:42:07.660 --> 01:42:10.580
[Guest]: It was like something was transplanted into these countries.

01:42:10.580 --> 01:42:13.020
[Guest]: And I would say not very different from what happened in India.

01:42:13.020 --> 01:42:18.140
[Guest]: I mean, maybe we just went through a deeper struggle, a longer struggle, which allowed

01:42:18.140 --> 01:42:22.540
[Guest]: us to sort of have way more legitimacy for people who were transplanting these ideas

01:42:22.540 --> 01:42:24.100
[Guest]: into India.

01:42:24.100 --> 01:42:28.220
[Guest]: But there it was like some World Bank guy would come and sit in a conference room.

01:42:28.220 --> 01:42:33.060
[Guest]: Two guys would come from some Brookings Institute, and then they would start writing the constitution

01:42:33.060 --> 01:42:36.660
[Guest]: along with a couple of people who studied in Cambridge.

01:42:36.660 --> 01:42:40.780
[Guest]: And a lot of these guys, Victor Oban and all, are all educated in, you know, Oxford or Cambridge,

01:42:40.780 --> 01:42:41.780
[Guest]: one of those places.

01:42:41.780 --> 01:42:42.780
[Guest]: Right.

01:42:42.780 --> 01:42:47.980
[Guest]: So, this cheap imitation is one part of the problem that you just copied some, and some

01:42:47.980 --> 01:42:52.500
[Guest]: of, sometimes the entire constitution is largely sort of, you know, copied and pasted into

01:42:52.500 --> 01:42:59.260
[Guest]: this, which I think is a problem because you are not, you know, people will want to locate

01:42:59.260 --> 01:43:04.540
[Guest]: their sort of, you know, their intellectual tradition, their history, you know, their

01:43:04.540 --> 01:43:09.780
[Guest]: customs, and ask whether this is in some ways consistent with what we are, you know, what

01:43:09.780 --> 01:43:11.740
[Guest]: we are actually now going to follow.

01:43:11.740 --> 01:43:13.180
[Guest]: So that didn't happen.

01:43:13.180 --> 01:43:18.420
[Guest]: It's somewhat similar to this, you know, you had Alex Tabarrok and Shruti Rajgopal and

01:43:18.420 --> 01:43:25.060
[Guest]: episode on public policy where our problem was we were doing some cheap imitation of,

01:43:25.060 --> 01:43:27.060
[Guest]: you know, a lot of stuff which we should not be doing.

01:43:27.060 --> 01:43:33.460
[Guest]: We are way behind on the economic sort of, you know, cycle to start taking some maternity

01:43:33.460 --> 01:43:39.460
[Guest]: leave and some environmental issues right now as the, you know, public policy framework

01:43:39.460 --> 01:43:40.460
[Guest]: for ourselves.

01:43:40.460 --> 01:43:41.460
[Guest]: It's a similar thing.

01:43:41.460 --> 01:43:48.020
[Guest]: They took the whole constitution, forget about just taking a few policies and imitating them.

01:43:48.020 --> 01:43:54.900
[Guest]: The second was, there is a demographic stress there, right, which is a lot of people who

01:43:54.900 --> 01:43:57.860
[Guest]: could get out of those countries got out.

01:43:57.860 --> 01:43:59.380
[Guest]: And in some sense in India, this is also true.

01:43:59.380 --> 01:44:01.780
[Guest]: I mean, a lot of people who could get out, got out.

01:44:01.780 --> 01:44:08.540
[Guest]: And once they went out, they were then forming their own pressure groups, all kinds of things

01:44:08.540 --> 01:44:10.460
[Guest]: from there and trying to influence.

01:44:10.460 --> 01:44:13.700
[Guest]: And those who remained back, they were just getting more and more xenophobic because they

01:44:13.700 --> 01:44:16.100
[Guest]: were now starting to become a minority in the same country.

01:44:16.100 --> 01:44:20.140
[Guest]: And in many of these places, there is a real fear that, you know, what is our original

01:44:20.140 --> 01:44:24.300
[Guest]: sort of identity is going to get run over because of immigration and things of that

01:44:24.300 --> 01:44:25.300
[Guest]: kind.

01:44:25.300 --> 01:44:29.060
[Guest]: And then they see that you are now forming, you know, coming to us with a form of government

01:44:29.060 --> 01:44:31.940
[Guest]: where these guys, if they stay for five more years, they will become citizens and they

01:44:31.940 --> 01:44:33.220
[Guest]: will vote.

01:44:33.220 --> 01:44:34.540
[Guest]: And then, you know, then what will happen?

01:44:34.540 --> 01:44:39.700
[Guest]: This is again, some of these things also animate our polity at this point in time.

01:44:39.700 --> 01:44:41.420
[Guest]: So that's second.

01:44:41.420 --> 01:44:46.340
[Guest]: And then the third issue, I think, is also the fact that there was a sort of liberal

01:44:46.340 --> 01:44:47.340
[Guest]: triumphalism.

01:44:47.340 --> 01:44:53.420
[Guest]: And, you know, then there is no further sort of reflection that, you know, what do we need

01:44:53.420 --> 01:44:54.780
[Guest]: to do?

01:44:54.780 --> 01:44:56.660
[Guest]: What is the next set of agenda?

01:44:56.660 --> 01:45:02.660
[Guest]: And then the GFC happened, the global financial crisis happened, which, I mean, its impact,

01:45:02.660 --> 01:45:06.900
[Guest]: I think, is much larger than what people are still, you know, have still written about

01:45:06.900 --> 01:45:07.900
[Guest]: and thought about.

01:45:07.900 --> 01:45:13.420
[Guest]: I think, you know, all of this, you know, in some form or the other, this populist movement,

01:45:13.420 --> 01:45:18.500
[Guest]: Trump and, you know, the Tea Party movement and whatever has happened to the American

01:45:18.500 --> 01:45:21.220
[Guest]: conservatives and the American right.

01:45:21.220 --> 01:45:26.380
[Guest]: And what is happening in many of these is a belief that that liberalism eventually GFC

01:45:26.380 --> 01:45:32.500
[Guest]: showed is that old thing of, you know, socializing losses and, you know, privatizing profits

01:45:32.500 --> 01:45:37.420
[Guest]: and, you know, letting people get away, you know, after they having done this.

01:45:37.420 --> 01:45:41.300
[Guest]: I think that imprint is very, very strong in many parts of the world.

01:45:41.300 --> 01:45:44.380
[Guest]: And there is, therefore, a backlash, which is continuing.

01:45:44.380 --> 01:45:48.900
[Guest]: And I think when you combine social media and a whole lot of other things along with

01:45:48.900 --> 01:45:54.060
[Guest]: it, it's just, you know, created, I mean, it's just formed a very different sort of,

01:45:54.060 --> 01:45:59.500
[Guest]: you know, movement, which I think is a genuine threat to liberalism.

01:45:59.500 --> 01:46:03.100
[Guest]: And I think more than I would say even the Cold War threat to liberalism.

01:46:03.100 --> 01:46:08.180
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and the sort of the interesting thing about the GFC also is that, number one, I

01:46:08.180 --> 01:46:12.300
[Amit Varma]: think there was a misdiagnosis that a lot of the problems that why that failure happened

01:46:12.300 --> 01:46:16.900
[Amit Varma]: have to do with statism, I linked to a great essay by Lawrence White, in my show notes

01:46:16.900 --> 01:46:21.860
[Amit Varma]: about all the sort of the distortions, which kind of led to that.

01:46:21.860 --> 01:46:27.340
[Amit Varma]: And also, we saw, you know, what I would not really consider would call free markets like,

01:46:27.340 --> 01:46:31.780
[Amit Varma]: you know, bailing, like you said, you're socializing losses, privatizing profits, bailing out companies

01:46:31.780 --> 01:46:37.260
[Amit Varma]: which are failing is just, you know, creates moral hazard, then you bail out a company

01:46:37.260 --> 01:46:41.900
[Amit Varma]: today for failing tomorrow, you're giving an incentive to people to take great risks,

01:46:41.900 --> 01:46:45.260
[Amit Varma]: knowing that there is no cost to them for doing so they'll be bailed out.

01:46:45.260 --> 01:46:50.620
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, which doesn't make any sense at all, I think it's a fundamental tenet of

01:46:50.620 --> 01:46:53.940
[Amit Varma]: free markets that companies that fail should be allowed to fail.

01:46:53.940 --> 01:46:56.020
[Amit Varma]: And that's another thing that sort of distresses me.

01:46:56.020 --> 01:46:59.700
[Amit Varma]: And I know you've written about this, as well is that markets get a bad rap because people

01:46:59.700 --> 01:47:04.020
[Amit Varma]: confuse what is good for business with what is good for markets, like I saw someone on

01:47:04.020 --> 01:47:08.420
[Amit Varma]: Twitter use the phrase, pro business and free market in the same sentence.

01:47:08.420 --> 01:47:12.380
[Amit Varma]: And I was just thinking to myself that dude, these are opposite things.

01:47:12.380 --> 01:47:14.020
[Amit Varma]: These are completely opposite things.

01:47:14.020 --> 01:47:20.260
[Amit Varma]: What is good for big businesses are bad for people in general, because, you know, what

01:47:20.260 --> 01:47:25.820
[Amit Varma]: is good for them is that if you sort of prevent competition to them, you protect their markets,

01:47:25.820 --> 01:47:29.460
[Amit Varma]: you create entry barriers, that's not what is good for consumers.

01:47:29.460 --> 01:47:34.780
[Amit Varma]: So inevitably, big business will always kind of speak out against free markets.

01:47:34.780 --> 01:47:37.500
[Amit Varma]: But this sort of fundamental notion people don't get.

01:47:37.500 --> 01:47:42.460
[Amit Varma]: So they look at like a cronyistic system like we've had over so many decades in India.

01:47:42.460 --> 01:47:48.100
[Amit Varma]: And we look at the bad aspects of that where state coercion is helping companies, you know,

01:47:48.100 --> 01:47:49.700
[Amit Varma]: make money or whatever.

01:47:49.700 --> 01:47:52.060
[Amit Varma]: And the assumption will be that, oh, look, markets are bad.

01:47:52.060 --> 01:47:57.020
[Amit Varma]: But these are not markets, this is not voluntary action, this is a coercive hand of the state.

01:47:57.020 --> 01:48:00.820
[Amit Varma]: But that's kind of a little bit of a ramble.

01:48:00.820 --> 01:48:08.460
[Guest]: Let's, and I'll come to economics later, but while we are, sure, yeah, go ahead.

01:48:08.460 --> 01:48:14.980
[Guest]: You know, like you are, you run this writing course for almost, what now, maybe eight months?

01:48:14.980 --> 01:48:17.540
[Amit Varma]: The 10th cohort is going on and I skipped a month in between.

01:48:17.540 --> 01:48:18.540
[Guest]: Okay.

01:48:18.540 --> 01:48:19.540
[Guest]: So 11 months, right.

01:48:19.540 --> 01:48:22.020
[Guest]: And then you're doing a podcasting thing and you're doing a TikTok.

01:48:22.020 --> 01:48:27.500
[Guest]: I'll suggest two courses if you still have time, that you must do.

01:48:27.500 --> 01:48:33.300
[Guest]: One is this, you know, just this course on economic reasoning, just because, I mean,

01:48:33.300 --> 01:48:37.500
[Guest]: both you have the reach as well as your ability to sort of, you know, demystify some of these

01:48:37.500 --> 01:48:39.740
[Guest]: things in a nice and patient manner.

01:48:39.740 --> 01:48:45.060
[Guest]: I think what this economic, I see so many people, otherwise well-intentioned, can argue

01:48:45.060 --> 01:48:50.580
[Guest]: things and just slip down this path of not being able to think through.

01:48:50.580 --> 01:48:54.220
[Guest]: And the second one, since you are a poker player and this, I've been thinking for some

01:48:54.220 --> 01:48:56.980
[Guest]: time that I should suggest this to you.

01:48:56.980 --> 01:49:05.780
[Guest]: One course on BOSS, just probabilistic thinking, Bayesian reasoning, it's like, it's a must

01:49:05.780 --> 01:49:06.780
[Guest]: for almost everyone.

01:49:06.780 --> 01:49:11.020
[Guest]: I mean, it's, otherwise people just read so many wrong conclusions, it's just, it's not

01:49:11.020 --> 01:49:12.020
[Guest]: funny.

01:49:12.020 --> 01:49:16.660
[Amit Varma]: See, Raghu, I got to tell you that you don't know what resonance your words have with me.

01:49:16.660 --> 01:49:19.740
[Amit Varma]: It's almost like you're reading my mind, like have you hacked into my brain or something?

01:49:19.740 --> 01:49:22.900
[Amit Varma]: Because one of the things I'm toying with and I want to do at some point in time is

01:49:22.900 --> 01:49:28.180
[Amit Varma]: that my sense is that our education system is not flawed just in terms of delivery, but

01:49:28.180 --> 01:49:33.540
[Amit Varma]: also conception, which is why people who come out of our education system don't even have

01:49:33.540 --> 01:49:34.700
[Amit Varma]: basic skills.

01:49:34.700 --> 01:49:38.140
[Amit Varma]: And these specifically include skills of thinking about the world.

01:49:38.140 --> 01:49:42.220
[Amit Varma]: So I've been thinking for a while of putting a course together consisting of essential

01:49:42.220 --> 01:49:47.180
[Amit Varma]: things that I think everyone should learn, taught by me and perhaps others, which include,

01:49:47.180 --> 01:49:51.580
[Amit Varma]: of course, writing and communication, which include things like financial literacy, which

01:49:51.580 --> 01:49:56.300
[Amit Varma]: I am not the person to teach, but it's something everyone should know, logical thinking and

01:49:56.300 --> 01:49:59.220
[Amit Varma]: economic reasoning and probabilistic thinking.

01:49:59.220 --> 01:50:04.620
[Amit Varma]: So you know, it's almost like you're sort of, you're messing with my brain here, you

01:50:04.620 --> 01:50:09.820
[Amit Varma]: know, have you done a phishing scam on my brain or something is what I must ask at this

01:50:09.820 --> 01:50:11.140
[Amit Varma]: point.

01:50:11.140 --> 01:50:15.340
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I'll come to economics later, and particularly to your father's scooter,

01:50:15.340 --> 01:50:17.900
[Amit Varma]: which is a subject of great interest to me.

01:50:17.900 --> 01:50:22.260
[Amit Varma]: But before we do that, I want to sort of talk a little bit about nationalism, where you

01:50:22.260 --> 01:50:27.420
[Amit Varma]: made a couple of interesting points, and I want to take off of one of them to ask sort

01:50:27.420 --> 01:50:28.800
[Amit Varma]: of a broader question.

01:50:28.800 --> 01:50:33.260
[Amit Varma]: So at one point where you're talking about the idea of India, you wrote, quote, the real

01:50:33.260 --> 01:50:37.380
[Amit Varma]: dividing line on political thought in India has always been nationalism.

01:50:37.380 --> 01:50:42.940
[Amit Varma]: This pits one imagination of the Indian nation with another complete with their own imagined

01:50:42.940 --> 01:50:47.100
[Amit Varma]: past, a lament of the present and a vision for an ideal nation, stop quote.

01:50:47.100 --> 01:50:52.260
[Amit Varma]: And this is obviously the founders idea of India, as it were, and the current idea of

01:50:52.260 --> 01:50:53.880
[Amit Varma]: India of the current dispensation.

01:50:53.880 --> 01:50:56.340
[Amit Varma]: And even there, it's not like any one thing.

01:50:56.340 --> 01:50:59.380
[Amit Varma]: There are many competing ideas within these ideas.

01:50:59.380 --> 01:51:04.660
[Amit Varma]: But my larger question is this, that I think that at some level, given that instinctively

01:51:04.660 --> 01:51:10.140
[Amit Varma]: we are hardwired to be tribalistic, to look at the world in terms of us and the other,

01:51:10.140 --> 01:51:15.060
[Amit Varma]: would it then be the case that the question just comes down to how do we define the us

01:51:15.060 --> 01:51:17.140
[Amit Varma]: and how do we define the other?

01:51:17.140 --> 01:51:19.820
[Amit Varma]: And you can define it narrowly or broadly.

01:51:19.820 --> 01:51:25.980
[Amit Varma]: And one of the great sort of political successes of the Hindutva movement, and I'm not praising

01:51:25.980 --> 01:51:29.860
[Amit Varma]: them, it's success in the way that they have achieved this.

01:51:29.860 --> 01:51:32.780
[Amit Varma]: It's not a movement that I have anything good to say about.

01:51:32.780 --> 01:51:38.840
[Amit Varma]: But one of the things that they have successfully done is that they've subsumed a lot of identities

01:51:38.840 --> 01:51:43.300
[Amit Varma]: within this broad Hindutva identity, which is a remarkable political success.

01:51:43.300 --> 01:51:45.780
[Amit Varma]: Like a few years ago, I would have said it's not possible.

01:51:45.780 --> 01:51:50.420
[Amit Varma]: We are a country driven by identity politics, divided by identity.

01:51:50.420 --> 01:51:57.060
[Amit Varma]: But yet they have created this larger banner of Hindutva, which has subsumed some of them.

01:51:57.060 --> 01:52:03.500
[Amit Varma]: And one illustration of this is that in both 2014 and 2019, the BJP got more of the Dalit

01:52:03.500 --> 01:52:05.460
[Amit Varma]: vote than anyone else.

01:52:05.460 --> 01:52:09.700
[Amit Varma]: You know, they were described by a scholar of the Dalit movements in Prashanth Jha's

01:52:09.700 --> 01:52:11.420
[Amit Varma]: book, How the BJP Wins.

01:52:11.420 --> 01:52:14.980
[Amit Varma]: I forget the name of the scholar in question, but he called them the default Dalit party

01:52:14.980 --> 01:52:16.060
[Amit Varma]: of India.

01:52:16.060 --> 01:52:20.460
[Amit Varma]: So they've managed this thing where they've subsumed all of these different identities.

01:52:20.460 --> 01:52:26.620
[Amit Varma]: And now the dominant sort of tribal vision, as it were, in India is a BJP's vision of

01:52:26.620 --> 01:52:27.900
[Amit Varma]: nationalism.

01:52:27.900 --> 01:52:32.940
[Amit Varma]: Now the thing is, if somebody is to say that there are elements of this which are toxic,

01:52:32.940 --> 01:52:37.100
[Amit Varma]: because they do the othering of Muslims, because it is, you know, so many regressive notions

01:52:37.100 --> 01:52:38.340
[Amit Varma]: are part of it.

01:52:38.340 --> 01:52:42.860
[Amit Varma]: If someone is to come up with a competing vision, what is that competing vision based

01:52:42.860 --> 01:52:43.860
[Amit Varma]: on?

01:52:43.860 --> 01:52:47.460
[Amit Varma]: Because that competing vision cannot, you know, you don't have an ideas based nationalism

01:52:47.460 --> 01:52:48.660
[Amit Varma]: happening.

01:52:48.660 --> 01:52:50.460
[Amit Varma]: That doesn't appeal at a visceral level.

01:52:50.460 --> 01:52:53.980
[Amit Varma]: You can't build a nationalism around liberalism, for example.

01:52:53.980 --> 01:52:58.460
[Amit Varma]: I know people think that it's possible, but I am a little skeptical of that process because

01:52:58.460 --> 01:53:05.180
[Amit Varma]: people don't have that visceral feeling towards, you know, ideas as they do towards notions

01:53:05.180 --> 01:53:06.660
[Amit Varma]: of identity.

01:53:06.660 --> 01:53:08.060
[Amit Varma]: What's your response to that?

01:53:08.060 --> 01:53:09.060
[Guest]: Right.

01:53:09.060 --> 01:53:14.140
[Guest]: So I think just going back to that point, I think in that particular edition, if I remember

01:53:14.140 --> 01:53:24.180
[Guest]: it right, the idea was the Indian state is always statist, conservative, and also in

01:53:24.180 --> 01:53:29.060
[Guest]: some sense, you know, socialist, socialist.

01:53:29.060 --> 01:53:32.580
[Guest]: And therefore, there is no difference among Indian parties on these grounds.

01:53:32.580 --> 01:53:38.340
[Guest]: So the only access is this notion of idea of India or the nationalist idea.

01:53:38.340 --> 01:53:42.820
[Guest]: And I think if you have to broaden it, right, like you rightly said, us versus them, I mean,

01:53:42.820 --> 01:53:49.940
[Guest]: sometimes it manifests itself in India as nativist, you know, Mumbiker or whatever Maharashtrian

01:53:49.940 --> 01:53:53.240
[Guest]: versus non-Maharashtrian and things of that kind.

01:53:53.240 --> 01:53:56.980
[Guest]: And then sometimes it manifests itself as nationalist.

01:53:56.980 --> 01:54:01.500
[Guest]: And then there is one strand in India, which is internationalist, you know, these guys

01:54:01.500 --> 01:54:05.700
[Guest]: who are using toolkits these days, as it is alleged, right.

01:54:05.700 --> 01:54:10.940
[Guest]: So I think what the success of the current dispensation is the idea of taking it to the

01:54:10.940 --> 01:54:16.580
[Guest]: nationalist identity level, subsuming the nativist and the nativist, I'm not saying

01:54:16.580 --> 01:54:23.260
[Guest]: is only region based, nativist is just any identity that is, you know, sub nationalist.

01:54:23.260 --> 01:54:30.460
[Guest]: Now your question of what is the competing idea or a competing political force that might

01:54:30.460 --> 01:54:32.540
[Guest]: take this on?

01:54:32.540 --> 01:54:35.740
[Guest]: I mean, I would rather go the other way.

01:54:35.740 --> 01:54:38.620
[Guest]: See there are two things that will happen eventually.

01:54:38.620 --> 01:54:45.660
[Guest]: One is, it's like the Carl Schmitt mentioned that, listen, politics is eventually about

01:54:45.660 --> 01:54:49.060
[Guest]: friend enemy divide and enemy distinction.

01:54:49.060 --> 01:54:55.540
[Guest]: The more agglomerated you make things, you will find that people will look for enemies

01:54:55.540 --> 01:55:03.820
[Guest]: because you know, it is in the nature of people to find a competing sort of a view and then

01:55:03.820 --> 01:55:06.340
[Guest]: you will split.

01:55:06.340 --> 01:55:08.860
[Guest]: And in that sense, it is what happened to Congress, right.

01:55:08.860 --> 01:55:13.940
[Guest]: Congress was this sort of a, you know, tent, whatever a huge tent or whatever the term

01:55:13.940 --> 01:55:18.180
[Guest]: was for it, and then, you know, everybody came in and everybody, you know, where they're

01:55:18.180 --> 01:55:19.180
[Guest]: under it.

01:55:19.180 --> 01:55:22.460
[Guest]: And then that agglomeration then eventually started splitting, because there is an idea

01:55:22.460 --> 01:55:27.140
[Guest]: that we have to have a friend enemy distinction in order to actually do politics.

01:55:27.140 --> 01:55:29.660
[Guest]: Otherwise, what's the point?

01:55:29.660 --> 01:55:37.100
[Guest]: So I have a feeling that as opposed to the probability of a competing idea coming over

01:55:37.100 --> 01:55:42.820
[Guest]: a period of time, maybe because of lack of personalities of the kind that actually created

01:55:42.820 --> 01:55:48.700
[Guest]: this agglomeration, which is true of what happened with Congress as well, the agglomeration

01:55:48.700 --> 01:55:55.820
[Guest]: will again split and the people will start looking for competing ideas themselves, right.

01:55:55.820 --> 01:56:00.140
[Guest]: And you know, then start going and splitting and doing that now, will that take 10 years?

01:56:00.140 --> 01:56:01.620
[Guest]: Will that take 20?

01:56:01.620 --> 01:56:02.620
[Guest]: I don't know.

01:56:02.620 --> 01:56:05.620
[Guest]: I think it's all of us are underestimating how much it will take.

01:56:05.620 --> 01:56:10.500
[Guest]: I think it's going to take longer than what people think it might take, but it is going

01:56:10.500 --> 01:56:13.860
[Guest]: back to that other, you know, I like to do this.

01:56:13.860 --> 01:56:17.740
[Guest]: And just because you brought this up, suddenly, you know, the other notion came in.

01:56:17.740 --> 01:56:24.580
[Guest]: It's this notion in economics by this economist called Minsky, which is the Minsky cycle,

01:56:24.580 --> 01:56:31.100
[Guest]: that in the root, in the heart of the boom is the seed of the bust, right.

01:56:31.100 --> 01:56:35.180
[Guest]: And which is what happened in the GFC, in the subprime crisis, right.

01:56:35.180 --> 01:56:39.900
[Guest]: So I think the Minskyian moment will, I think it's already happened.

01:56:39.900 --> 01:56:43.780
[Guest]: As you build the agglomeration, you've already seeded it.

01:56:43.780 --> 01:56:49.220
[Guest]: It's a question of when it grows up, becomes a large tree and then, you know, cleaves this

01:56:49.220 --> 01:56:50.220
[Guest]: whole thing.

01:56:50.220 --> 01:56:51.220
[Guest]: We'll see.

01:56:51.220 --> 01:56:52.220
[Amit Varma]: But I think that is...

01:56:52.220 --> 01:56:53.220
[Amit Varma]: But what form would it take?

01:56:53.220 --> 01:56:54.780
[Amit Varma]: Would it take a more extreme form?

01:56:54.780 --> 01:56:59.780
[Amit Varma]: Like, the reason I ask is again, you know, you referred to Schmidt in your recent newsletter

01:56:59.780 --> 01:57:02.460
[Amit Varma]: on, you know, why coup won't take over Twitter.

01:57:02.460 --> 01:57:06.340
[Amit Varma]: And the obvious answer, of course, is network effects and Twitter already has that space.

01:57:06.340 --> 01:57:10.740
[Amit Varma]: But apart from that, the two points you mentioned was one that you need an other to fight against

01:57:10.740 --> 01:57:12.620
[Amit Varma]: for political mobilization.

01:57:12.620 --> 01:57:15.820
[Amit Varma]: And that is something that an echo chamber won't give you, which is presumably what they

01:57:15.820 --> 01:57:16.980
[Amit Varma]: mean coup to me.

01:57:16.980 --> 01:57:21.760
[Amit Varma]: But the other interesting point you made, which plays into this, is that because you

01:57:21.760 --> 01:57:25.740
[Amit Varma]: always need another, even when you seem to be a homogenous group, you will manufacture

01:57:25.740 --> 01:57:27.660
[Amit Varma]: it within that homogenous group.

01:57:27.660 --> 01:57:33.020
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes like I look at these, you know, right wing Twitter feeds and whatever for

01:57:33.020 --> 01:57:34.380
[Amit Varma]: my own amusement.

01:57:34.380 --> 01:57:39.220
[Amit Varma]: And there is already sort of these groupings between them of what they call trads and writers.

01:57:39.220 --> 01:57:43.060
[Amit Varma]: And I haven't bothered to look deep into the distinctions, but the trads are the guys who

01:57:43.060 --> 01:57:47.060
[Amit Varma]: says nobody should eat beef, the coercive hand of the state should prevent anybody from

01:57:47.060 --> 01:57:51.100
[Amit Varma]: eating what they don't want, they're basically imposing their values.

01:57:51.100 --> 01:57:55.660
[Amit Varma]: And writers, I don't really know what they're about, but, you know, I think they want to

01:57:55.660 --> 01:57:59.100
[Amit Varma]: eat beef privately, but otherwise publicly they support Modi.

01:57:59.100 --> 01:58:01.460
[Amit Varma]: So I don't know what the deal there is.

01:58:01.460 --> 01:58:06.780
[Amit Varma]: So the question that then comes up is that fine, that, you know, this evolves.

01:58:06.780 --> 01:58:08.620
[Amit Varma]: This is not how it's always going to be.

01:58:08.620 --> 01:58:14.300
[Amit Varma]: But does it necessarily evolve in a more extreme direction in the sense that, you know, the

01:58:14.300 --> 01:58:19.220
[Amit Varma]: trads beating the writers, for example, Yogi Adityanath or someone even more extreme becoming

01:58:19.220 --> 01:58:20.340
[Amit Varma]: the next PM.

01:58:20.340 --> 01:58:24.780
[Amit Varma]: And the reason I ask is, and this again comes back to, you know, the change in the gravitational

01:58:24.780 --> 01:58:28.960
[Amit Varma]: force as it were, how social media has changed everything that I think social media drives

01:58:28.960 --> 01:58:31.420
[Amit Varma]: us naturally towards the extremes.

01:58:31.420 --> 01:58:35.700
[Amit Varma]: There is no moderating influence anymore, there is no middle, the middle is gone.

01:58:35.700 --> 01:58:40.740
[Amit Varma]: Everyone always has to posture and do virtue signaling to rise within their in groups.

01:58:40.740 --> 01:58:44.740
[Amit Varma]: And the only way of doing that is by going further away to the extremes.

01:58:44.740 --> 01:58:50.180
[Amit Varma]: And you see the same kind of schism in the liberals as well, where people will be berated

01:58:50.180 --> 01:58:54.700
[Amit Varma]: for being too centrist or too whatever, and it's almost like a bad word.

01:58:54.700 --> 01:58:57.740
[Amit Varma]: And you have to go more and more towards the extremes.

01:58:57.740 --> 01:59:00.980
[Amit Varma]: And so all your incentives are towards being more extreme.

01:59:00.980 --> 01:59:07.420
[Amit Varma]: And that makes me worried that perhaps a natural direction for politics is towards the edges,

01:59:07.420 --> 01:59:12.780
[Amit Varma]: towards the fringes, as it were, where yesterday's fringe becomes today's mainstream, where yesterday's

01:59:12.780 --> 01:59:18.460
[Amit Varma]: firebrand rebel rouser, Yogi ji becomes, you know, the Chief Minister of UP now.

01:59:18.460 --> 01:59:24.340
[Amit Varma]: Is that a necessary direction or do you feel that that might be countervailed either by

01:59:24.340 --> 01:59:28.820
[Amit Varma]: something that I'm not considering, or by the fact that, you know, in general, the future

01:59:28.820 --> 01:59:31.540
[Amit Varma]: is unknown, unknown, so who knows something good may happen?

01:59:31.540 --> 01:59:32.540
[Guest]: Right.

01:59:32.540 --> 01:59:34.860
[Guest]: So this is a fresh point to consider.

01:59:34.860 --> 01:59:35.860
[Guest]: Right.

01:59:35.860 --> 01:59:43.940
[Guest]: So let me sort of, you know, on the fly, give some, and please, please add or, you know,

01:59:43.940 --> 01:59:45.940
[Guest]: contest some of this.

01:59:45.940 --> 01:59:47.380
[Guest]: Let's take two views of this.

01:59:47.380 --> 01:59:54.860
[Guest]: One is what happened when the previous agglomeration split, you know, the Congress agglomeration,

01:59:54.860 --> 01:59:56.300
[Guest]: they split on a few things, right?

01:59:56.300 --> 02:00:00.300
[Guest]: They split on this sub-identity, because the sub-identity was still there, there was a

02:00:00.300 --> 02:00:05.820
[Guest]: history and there was a, you know, this, this recidivism or whatever this, it's always there,

02:00:05.820 --> 02:00:09.060
[Guest]: I mean, people's mind.

02:00:09.060 --> 02:00:14.220
[Guest]: And it also split on the back of some socialistic slash, you know, the sort of guys who went

02:00:14.220 --> 02:00:21.700
[Guest]: away from Lohia and then down Karan Singh and Jabzeeban Ram and things of that kind.

02:00:21.700 --> 02:00:27.180
[Guest]: So, and, but nobody went the sort of the extreme in that sense that nobody became a radical

02:00:27.180 --> 02:00:31.780
[Guest]: Maoist or a communist, they went in some other direction.

02:00:31.780 --> 02:00:38.300
[Guest]: So I have a couple of points to make, one, when you are doing this agglomeration, you

02:00:38.300 --> 02:00:46.820
[Guest]: are again, in some sense, doing a top-down view of what the common identity is.

02:00:46.820 --> 02:00:50.300
[Guest]: And maybe there is a reason today to come together with that top-down view, because

02:00:50.300 --> 02:00:56.660
[Guest]: you have all kinds of imagined or real grievances and other, and all of that.

02:00:56.660 --> 02:01:00.460
[Guest]: Once you have sort of, you know, sorted some of those things out largely, or maybe at least

02:01:00.460 --> 02:01:09.660
[Guest]: some percent, then will your memory of what you were come back, you know, the, you know,

02:01:09.660 --> 02:01:15.740
[Guest]: will you remember that you were, you know, during Durga Puja on the seventh day, mutton

02:01:15.740 --> 02:01:20.580
[Guest]: was absolutely there, as you know, bhog in the house.

02:01:20.580 --> 02:01:26.060
[Guest]: And just because now, you know, some kind of something was told to you and you sort

02:01:26.060 --> 02:01:28.580
[Guest]: of, you know, left it.

02:01:28.580 --> 02:01:33.780
[Guest]: And Koshavangsha is no longer the thing, which is kosher at this point in time.

02:01:33.780 --> 02:01:38.340
[Guest]: But 10 years later, who knows, I mean, you will say, boss, that was there.

02:01:38.340 --> 02:01:44.460
[Guest]: And all it needs is somebody reasonably persuasive and a few other grievances that you might

02:01:44.460 --> 02:01:50.820
[Guest]: have about other things, not coming your way for it to, you know, coalesce and start another

02:01:50.820 --> 02:01:53.060
[Guest]: sort of, you know, splinter, splintering of this.

02:01:53.060 --> 02:01:55.820
[Guest]: So that is one sort of thought.

02:01:55.820 --> 02:01:57.660
[Guest]: Second is economic progress.

02:01:57.660 --> 02:02:05.060
[Guest]: I mean, what would it mean that if today we are at $2,000 per capita economy, and if we

02:02:05.060 --> 02:02:12.340
[Guest]: become 5,000, how much of these things, and then you have further aspirations of growth,

02:02:12.340 --> 02:02:18.300
[Guest]: or if you don't get to 5,000, either way, how would you look at some of these things?

02:02:18.300 --> 02:02:22.140
[Guest]: You would look at these things as success that actually has sated you, and you are very

02:02:22.140 --> 02:02:25.900
[Guest]: happy despite having not enough growth and everything.

02:02:25.900 --> 02:02:30.380
[Guest]: And will you be able to continue with that, you know, frame of mind that this is fine?

02:02:30.380 --> 02:02:37.760
[Guest]: Or even otherwise, once you get to 5,000, would that make you ask for more?

02:02:37.760 --> 02:02:39.780
[Guest]: And you'll say, why not 10,000?

02:02:39.780 --> 02:02:42.500
[Guest]: And then what does it mean for us to do 10,000?

02:02:42.500 --> 02:02:49.660
[Guest]: And once you are in that journey, you will realize that, you know, market is something

02:02:49.660 --> 02:02:52.620
[Guest]: that brings freedom, brings individual choice.

02:02:52.620 --> 02:02:57.940
[Guest]: I mean, you know, it is the easiest way to break, you know, a lot of, you know, whatever,

02:02:57.940 --> 02:03:02.340
[Guest]: you know, some of these firm social beliefs, et cetera.

02:03:02.340 --> 02:03:03.460
[Guest]: So that now that is another one.

02:03:03.460 --> 02:03:04.460
[Guest]: And I see this.

02:03:04.460 --> 02:03:09.820
[Guest]: I mean, some of these are like apparent to me in many of these conversations with friends

02:03:09.820 --> 02:03:10.820
[Guest]: and others.

02:03:10.820 --> 02:03:14.980
[Guest]: The guy is sort of starting to become more and more, you know, whatever, right wing and

02:03:14.980 --> 02:03:15.980
[Guest]: conservative.

02:03:15.980 --> 02:03:23.780
[Guest]: But, you know, in the same instance, he's posing, I mean, he's very happy that his daughter

02:03:23.780 --> 02:03:29.500
[Guest]: is wearing a short and, you know, sleeveless t-shirt, and he wants her to go somewhere.

02:03:29.500 --> 02:03:35.780
[Guest]: And somewhere these two forces will, you know, come against one another, because somebody

02:03:35.780 --> 02:03:40.740
[Guest]: out there is pushing against this also, right?

02:03:40.740 --> 02:03:45.220
[Guest]: So today you might say all of that while on Facebook, you're posting, you know, things

02:03:45.220 --> 02:03:49.420
[Unknown]: that your wife is wearing a sleeveless, which, you know, you never know three years later,

02:03:49.420 --> 02:03:51.460
[Guest]: some guy will say, boss, that is also not allowed.

02:03:51.460 --> 02:03:58.420
[Guest]: You know, so this, I mean, the thing that once you are done with some first level objectives

02:03:58.420 --> 02:04:03.140
[Guest]: for which you are agglomerating, the next and the next level of objectives that people

02:04:03.140 --> 02:04:08.420
[Guest]: might go for might actually bring you into that Smitty and friend and enemy, you know,

02:04:08.420 --> 02:04:09.420
[Unknown]: distinction.

02:04:09.420 --> 02:04:11.700
[Guest]: So I have a feeling that's also something that might happen.

02:04:11.700 --> 02:04:17.620
[Guest]: I mean, eventually maybe it's not, it's not going to the other sort of extreme.

02:04:17.620 --> 02:04:24.060
[Guest]: It might actually regress and go back into something which is slightly more, you know,

02:04:24.060 --> 02:04:28.540
[Guest]: I would say less extreme, more moderate because people have the memories of those things and

02:04:28.540 --> 02:04:33.700
[Guest]: people will continue to see outside and look at the world that is outside of India and

02:04:33.700 --> 02:04:34.700
[Guest]: what's happening there.

02:04:34.700 --> 02:04:35.700
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:04:35.700 --> 02:04:39.940
[Amit Varma]: No, that's a great point that, you know, becoming more extreme means you become more splintered

02:04:39.940 --> 02:04:43.900
[Amit Varma]: because they keep, there are drop offs at every point.

02:04:43.900 --> 02:04:48.540
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, and I can certainly see that if this battle between the Trads and the Raitas

02:04:48.540 --> 02:04:52.540
[Amit Varma]: accelerates, what are the beef eaters within the party going to do or even the meat eaters

02:04:52.540 --> 02:04:53.700
[Amit Varma]: for that matter?

02:04:53.700 --> 02:04:57.900
[Amit Varma]: The other sort of interesting point here, again, comes back to one of the favorite theme

02:04:57.900 --> 02:05:02.260
[Amit Varma]: of the show, which is incentives, is that, you know, the point that you made about what

02:05:02.260 --> 02:05:03.980
[Amit Varma]: role does economics play in this?

02:05:03.980 --> 02:05:06.380
[Amit Varma]: Because I think that economic incentives are huge.

02:05:06.380 --> 02:05:13.220
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you know, one of the reasons that there is less of, say, these identity based

02:05:13.220 --> 02:05:18.940
[Amit Varma]: problems in cities, like nothing is solved, but you still see less caste problems in cities

02:05:18.940 --> 02:05:24.300
[Amit Varma]: as opposed to rural areas where they're completely entrenched, is that you have a different set

02:05:24.300 --> 02:05:25.300
[Amit Varma]: of incentives.

02:05:25.300 --> 02:05:29.020
[Amit Varma]: Now, you're part of a large economic network, and there are many situations where you cannot

02:05:29.020 --> 02:05:30.340
[Amit Varma]: afford to discriminate.

02:05:30.340 --> 02:05:35.780
[Amit Varma]: Like if you are a company in a very competitive marketplace, or by company, I don't mean just

02:05:35.780 --> 02:05:39.940
[Amit Varma]: a big company, but you could even be a small outfit in a very competitive marketplace,

02:05:39.940 --> 02:05:43.620
[Amit Varma]: you are competing for the best workers, you can't afford to discriminate on the basis

02:05:43.620 --> 02:05:49.180
[Amit Varma]: of what someone's identity is, and those economic incentives come into play, and that therefore

02:05:49.180 --> 02:05:54.140
[Amit Varma]: I'm just thinking aloud, that then there are sort of incentives coming at you from two

02:05:54.140 --> 02:05:55.300
[Amit Varma]: kinds of networks.

02:05:55.300 --> 02:06:00.260
[Amit Varma]: One is your economic network, where you want your economic network to be as large as possible,

02:06:00.260 --> 02:06:01.780
[Amit Varma]: because that is most profitable for you.

02:06:01.780 --> 02:06:03.980
[Amit Varma]: And that's where your skills can get scaled.

02:06:03.980 --> 02:06:08.580
[Amit Varma]: But there are the incentives of your social networks, which is also feeding into your

02:06:08.580 --> 02:06:11.740
[Amit Varma]: economic network and vice versa.

02:06:11.740 --> 02:06:17.300
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, I kind of agree that progress is sort of something that can change these incentives.

02:06:17.300 --> 02:06:21.860
[Amit Varma]: Again, I do not want to say that this is panacea or that economic growth will solve all our

02:06:21.860 --> 02:06:22.860
[Amit Varma]: social problems.

02:06:22.860 --> 02:06:23.980
[Amit Varma]: Of course, it won't.

02:06:23.980 --> 02:06:28.540
[Amit Varma]: But on the margins, it does, you know, change the incentives and make a little bit of a

02:06:28.540 --> 02:06:30.220
[Amit Varma]: positive difference.

02:06:30.220 --> 02:06:31.900
[Amit Varma]: And that's kind of something to be noted.

02:06:31.900 --> 02:06:35.940
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing that comes to mind also is that, you know, in recent episodes, I've

02:06:35.940 --> 02:06:40.640
[Amit Varma]: been musing aloud on how a lot of this is a battle between the concrete and the abstract,

02:06:40.640 --> 02:06:44.300
[Amit Varma]: that when we focus on the concrete things in our lives, we are all actually pretty liberal

02:06:44.300 --> 02:06:50.460
[Amit Varma]: and inclusive, you know, like your friend whose wife may wear sleeveless or whose daughter

02:06:50.460 --> 02:06:51.700
[Amit Varma]: may wear shorts.

02:06:51.700 --> 02:06:56.300
[Amit Varma]: But when it comes to abstract notions, we get into all these narratives, where it's

02:06:56.300 --> 02:06:59.300
[Amit Varma]: us versus the other and these people are bad.

02:06:59.300 --> 02:07:01.780
[Amit Varma]: So you will say that, oh, you know, Muslims are bad.

02:07:01.780 --> 02:07:07.180
[Amit Varma]: But if you actually encounter one in person, you will be perfectly friendly and all that.

02:07:07.180 --> 02:07:12.940
[Amit Varma]: And this is sort of this bizarre dichotomy that I can't figure out, you know, it's it's

02:07:12.940 --> 02:07:17.860
[Amit Varma]: almost like, you know, Hitler being vegetarian, a nice guy being a fascist, like, what the

02:07:17.860 --> 02:07:19.140
[Amit Varma]: hell is going on?

02:07:19.140 --> 02:07:24.900
[Amit Varma]: You know, why does the abstract have so much sort of pull over our lives when we behave

02:07:24.900 --> 02:07:29.300
[Amit Varma]: in when we think of the like, this even applies to, for example, classical liberal values,

02:07:29.300 --> 02:07:32.820
[Amit Varma]: like I, I say that in our personal lives, you're all libertarian, right?

02:07:32.820 --> 02:07:34.540
[Amit Varma]: We don't force anybody to do anything.

02:07:34.540 --> 02:07:35.660
[Amit Varma]: We respect consent.

02:07:35.660 --> 02:07:37.260
[Amit Varma]: We don't like coercion.

02:07:37.260 --> 02:07:40.540
[Amit Varma]: You know, if you go to have a meal at a restaurant with our friends, we are not going to force

02:07:40.540 --> 02:07:42.460
[Amit Varma]: them to eat exactly what we want them to eat.

02:07:42.460 --> 02:07:45.420
[Amit Varma]: We are not going to force them to pay for us.

02:07:45.420 --> 02:07:50.860
[Amit Varma]: But when we sort of abstract it out into a larger domain, suddenly consent doesn't matter.

02:07:50.860 --> 02:07:52.540
[Amit Varma]: Coercion is fine.

02:07:52.540 --> 02:07:58.220
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, is this sort of and this dichotomy is kind of disturbing to me.

02:07:58.220 --> 02:08:01.300
[Amit Varma]: Is this something that you've kind of thought about?

02:08:01.300 --> 02:08:02.860
[Guest]: I mean, not in these terms.

02:08:02.860 --> 02:08:09.540
[Guest]: I mean, there is this dichotomy, which I think exists in many areas, because what happens

02:08:09.540 --> 02:08:18.660
[Guest]: is when it's concrete, then it's a bit difficult for you to, you know, play that, you know,

02:08:18.660 --> 02:08:24.140
[Guest]: what's there in your mind out in real action, because there are other things that come into

02:08:24.140 --> 02:08:25.140
[Guest]: play.

02:08:25.140 --> 02:08:30.460
[Guest]: The ideas that you've been brought up with, you know, for a fact that, you know, you can't

02:08:30.460 --> 02:08:35.420
[Guest]: be bad to a person on his face, abuse him onto his face.

02:08:35.420 --> 02:08:37.580
[Guest]: Most of us would not do that.

02:08:37.580 --> 02:08:44.820
[Guest]: But in abstract, I think it's a bit more, you know, you have these things in your mind,

02:08:44.820 --> 02:08:50.980
[Guest]: which are biases, which you keep getting reinforced when you are having, you know, conversation

02:08:50.980 --> 02:08:54.220
[Guest]: when you are reading things and things of that kind.

02:08:54.220 --> 02:09:03.220
[Guest]: Now, I have a feeling that the, for the people who actually act on the abstract views that

02:09:03.220 --> 02:09:08.620
[Guest]: they have, on the abstract notions that they have, there are a few who don't make this

02:09:08.620 --> 02:09:11.300
[Guest]: difference and who act on it.

02:09:11.300 --> 02:09:18.540
[Guest]: They actually get emboldened because of the fact that there are way more people that are

02:09:18.540 --> 02:09:23.500
[Guest]: actually having these abstract notions, because the guys having the abstract notions will

02:09:23.500 --> 02:09:28.860
[Guest]: continue to give license to people who will actually act in this manner, till it actually

02:09:28.860 --> 02:09:32.460
[Guest]: starts impacting their life, which is when the splintering hopefully, or whenever the

02:09:32.460 --> 02:09:34.820
[Guest]: splintering happens, might happen that way.

02:09:34.820 --> 02:09:36.460
[Guest]: But yeah, I mean, I really don't know.

02:09:36.460 --> 02:09:41.300
[Guest]: I think there are many places where I would say that the same thing applies to me.

02:09:41.300 --> 02:09:47.420
[Guest]: I have some abstract views, but when I actually get in front of somebody, I'm not telling

02:09:47.420 --> 02:09:54.180
[Guest]: him that, you know, what I have in my mind, exactly, or I'm not behaving in that manner,

02:09:54.180 --> 02:09:57.340
[Guest]: which I thought I would behave because I was thinking about it that way.

02:09:57.340 --> 02:10:04.460
[Guest]: So I think that's mind-body dualism it is, eventually, since we have a mind and then

02:10:04.460 --> 02:10:08.980
[Guest]: the body acts differently, because it's still dual.

02:10:08.980 --> 02:10:10.100
[Amit Varma]: Right.

02:10:10.100 --> 02:10:15.820
[Amit Varma]: So one sort of final, and before we kind of move on, just, I again want to clarify that

02:10:15.820 --> 02:10:19.980
[Amit Varma]: lest I be seen as generalizing too much, of course, there are exceptions, there are abstract

02:10:19.980 --> 02:10:23.780
[Amit Varma]: concepts which are good and beautiful, like freedom and individual liberty.

02:10:23.780 --> 02:10:28.340
[Amit Varma]: And there are concrete actions which people do, which are a problem, which is why our

02:10:28.340 --> 02:10:29.900
[Amit Varma]: world is not a perfect world.

02:10:29.900 --> 02:10:36.660
[Amit Varma]: People do go out and lynch others because they are allegedly, you know, eating the wrong

02:10:36.660 --> 02:10:42.100
[Amit Varma]: kind of food or dating someone that, you know, the lyncher would rather have had an opportunity

02:10:42.100 --> 02:10:44.860
[Amit Varma]: to date instead.

02:10:44.860 --> 02:10:48.940
[Amit Varma]: So you know, let's kind of move on to our final political subject before we move on

02:10:48.940 --> 02:10:50.420
[Amit Varma]: to economics.

02:10:50.420 --> 02:10:55.420
[Amit Varma]: And I'm thinking of our Prime Minister, Narendra Modi, fascinating character.

02:10:55.420 --> 02:11:00.260
[Amit Varma]: And in edition 33 of your newsletter, you wrote, quote, even his detractors will admit

02:11:00.260 --> 02:11:02.940
[Amit Varma]: PM Modi is a transformational political leader.

02:11:02.940 --> 02:11:06.920
[Amit Varma]: He has an appeal that transcends ideological positions on both statism and recognition

02:11:06.920 --> 02:11:08.180
[Amit Varma]: in Indian polity.

02:11:08.180 --> 02:11:12.580
[Amit Varma]: His arrival coincided with a temporal phase in the Indian society that enabled him to

02:11:12.580 --> 02:11:17.540
[Amit Varma]: shift the ideological position of the medium Indian voter proximate to that of the BJP.

02:11:17.540 --> 02:11:22.500
[Amit Varma]: This has meant a Modi coalition of voters, which only exists because he has willed it.

02:11:22.500 --> 02:11:27.260
[Amit Varma]: Unfortunately, he hasn't been able to transplant his success as a transformation leader in

02:11:27.260 --> 02:11:29.680
[Amit Varma]: electoral area to governance.

02:11:29.680 --> 02:11:30.840
[Amit Varma]: This is a surprise.

02:11:30.840 --> 02:11:34.860
[Amit Varma]: The meticulous planning and the attention to details that mark his electoral success

02:11:34.860 --> 02:11:40.420
[Amit Varma]: are conspicuously absent in many of the key decisions he has taken over the years.

02:11:40.420 --> 02:11:44.300
[Amit Varma]: And I think at one point even I wrote a sort of a column when I think Amit Shah was made

02:11:44.300 --> 02:11:50.860
[Amit Varma]: Home Minister about that someone who is such a remarkable political strategist, you know,

02:11:50.860 --> 02:11:57.340
[Amit Varma]: and almost single handedly the architect of BJP's great win in 2014.

02:11:57.340 --> 02:12:00.740
[Amit Varma]: Can he bring any of those skills to governance?

02:12:00.740 --> 02:12:01.740
[Amit Varma]: And I felt he wouldn't.

02:12:01.740 --> 02:12:02.740
[Amit Varma]: I felt it wouldn't happen.

02:12:02.740 --> 02:12:07.340
[Amit Varma]: And the reason it possibly doesn't happen in Modi's case is simply because of the incentives.

02:12:07.340 --> 02:12:11.100
[Amit Varma]: You know, in politics, they'll put everything into it, because that is an incentive the

02:12:11.100 --> 02:12:12.380
[Amit Varma]: will to power.

02:12:12.380 --> 02:12:18.060
[Amit Varma]: But when you are in government, the how you govern has actually nothing to do with whether

02:12:18.060 --> 02:12:20.000
[Amit Varma]: you get reelected or not.

02:12:20.000 --> 02:12:23.900
[Amit Varma]: Everything has to do with narrative control, which those guys are pretty good at, though

02:12:23.900 --> 02:12:28.420
[Amit Varma]: I think they make a lot of mistakes as well, such as, you know, letting their IT cell run

02:12:28.420 --> 02:12:35.480
[Amit Varma]: the narrative on issues where you need sort of a less thuggish kind of thinking, you know,

02:12:35.480 --> 02:12:40.180
[Amit Varma]: as in the case of the farm bills, where they lost the narrative completely, I think, you

02:12:40.180 --> 02:12:43.980
[Amit Varma]: know, with the way they came down on the protests and painted the protesters as anti-national.

02:12:43.980 --> 02:12:46.580
[Amit Varma]: So one could argue that that may work for them in the long run.

02:12:46.580 --> 02:12:51.260
[Amit Varma]: But I just felt that there was a more sort of statesman like approach they could have

02:12:51.260 --> 02:12:54.380
[Amit Varma]: taken, though that is perhaps expecting too much of this lot.

02:12:54.380 --> 02:12:59.500
[Amit Varma]: So what do you think of Modi when you sort of look at him that at one level such a remarkable

02:12:59.500 --> 02:13:04.540
[Amit Varma]: politician and again by remarkable, I don't mean it in a good or bad way, it's just a

02:13:04.540 --> 02:13:08.700
[Amit Varma]: fact in terms of what he achieved in politics and, you know, building this vote bank and

02:13:08.700 --> 02:13:11.180
[Amit Varma]: the kind of leadership that he has.

02:13:11.180 --> 02:13:16.740
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you know, in governance, you know, just the opposite.

02:13:16.740 --> 02:13:19.500
[Amit Varma]: So what do you make of this fascinating figure?

02:13:19.500 --> 02:13:24.940
[Guest]: So I mean, listen, I think all of us agree that in terms of maybe there are only two

02:13:24.940 --> 02:13:31.380
[Guest]: or three really transformative political leaders that have emerged in the post-independent

02:13:31.380 --> 02:13:37.820
[Guest]: India and in some ways, I think Modi will eventually tower above all of them by the

02:13:37.820 --> 02:13:43.700
[Guest]: time, you know, Modi's innings is over.

02:13:43.700 --> 02:13:50.860
[Guest]: And the question is, you know, what is the legacy going to be in the long run?

02:13:50.860 --> 02:14:01.860
[Guest]: And I still hold out some hope for a reason, for a reason, because I think that in some

02:14:01.860 --> 02:14:12.740
[Guest]: sense, he also is aware of the fact that, you know, what he has done politically is,

02:14:12.740 --> 02:14:19.640
[Guest]: you know, almost unbeatable, at least insofar as he's active in politics.

02:14:19.640 --> 02:14:23.940
[Guest]: But then, you know, what is the hundred year view of him?

02:14:23.940 --> 02:14:33.100
[Guest]: And I think my view is a lot of really good politicians do have this in their minds that,

02:14:33.100 --> 02:14:36.700
[Guest]: you know, how is history going to judge me?

02:14:36.700 --> 02:14:44.180
[Guest]: And I have a hope, I mean, this is more optimism speaking, that as more electoral victories

02:14:44.180 --> 02:14:48.180
[Guest]: pile up and as you sort of, you know, finish off all the final frontiers, you know, you

02:14:48.180 --> 02:14:52.580
[Guest]: have not won Bengal, you might win Bengal and you not won some other southern state,

02:14:52.580 --> 02:14:54.540
[Guest]: you win those southern states.

02:14:54.540 --> 02:14:58.420
[Guest]: And it might happen in the next couple of years, for all you know.

02:14:58.420 --> 02:15:07.260
[Guest]: This question will start animating, at least I hope it starts animating, you know, him.

02:15:07.260 --> 02:15:12.820
[Guest]: And I have a feeling that, again, maybe it's optimism in my mind, but I think there are

02:15:12.820 --> 02:15:21.420
[Guest]: some signs of that as maybe the pandemic has precipitated it, maybe the time is right now

02:15:21.420 --> 02:15:26.100
[Guest]: because there is, you know, absolute decimation of the opposition, because, you know, once

02:15:26.100 --> 02:15:31.220
[Guest]: you have decimated the opposition and once you have pretty much, you know, won all the

02:15:31.220 --> 02:15:38.140
[Guest]: sort of electoral battles you have to win, it's natural for someone who has a high achievement

02:15:38.140 --> 02:15:44.820
[Guest]: orientation, has a sense of, you know, that history should view me in a certain way, for

02:15:44.820 --> 02:15:46.820
[Guest]: them to do something more, right.

02:15:46.820 --> 02:15:54.040
[Guest]: So I have that kind of, you know, expectation that this thing might turn a bit differently

02:15:54.040 --> 02:15:57.620
[Guest]: than what people are thinking that it might go.

02:15:57.620 --> 02:16:04.820
[Guest]: And some of it is also my hope that, you know, we actually get to see that because with that

02:16:04.820 --> 02:16:13.740
[Guest]: kind of both political capital and the ability to set the narrative, I mean, if channelled

02:16:13.740 --> 02:16:16.180
[Guest]: the right way, this can be transformational for the country.

02:16:16.180 --> 02:16:22.180
[Guest]: I mean, and, you know, we should somehow both hope as well as make this effort through various

02:16:22.180 --> 02:16:27.380
[Guest]: means that, you know, that the right message and the right sort of, because politically

02:16:27.380 --> 02:16:31.680
[Guest]: to sort of fight and defeat, I don't think is happening easily.

02:16:31.680 --> 02:16:39.860
[Guest]: So if you're an optimist, then the hope is that the right agenda is then picked up.

02:16:39.860 --> 02:16:43.260
[Guest]: And then you hope that if there are ways to sort of make sure that the right agenda is

02:16:43.260 --> 02:16:49.660
[Guest]: picked up through whichever means that you can, you know, employ, you hope that that

02:16:49.660 --> 02:16:50.660
[Amit Varma]: is picked up.

02:16:50.660 --> 02:16:54.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'll also think about on a couple of points, which I'll make to that.

02:16:54.380 --> 02:16:58.060
[Amit Varma]: And one is that, I mean, I don't know if you've heard similar whispers, but I've heard murmurings

02:16:58.060 --> 02:17:02.300
[Amit Varma]: from the corridors of power that, you know, there's a bit of a rift forming between Modi

02:17:02.300 --> 02:17:07.100
[Amit Varma]: and Shah, because Modi really cares about his image, especially to foreigners.

02:17:07.100 --> 02:17:11.180
[Amit Varma]: And he's a little pissed off that so many of the things Shah does with the home ministries,

02:17:11.180 --> 02:17:14.500
[Amit Varma]: CAA onwards, is hurting his image abroad.

02:17:14.500 --> 02:17:19.420
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I don't think Modi really listens to Rihanna while he's out doing yoga.

02:17:19.420 --> 02:17:25.040
[Amit Varma]: But those kinds of tweets cannot be something that he would not consider avoidable.

02:17:25.040 --> 02:17:28.260
[Amit Varma]: So you know, so maybe there's a ray of light there.

02:17:28.260 --> 02:17:31.520
[Amit Varma]: But then, you know, I look back at the mandate he got in 2014, he could have done pretty

02:17:31.520 --> 02:17:32.620
[Amit Varma]: much anything then.

02:17:32.620 --> 02:17:33.620
[Amit Varma]: And what did he do?

02:17:33.620 --> 02:17:37.660
[Amit Varma]: He did demonetization, which, as I will say, for the hundredth time on the show is the

02:17:37.660 --> 02:17:40.460
[Amit Varma]: largest assault on property rights in human history.

02:17:40.460 --> 02:17:46.220
[Amit Varma]: But my other reaction to what you said was that, let us say that he gets all of this,

02:17:46.220 --> 02:17:52.040
[Amit Varma]: he gets that, okay, I got the mandate, I am the greatest politician, I am the election

02:17:52.040 --> 02:17:57.780
[Amit Varma]: overlord or the election OG, as it were, now the question is, I want to leave a legacy.

02:17:57.780 --> 02:18:02.580
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, aspiration has to meet ability and ability doesn't just mean governance ability

02:18:02.580 --> 02:18:08.860
[Amit Varma]: in terms of getting things done, but also includes the vision and the intelligence and

02:18:08.860 --> 02:18:10.540
[Amit Varma]: the humility to learn.

02:18:10.540 --> 02:18:15.240
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I once wrote a column called the Aankho Dekhi Prime Minister, which was

02:18:15.240 --> 02:18:20.780
[Amit Varma]: based on an anecdote, a friend of the Prime Minister told me that she mentioned that once

02:18:20.780 --> 02:18:25.820
[Amit Varma]: about 13 years ago or something, she was, when he was in Gujarat, she was at a house

02:18:25.820 --> 02:18:27.900
[Amit Varma]: at a gathering of seven, eight people.

02:18:27.900 --> 02:18:31.900
[Amit Varma]: And Modi started telling them a story about how once his mother was very ill, and she

02:18:31.900 --> 02:18:33.040
[Amit Varma]: was feeling hot.

02:18:33.040 --> 02:18:36.900
[Amit Varma]: So he went to switch on the fan, and then he realized there was no electricity.

02:18:36.900 --> 02:18:41.780
[Amit Varma]: And from then on, he decided that, you know, if he ever is in a position of power, he'll

02:18:41.780 --> 02:18:43.980
[Amit Varma]: do something to get electricity to poor people.

02:18:43.980 --> 02:18:48.900
[Amit Varma]: And her point was that as CM of Gujarat, he did do that or try to do that whatever I mean,

02:18:48.900 --> 02:18:52.300
[Amit Varma]: I don't know what the facts on the ground are in terms of getting electricity to every

02:18:52.300 --> 02:18:53.300
[Amit Varma]: village.

02:18:53.300 --> 02:18:57.260
[Amit Varma]: And my friend's point there was that he, his view of the world is very experiential.

02:18:57.260 --> 02:19:01.260
[Amit Varma]: He's experienced the importance of electricity, he would have experienced the importance of

02:19:01.260 --> 02:19:07.420
[Amit Varma]: good roads, whatever he can experience, he can then try to do something about.

02:19:07.420 --> 02:19:12.580
[Amit Varma]: But now the point is when you beyond a certain scale beyond the scale of a neighborhood or

02:19:12.580 --> 02:19:16.660
[Amit Varma]: even a village, it's not just about what you experience when you're running a country,

02:19:16.660 --> 02:19:22.540
[Amit Varma]: the whole bunch of abstract conceptual models and all are important for you to understand.

02:19:22.540 --> 02:19:25.780
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the ways of getting that is through a lot of reading.

02:19:25.780 --> 02:19:30.940
[Amit Varma]: Now, obviously, he didn't have a privileged enough childhood to be someone who read a

02:19:30.940 --> 02:19:33.620
[Amit Varma]: lot of books, and one cannot hold that against him.

02:19:33.620 --> 02:19:38.660
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, what a good leader would do is, you know, have a ton of humility, surround

02:19:38.660 --> 02:19:44.620
[Amit Varma]: himself with people who know these things and, and rely on them.

02:19:44.620 --> 02:19:50.100
[Amit Varma]: And you wrote in that column in that edition of your newsletter, where you said that a

02:19:50.100 --> 02:19:54.100
[Amit Varma]: lot of his thinking when it comes to governance is system one thinking, you know, he's going

02:19:54.100 --> 02:19:57.100
[Amit Varma]: by his intuitions or his folksy wisdom.

02:19:57.100 --> 02:20:00.860
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I can see Demon would have also come from there that, oh, kaala paisa hai,

02:20:00.860 --> 02:20:06.140
[Amit Varma]: kya karne ka, let's ban the big notes without realizing that, you know, 85% of the currency

02:20:06.140 --> 02:20:07.140
[Amit Varma]: is whatever.

02:20:07.140 --> 02:20:14.180
[Amit Varma]: And, and this again brings me to the question of, you've also, you know, spoken about how

02:20:14.180 --> 02:20:18.860
[Amit Varma]: experts in the government are like lampposts, where you've said that, you know, the government

02:20:18.860 --> 02:20:24.340
[Amit Varma]: will use the experts like a drunk uses a lamppost for support and not illumination.

02:20:24.340 --> 02:20:28.340
[Amit Varma]: And I have written a column in the past, which I linked from the show notes about how, you

02:20:28.340 --> 02:20:32.540
[Amit Varma]: know, there are so many well meaning people who became in Lenin's phrase, useful idiots

02:20:32.540 --> 02:20:36.140
[Amit Varma]: for the government that they would lend their credibility and their voice because they thought,

02:20:36.140 --> 02:20:40.380
[Amit Varma]: hey, our teacher will rise within the government or we'll get some good change done or whatever,

02:20:40.380 --> 02:20:41.940
[Amit Varma]: whatever the intentions were.

02:20:41.940 --> 02:20:47.700
[Amit Varma]: But they ended up legitimizing a lot that was nonsensical, including, you know, things

02:20:47.700 --> 02:20:49.260
[Amit Varma]: like demonetization.

02:20:49.260 --> 02:20:53.340
[Amit Varma]: And in an aside, it strikes me that, you know, you're talking about Carl Schmitt earlier.

02:20:53.340 --> 02:20:57.780
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, Carl Schmitt was also a similarly useful idiot for Hitler.

02:20:57.780 --> 02:21:02.380
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, was attacked from within also in 1936 from within the Nazi Party for, you

02:21:02.380 --> 02:21:05.220
[Amit Varma]: know, not being sincere enough and being exactly that.

02:21:05.220 --> 02:21:10.860
[Amit Varma]: So what's your take on this kind of landscape that we have seen, where all the experts who

02:21:10.860 --> 02:21:16.380
[Amit Varma]: remain are basically, you know, I don't want to use a pejorative on the show, and I can't

02:21:16.380 --> 02:21:19.460
[Amit Varma]: think of anything else when it comes to describing them.

02:21:19.460 --> 02:21:23.220
[Guest]: I think there are, I mean, let's take the optimistic scenario.

02:21:23.220 --> 02:21:26.540
[Guest]: And then let's take the pessimistic scenario here.

02:21:26.540 --> 02:21:34.860
[Guest]: I think for where we are, in terms of, you know, economic growth, and I don't think that

02:21:34.860 --> 02:21:43.940
[Guest]: you need very sharp, deeply felt, deeply thought, you know, economic sort of decision making

02:21:43.940 --> 02:21:44.940
[Unknown]: instincts.

02:21:44.940 --> 02:21:51.420
[Guest]: We have very basic, you know, things that we have to get right.

02:21:51.420 --> 02:21:58.980
[Guest]: And my view on this one is that maybe in the past, you know, some of these ideas of black

02:21:58.980 --> 02:22:03.060
[Guest]: money, etc, were manifesto driven things, then you have to do something about it.

02:22:03.060 --> 02:22:04.820
[Guest]: And maybe you chose the wrong one.

02:22:04.820 --> 02:22:11.700
[Guest]: But I mean, if you just take Infra, you take Agri, you take a few other things, I think

02:22:11.700 --> 02:22:16.940
[Guest]: the decisions here are very apparent for most people.

02:22:16.940 --> 02:22:22.660
[Guest]: I mean, we are not at that stage where we need economic thinking of the kind that is

02:22:22.660 --> 02:22:29.460
[Guest]: very nuanced, because we have a very sort of nuanced problem to address.

02:22:29.460 --> 02:22:36.020
[Guest]: So my sense is that it's more a will and a point that I would now take this and solve

02:22:36.020 --> 02:22:40.180
[Guest]: it with the simplest of sort of interventions, which I know will still be better than where

02:22:40.180 --> 02:22:41.380
[Guest]: we are today.

02:22:41.380 --> 02:22:43.260
[Guest]: I think farm laws are that kind of intervention.

02:22:43.260 --> 02:22:47.780
[Guest]: I think it's good, you know, maybe the narrative building and the consensus and everything

02:22:47.780 --> 02:22:52.680
[Guest]: around it is not something that happened in the right manner.

02:22:52.680 --> 02:22:56.260
[Guest]: So that's one optimistic sort of, you know, way of looking at this.

02:22:56.260 --> 02:22:58.260
[Guest]: I mean, and there are some parallels here, right?

02:22:58.260 --> 02:23:06.700
[Guest]: I mean, you take Regan, Regan was not, I mean, I would hazard a guess that he was not necessarily

02:23:06.700 --> 02:23:09.020
[Guest]: a guy who used to read a lot.

02:23:09.020 --> 02:23:15.060
[Guest]: I know for a fact that I, you know, I did an interview of one of his sort of guys who

02:23:15.060 --> 02:23:19.940
[Guest]: was his, I think, press secretary or someone, used to watch a movie every Friday evening

02:23:19.940 --> 02:23:22.460
[Guest]: with Nancy Reagan at the White House.

02:23:22.460 --> 02:23:27.540
[Guest]: I think that was what he used to do very regularly, but I don't think so, he read a lot.

02:23:27.540 --> 02:23:33.820
[Guest]: Now, you might argue that he had maybe a, you know, a Milton Friedman and, you know,

02:23:33.820 --> 02:23:42.820
[Guest]: the entire Friedman sort of, you know, whatever, Rat Pack, which supported and gave an intellectual,

02:23:42.820 --> 02:23:48.940
[Guest]: you know, sort of foundation and structure to what he was planning to do.

02:23:48.940 --> 02:23:54.300
[Guest]: And he followed it to the T. Now, is that something that is lacking in India?

02:23:54.300 --> 02:23:59.660
[Guest]: I would say that if you look at it very conventionally and, you know, you take the fact that, okay,

02:23:59.660 --> 02:24:05.540
[Guest]: the right kind of intellectual support should come from a certain kind of universities,

02:24:05.540 --> 02:24:08.460
[Guest]: a certain kind of background, it's not there.

02:24:08.460 --> 02:24:13.500
[Guest]: But again, my question is, if you keep some of these things simple, you will still achieve

02:24:13.500 --> 02:24:14.500
[Guest]: a lot.

02:24:14.500 --> 02:24:19.140
[Guest]: And I'm hoping that you, as long as we keep it simple and we do the smaller things, the

02:24:19.140 --> 02:24:20.140
[Guest]: simpler things, right?

02:24:20.140 --> 02:24:23.540
[Guest]: I think we can achieve still a lot of lot in the next five, 10 years, instead of trying

02:24:23.540 --> 02:24:25.700
[Guest]: to do the more complex things.

02:24:25.700 --> 02:24:29.500
[Guest]: The more complex things we can get there, or if you leave them aside, they will sort

02:24:29.500 --> 02:24:30.500
[Guest]: themselves out.

02:24:30.500 --> 02:24:40.700
[Guest]: I mean, so I still believe just Infra and Agri are too big enough agenda to take care

02:24:40.700 --> 02:24:42.100
[Guest]: of next five, seven years of India.

02:24:42.100 --> 02:24:46.300
[Guest]: I mean, if you sort them in the right manner, and then you don't shoot yourself in foot

02:24:46.300 --> 02:24:52.740
[Guest]: with some completely crazy out of the park or whatever, out of the left field idea like

02:24:52.740 --> 02:24:58.980
[Guest]: demon or something, and you just do two or three things right, because all other forces

02:24:58.980 --> 02:25:06.900
[Guest]: of digital and data revolution and things of that kind are anyway supporting some of

02:25:06.900 --> 02:25:12.500
[Guest]: these broader sort of trends of people getting into the mainstream, getting into formal economy

02:25:12.500 --> 02:25:14.540
[Guest]: and things of that kind.

02:25:14.540 --> 02:25:21.900
[Guest]: So I'm hoping again here that if you just focus on a few small important things, which

02:25:21.900 --> 02:25:26.420
[Guest]: are simple enough for everyone to understand and do, we'll still achieve a lot in the next

02:25:26.420 --> 02:25:27.420
[Guest]: five years.

02:25:27.420 --> 02:25:30.060
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's kind of a good point.

02:25:30.060 --> 02:25:34.340
[Amit Varma]: And aside on Reagan, I think at least Reagan's instincts were wonderful, they came from the

02:25:34.340 --> 02:25:35.340
[Amit Varma]: right place.

02:25:35.340 --> 02:25:40.060
[Amit Varma]: I'm not sure Modi's instincts are necessarily like that, that they're even coherent or consistent.

02:25:40.060 --> 02:25:44.500
[Amit Varma]: And equally, you look at the other transformative figure of that times, Margaret Thatcher, that

02:25:44.500 --> 02:25:50.140
[Amit Varma]: in her first cabinet meeting as Prime Minister, apparently, she put a book by Hayek, I think

02:25:50.140 --> 02:25:53.300
[Amit Varma]: it was a constitution of liberty, I forget which one, put a book by Hayek on the table

02:25:53.300 --> 02:25:58.100
[Amit Varma]: and said, this is going to be what is going to guide us in the next few years.

02:25:58.100 --> 02:26:01.820
[Amit Varma]: And of course, may not have been entirely consistent with that there is a political

02:26:01.820 --> 02:26:06.620
[Amit Varma]: economy, but starting with at least the right framework, while I'm not sure that's even

02:26:06.620 --> 02:26:10.740
[Amit Varma]: there in Modi's case, I mean, my sense in Modi's case is all the good things that he

02:26:10.740 --> 02:26:15.920
[Amit Varma]: said like, you know, minimum government, maximum governance, the kind of stuff that we could

02:26:15.920 --> 02:26:18.380
[Amit Varma]: agree with was not some core conviction.

02:26:18.380 --> 02:26:22.820
[Amit Varma]: These were lines given to him by one group of intellectuals, he thought he wanted on

02:26:22.820 --> 02:26:23.820
[Amit Varma]: his side.

02:26:23.820 --> 02:26:28.340
[Amit Varma]: So he just kind of said it if he, you know, if I think his actions would have been very

02:26:28.340 --> 02:26:32.260
[Amit Varma]: different if his convictions were anywhere near there.

02:26:32.260 --> 02:26:36.780
[Amit Varma]: And as far as the farm bills are concerned, I had an episode with Ajay Shah on it recently.

02:26:36.780 --> 02:26:43.300
[Amit Varma]: And there is also, I guess, a fundamental sort of tragedy in the sense that, you know,

02:26:43.300 --> 02:26:47.180
[Amit Varma]: both Ajay and I agreed that there is a lot about these farm bills, which is great, which

02:26:47.180 --> 02:26:51.500
[Amit Varma]: will help farmers, which all the parties have had on the agenda before, which all experts

02:26:51.500 --> 02:26:54.780
[Amit Varma]: agree will, you know, make a big difference.

02:26:54.780 --> 02:26:58.700
[Amit Varma]: You know, given how the status quo has performed, it's almost criminal to support it after what

02:26:58.700 --> 02:27:00.940
[Amit Varma]: it has done to farmers for seven decades.

02:27:00.940 --> 02:27:06.180
[Amit Varma]: And yet the Modi government messed it up completely in terms of not building consensus, you know,

02:27:06.180 --> 02:27:10.620
[Amit Varma]: not seeing the unintended consequences of it, like, you know, you and Pranay have written

02:27:10.620 --> 02:27:19.060
[Amit Varma]: about at length in your newsletter, and that kind of felt sort of a little tragic in the

02:27:19.060 --> 02:27:22.940
[Amit Varma]: ways played out because they've just handled it really badly, this painting of the farmers

02:27:22.940 --> 02:27:27.980
[Amit Varma]: as anti-national and bringing in Khalistan into this and all this nonsense about it's

02:27:27.980 --> 02:27:30.700
[Amit Varma]: a conspiracy against India.

02:27:30.700 --> 02:27:37.460
[Amit Varma]: And you kind of wonder that, you know, even if good economics is accompanied by bad politics

02:27:37.460 --> 02:27:43.100
[Amit Varma]: of this sort, and it fails because of that reason, you know, it'll kind of be tragic.

02:27:43.100 --> 02:27:47.180
[Amit Varma]: But like you pointed out, yeah, I mean, thinking about it, there are a certain set of reforms

02:27:47.180 --> 02:27:51.660
[Amit Varma]: which should not be rocket science and should be doable.

02:27:51.660 --> 02:27:56.580
[Amit Varma]: But there will be opposition to it for the sake of opposition anyway, right?

02:27:56.580 --> 02:28:00.740
[Amit Varma]: Like privatizations, for example, you know, things that the opposition would have put

02:28:00.740 --> 02:28:06.500
[Amit Varma]: in the manifesto, but if the Modi government does it, they will oppose it and, you know,

02:28:06.500 --> 02:28:07.500
[Amit Varma]: mobilize against it.

02:28:07.500 --> 02:28:09.500
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, what does one do?

02:28:09.500 --> 02:28:15.540
[Guest]: Yeah, but I think the only good part here is that the power of narrative is with them.

02:28:15.540 --> 02:28:20.420
[Guest]: So I mean, if used in, which is what my point remains that if you handle it well, this can

02:28:20.420 --> 02:28:22.060
[Guest]: be quite transformational.

02:28:22.060 --> 02:28:27.460
[Guest]: And I'm still hoping that when some of these things that you have sought to achieve from

02:28:27.460 --> 02:28:33.300
[Guest]: a political perspective, those ends are met, all the final frontiers are, you know, finally

02:28:33.300 --> 02:28:35.300
[Guest]: done and dusted with.

02:28:35.300 --> 02:28:41.900
[Guest]: And I think that we are possibly at the homestretch of some of those political ends and then hopefully,

02:28:41.900 --> 02:28:48.020
[Guest]: you know, you will get some action happening on the, on the, on the, on in the areas that

02:28:48.020 --> 02:28:50.460
[Guest]: all of us want the action to happen.

02:28:50.460 --> 02:28:51.460
[Guest]: That's the hope.

02:28:51.460 --> 02:28:55.620
[Guest]: But otherwise, you know, you will, you will not, you will not, you know, sort of start

02:28:55.620 --> 02:29:01.060
[Guest]: the day or end the day well, based on the news cycle that's around you.

02:29:01.060 --> 02:29:02.060
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:29:02.060 --> 02:29:06.980
[Amit Varma]: And it's honestly not only Modi's will that comes into play, the mindset of the bureaucracy

02:29:06.980 --> 02:29:10.940
[Amit Varma]: and the Indian state, the deep state, as it were, the inertia that's built into the system

02:29:10.940 --> 02:29:12.500
[Amit Varma]: comes into play as well.

02:29:12.500 --> 02:29:18.020
[Amit Varma]: And I'll quote another sort of lovely passage from you, which is from edition 25, where

02:29:18.020 --> 02:29:22.100
[Amit Varma]: you write quote, the default mental model of the economy among the executive and the

02:29:22.100 --> 02:29:27.300
[Amit Varma]: legislature is that of a giant planning machine, where you plan for a certain volume of output,

02:29:27.300 --> 02:29:32.100
[Amit Varma]: say motorbikes, and you derive a specific volume of inputs, steel, tires, plastics,

02:29:32.100 --> 02:29:33.700
[Amit Varma]: et cetera, that you must produce.

02:29:33.700 --> 02:29:35.260
[Amit Varma]: You do this for each industry.

02:29:35.260 --> 02:29:38.580
[Amit Varma]: And the planning algorithm will give you a complete picture of what every sector must

02:29:38.580 --> 02:29:39.820
[Amit Varma]: produce every year.

02:29:39.820 --> 02:29:44.100
[Amit Varma]: Granted, the reality has changed a bit over the years, but the schema is planted deep

02:29:44.100 --> 02:29:45.100
[Amit Varma]: in the minds.

02:29:45.100 --> 02:29:50.620
[Amit Varma]: This is a PC Mahalanobis model, a variant of the Leontief input output model overseeing

02:29:50.620 --> 02:29:53.060
[Amit Varma]: this is a grand vizier of central planning.

02:29:53.060 --> 02:29:55.380
[Amit Varma]: The simplest gauge of efficiency of this model.

02:29:55.380 --> 02:30:00.220
[Amit Varma]: Well, my dad booked a scooter when I was born, and we got it delivered when I was in class

02:30:00.220 --> 02:30:01.220
[Amit Varma]: seven.

02:30:01.220 --> 02:30:04.300
[Amit Varma]: We got our lessons and virtues of patience early in life.

02:30:04.300 --> 02:30:05.300
[Amit Varma]: Stop good.

02:30:05.300 --> 02:30:09.380
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when young people ask me about what was the benefit of liberalization, and

02:30:09.380 --> 02:30:12.780
[Amit Varma]: the thing is, I just remembered that, you know, back in the day, you had to wait like

02:30:12.780 --> 02:30:17.780
[Amit Varma]: wait seven, eight years to get a freaking telephone, you know, it was, and today you

02:30:17.780 --> 02:30:22.860
[Amit Varma]: see how accessible that is all the sectors that were liberalized, like, you know, telecom

02:30:22.860 --> 02:30:26.860
[Amit Varma]: or airlines or whatever have become so much more accessible than they were.

02:30:26.860 --> 02:30:33.100
[Amit Varma]: And there is scope for even more kindly reduced taxes on aviation fuel, dear government, and

02:30:33.100 --> 02:30:38.380
[Amit Varma]: the sectors that weren't liberalized, like agriculture and education, continue to be

02:30:38.380 --> 02:30:41.060
[Amit Varma]: our sort of problem areas.

02:30:41.060 --> 02:30:45.900
[Amit Varma]: But broadly, you know, when we speak about this mindset, specifically, you spoke about

02:30:45.900 --> 02:30:50.260
[Amit Varma]: the default mental model of the economy among the executive and the legislature.

02:30:50.260 --> 02:30:58.300
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, is this something that you feel is changing has changed even if you because,

02:30:58.300 --> 02:31:01.380
[Amit Varma]: you know, it's going to take a long, long time, it's a decades long play to be able

02:31:01.380 --> 02:31:04.860
[Amit Varma]: to change it sufficiently in the demand end of the political marketplace.

02:31:04.860 --> 02:31:09.100
[Amit Varma]: Certainly, many of these are unintuitive, or do you feel that there is that mindset

02:31:09.100 --> 02:31:10.860
[Guest]: change that is happening?

02:31:10.860 --> 02:31:17.020
[Guest]: I think I really believe and I hope also that it should come true.

02:31:17.020 --> 02:31:23.940
[Guest]: But based on some of my empirical evidence of this, I mean, there is a generation of,

02:31:23.940 --> 02:31:32.380
[Guest]: you know, bureaucrats who are now the liberalization generation, who are there now in the bureaucracy.

02:31:32.380 --> 02:31:38.380
[Guest]: And you know, I don't think they, I mean, of course, the system can always, you know,

02:31:38.380 --> 02:31:40.980
[Guest]: change you into becoming that.

02:31:40.980 --> 02:31:48.380
[Guest]: But I think in the past, both the system as well as your instincts going in were the same.

02:31:48.380 --> 02:31:53.100
[Guest]: And therefore, you know, there was no, absolutely no opportunity for you to go in and then change

02:31:53.100 --> 02:31:54.100
[Guest]: the system.

02:31:54.100 --> 02:31:55.100
[Guest]: Because for what?

02:31:55.100 --> 02:31:56.540
[Guest]: I mean, you have not, there is no dissonance in your mind.

02:31:56.540 --> 02:32:00.660
[Guest]: This is what I was taught, this is how I lived and this is what I'm seeing here.

02:32:00.660 --> 02:32:07.060
[Guest]: But I think now there is a whole generation of, you know, I think bureaucrats and other

02:32:07.060 --> 02:32:13.020
[Guest]: people within the state machinery who have seen something different.

02:32:13.020 --> 02:32:17.220
[Guest]: And also the fact that, you know, just because of the liberalization, people have traveled

02:32:17.220 --> 02:32:21.340
[Guest]: out, your brother, your cousin, somebody is there outside, they come, you go to other

02:32:21.340 --> 02:32:22.340
[Guest]: places.

02:32:22.340 --> 02:32:27.980
[Guest]: I think in that sense, I believe that, you know, let's take, I mean, who in the sense

02:32:27.980 --> 02:32:33.060
[Guest]: the secretaries in various departments of the government today might be, you know, closer

02:32:33.060 --> 02:32:34.060
[Guest]: to 60 now.

02:32:34.060 --> 02:32:38.820
[Guest]: So these are all born in 1960s, you know, early to mid 60s.

02:32:38.820 --> 02:32:45.780
[Guest]: And they, by the time they entered the administration, you know, the bureaucracy, they had already,

02:32:45.780 --> 02:32:49.860
[Guest]: you know, been steeped in the previous sort of thing because you, they would have grown

02:32:49.860 --> 02:32:53.780
[Guest]: up in 70s and then in 80s, they must have joined the machinery.

02:32:53.780 --> 02:32:57.100
[Guest]: Then they would have seen some change around them, but you know, it's very difficult to

02:32:57.100 --> 02:32:59.780
[Guest]: change some of the original mental models.

02:32:59.780 --> 02:33:04.820
[Guest]: But even 10 years later, those who must have gone, must have been people like us, right?

02:33:04.820 --> 02:33:09.340
[Guest]: You know, you, you saw one part of your life in that model and then you saw the very, very

02:33:09.340 --> 02:33:15.060
[Guest]: different one and they might, might have entered civil services in mid to late 90s.

02:33:15.060 --> 02:33:21.100
[Guest]: So I'm hoping that even though the system is going to be sort of still supporting a

02:33:21.100 --> 02:33:27.260
[Guest]: grand planning, you know, kind of a, you know, model, many of them would have the instinct

02:33:27.260 --> 02:33:30.100
[Guest]: that something of this kind is possibly not necessary.

02:33:30.100 --> 02:33:33.020
[Guest]: I mean, it's too much of overplanning.

02:33:33.020 --> 02:33:40.940
[Guest]: And I also feel that there are mechanisms now of, and I think I have heard and seen

02:33:40.940 --> 02:33:46.780
[Guest]: many of these bureaucrats go to, you know, foreign universities, do six month courses,

02:33:46.780 --> 02:33:49.380
[Guest]: one year courses on public policy and things of that kind.

02:33:49.380 --> 02:33:56.100
[Guest]: I think some of those things should bear fruit, in my opinion, and, and, you know, I hope

02:33:56.100 --> 02:34:03.220
[Guest]: that we get to see some of that in, in, in practice, although I'm very, I have very limited

02:34:03.220 --> 02:34:07.660
[Guest]: interaction with many of the, some of these machineries, I have no clue whether that is

02:34:07.660 --> 02:34:15.220
[Guest]: truly happening or not, but I would suspect that some of this should be coming up in terms

02:34:15.220 --> 02:34:20.500
[Guest]: of, you know, the change in the mindset over the next decade, when many of these guys will

02:34:20.500 --> 02:34:24.740
[Guest]: become joint secretaries and secretaries of various departments.

02:34:24.740 --> 02:34:26.300
[Amit Varma]: Brilliant.

