[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:37:58.660 --> 02:37:59.660
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:37:59.660 --> 02:38:00.820
[Amit Varma]: So basically a Hindi film passes the test.

02:38:00.820 --> 02:38:05.400
[Amit Varma]: If it has, or rather a Hindi film passes the Raghu Sanjay Lal Jaitley test.

02:38:05.400 --> 02:38:10.660
[Amit Varma]: If it has two or more characters drinking without one, anyone nursing a heartbreak,

02:38:10.660 --> 02:38:15.820
[Amit Varma]: two, planning or doing something illegal, three, singing or dancing, a stop code.

02:38:15.820 --> 02:38:16.820
[Amit Varma]: So elaborate.

02:38:16.820 --> 02:38:23.980
[Guest]: I mean, I think this is, I think the broader point remains one of my favorite sort of areas

02:38:23.980 --> 02:38:31.660
[Guest]: to constantly have this sort of conversation and writing is about morality and society.

02:38:31.660 --> 02:38:37.020
[Guest]: And my view is, I think maybe in the last 10 years, there might be a few films that

02:38:37.020 --> 02:38:46.940
[Guest]: might possibly pass this test, but I think pre 2010, the answer to this test is zero.

02:38:46.940 --> 02:38:54.400
[Guest]: You would find hardly any films because for some strange reason, we just cannot show the

02:38:54.400 --> 02:39:01.060
[Guest]: idea that people can have, you know, can have fun with or whatever can indulge in what can

02:39:01.060 --> 02:39:08.780
[Guest]: be just considered as mild vices, you know, and without, you know, getting everything

02:39:08.780 --> 02:39:09.780
[Guest]: in twist.

02:39:09.780 --> 02:39:10.780
[Guest]: Right.

02:39:10.780 --> 02:39:17.340
[Guest]: I mean, so, and the idea, I think this particular post was around consumption being a public

02:39:17.340 --> 02:39:18.340
[Guest]: benefit.

02:39:18.340 --> 02:39:25.060
[Guest]: I think that was the post where this comes from, but yeah, that's the, that's the thing.

02:39:25.060 --> 02:39:29.220
[Guest]: I think only in the last 10 years, I think I've seen a few films where, you know, you

02:39:29.220 --> 02:39:33.700
[Guest]: can see people just having a drink without doing, without going through one of these

02:39:33.700 --> 02:39:36.260
[Guest]: three sort of life situations.

02:39:36.260 --> 02:39:37.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:39:37.260 --> 02:39:41.700
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, you know, since I would, you know, since you want me to disagree with you somewhere

02:39:41.700 --> 02:39:46.580
[Amit Varma]: or the other, I would actually say that while I agree with the conclusions that you come

02:39:46.580 --> 02:39:51.620
[Amit Varma]: up with about the role of morality and society and all, this particular test is a bit of

02:39:51.620 --> 02:39:55.780
[Amit Varma]: an issue for me because there is something in art called Shekhov's gun, where the great

02:39:55.780 --> 02:40:01.540
[Amit Varma]: short story writer Anton Shekhov said that if you show a gun in the first scene of your

02:40:01.540 --> 02:40:06.220
[Amit Varma]: story, it has to go off by at some point in the story, otherwise, what is it doing there?

02:40:06.220 --> 02:40:10.300
[Amit Varma]: So you could similarly argue that filmmakers and writers might take the Shekhov's gun approach

02:40:10.300 --> 02:40:14.820
[Amit Varma]: to alcohol and say that, listen, if you show alcohol, it has to lead to heartbreak or it

02:40:14.820 --> 02:40:16.940
[Amit Varma]: has to be there for a reason.

02:40:16.940 --> 02:40:21.220
[Amit Varma]: And I remember a long time back, someone similarly making an observation that in the movies,

02:40:21.220 --> 02:40:24.100
[Amit Varma]: you never see someone going to the toilet, like, don't they have to go to the toilet

02:40:24.100 --> 02:40:29.220
[Amit Varma]: in movies, which, but I don't think there's any larger philosophical point or observation

02:40:29.220 --> 02:40:34.700
[Amit Varma]: about society that can emerge from that specific thing.

02:40:34.700 --> 02:40:40.340
[Amit Varma]: And one of the nuggets that came up in this particular edition about drinking was that,

02:40:40.340 --> 02:40:45.340
[Amit Varma]: and I'll quote it, where you write, quote, a study by Pehle India Foundation found a

02:40:45.340 --> 02:40:51.700
[Amit Varma]: manufacturer needs about 10,900 certificates or licenses from various agencies to operate

02:40:51.700 --> 02:40:54.660
[Amit Varma]: a plant in Maharashtra, stop quote.

02:40:54.660 --> 02:41:00.260
[Amit Varma]: And your quote is actually incomplete, because the word that you took out from it was annually.

02:41:00.260 --> 02:41:05.100
[Amit Varma]: So it's not that you get 10,900 licenses, once and you are done, you can run your plant,

02:41:05.100 --> 02:41:07.540
[Amit Varma]: you have to get them every freaking year.

02:41:07.540 --> 02:41:11.900
[Amit Varma]: And I'd done an episode with a friend on restaurant regulations, and he was a restauranteur.

02:41:11.900 --> 02:41:17.060
[Amit Varma]: And he once told me about these two sort of, I mean, plethora of regulations, but there

02:41:17.060 --> 02:41:22.860
[Amit Varma]: was one regulation from the excise department that there can only be one entry to your restaurant.

02:41:22.860 --> 02:41:26.780
[Amit Varma]: So they can sort of monitor the entry of alcohol.

02:41:26.780 --> 02:41:31.060
[Amit Varma]: And another regulation which said that from the fire department, which said that for safety

02:41:31.060 --> 02:41:33.540
[Amit Varma]: reasons, there must be multiple entrances.

02:41:33.540 --> 02:41:37.500
[Amit Varma]: So the thing is, whatever you do, you are on the wrong side of the law.

02:41:37.500 --> 02:41:42.420
[Amit Varma]: And actually, it is irrelevant, because you're bribing both people anyway, along with 40

02:41:42.420 --> 02:41:48.740
[Amit Varma]: other people for 40 other licenses, which brings me to another Bollywood film, which

02:41:48.740 --> 02:41:55.380
[Amit Varma]: is the famous Kalyug, you know, Shyam Benegal's brilliant version of the Mahabharata, and

02:41:55.380 --> 02:41:59.740
[Amit Varma]: which is a film with a lot of Rajas, but one Raj is dominant over the others, which is

02:41:59.740 --> 02:42:01.420
[Amit Varma]: relevant to what we were just talking about.

02:42:01.420 --> 02:42:02.420
[Amit Varma]: So this is not out of nowhere.

02:42:02.420 --> 02:42:04.820
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about those different Rajas.

02:42:04.820 --> 02:42:12.460
[Guest]: Yeah, so this, so, you know, Kalyug is Benegal's take on the Mahabharata, outstanding film.

02:42:12.460 --> 02:42:19.540
[Guest]: And the, you know, so it's Mahabharata set in early 80s, in a business family, and pretty

02:42:19.540 --> 02:42:24.140
[Guest]: much follows the script, right, there is a, you know, there are two brothers and they

02:42:24.140 --> 02:42:29.900
[Guest]: have their kids and you know, the empire is split between the two and so on and so forth.

02:42:29.900 --> 02:42:34.860
[Guest]: And what, what Benegal does is he gives them interesting names.

02:42:34.860 --> 02:42:39.900
[Guest]: So the, you know, the Raj Babbar is, I guess, Yudhishthir is Dharam Raj.

02:42:39.900 --> 02:42:47.460
[Guest]: And, you know, Kulbhushan Kharbanda is, I think, Bheem and he's some other Raj, I forget

02:42:47.460 --> 02:42:49.100
[Guest]: now.

02:42:49.100 --> 02:42:51.300
[Guest]: So there are three, four Rajas.

02:42:51.300 --> 02:42:55.540
[Guest]: And my point is, when I saw the film, and I saw the film when I was quite young, but

02:42:55.540 --> 02:42:58.780
[Guest]: it's more a retrospective sort of view about the film.

02:42:58.780 --> 02:43:04.460
[Guest]: My point is, or there are four or five Rajas in the film, but the real Raj that dominates

02:43:04.460 --> 02:43:12.740
[Guest]: the film script is the, is the License Permit Raj, because on the back of License Permit

02:43:12.740 --> 02:43:18.500
[Guest]: Raj is what the, you know, the whole sort of the story turns and instead of Hastinapur

02:43:18.500 --> 02:43:23.580
[Guest]: and you know, that one sort of split, you want only five villages or whatever that,

02:43:23.580 --> 02:43:27.820
[Guest]: you know, the reason for which many people went to war in Mahabharata, it is actually

02:43:27.820 --> 02:43:30.860
[Guest]: on the license that people went to war in Kanyu.

02:43:30.860 --> 02:43:36.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, for those of my sort of readers who want to read it, this was edition number 26,

02:43:36.500 --> 02:43:40.980
[Amit Varma]: newsletter 26 of Anticipating the Unintended.

02:43:40.980 --> 02:43:47.260
[Amit Varma]: And let's kind of talk a little bit about, you know, we often, I think at the start of

02:43:47.260 --> 02:43:52.940
[Amit Varma]: the episode, I alluded to how we tend to kind of forget our history and where we came from.

02:43:52.940 --> 02:43:57.420
[Amit Varma]: And I often assume when I'm talking to people that my sort of shared experience of living

02:43:57.420 --> 02:44:02.100
[Amit Varma]: in those times, growing up in pre-liberalization India, the License Raj times, and sometimes

02:44:02.100 --> 02:44:09.020
[Amit Varma]: it's kind of worth full to, you know, remind people that that's not necessarily the case.

02:44:09.020 --> 02:44:13.660
[Amit Varma]: And the License Permit Raj is really the biggest villain of all, bigger than anyone else in

02:44:13.660 --> 02:44:14.820
[Amit Varma]: the Mahabharata.

02:44:14.820 --> 02:44:22.740
[Amit Varma]: And tell me a bit about how it sort of shaped behavior and incentives and our economy, kind

02:44:22.740 --> 02:44:27.260
[Amit Varma]: of through the decades, like what was the fundamental problem with it, and you've described

02:44:27.260 --> 02:44:29.580
[Amit Varma]: a few of them in this edition, of course.

02:44:29.580 --> 02:44:30.580
[Guest]: Right.

02:44:30.580 --> 02:44:41.140
[Guest]: So I think, I mean, the idea really was that the state believed as a central planner that,

02:44:41.140 --> 02:44:44.660
[Guest]: you know, this is what we need.

02:44:44.660 --> 02:44:49.620
[Guest]: And you had this matrix based on which you realize that this is the output.

02:44:49.620 --> 02:44:53.700
[Guest]: And based on this output, these are the numbers of things that you might need.

02:44:53.700 --> 02:45:00.700
[Guest]: And then you went out and, you know, made sure that people got licensed to manufacture

02:45:00.700 --> 02:45:07.100
[Guest]: only that many of those pieces that you, that you decided that they should make.

02:45:07.100 --> 02:45:12.300
[Guest]: Now, why only that many, you know, there are multiple reasons for it.

02:45:12.300 --> 02:45:17.940
[Guest]: I think the chief among that reason was that you believed, I mean, the state believed that

02:45:17.940 --> 02:45:20.660
[Guest]: we will have to make sure that there is no monopoly.

02:45:20.660 --> 02:45:25.740
[Guest]: I mean, there were all kinds of restrictive trade practices act, there was suspicion that

02:45:25.740 --> 02:45:29.940
[Guest]: people would make too much of profit and profit here out of it.

02:45:29.940 --> 02:45:37.020
[Guest]: So the way it worked was every sort of business group got a certain license to make a certain

02:45:37.020 --> 02:45:42.780
[Guest]: number and then somebody would come in and actually inspect that that's exactly the number

02:45:42.780 --> 02:45:44.620
[Guest]: that you made.

02:45:44.620 --> 02:45:49.700
[Guest]: And as you would realize that, you know, while trying to do this kind of control, there was

02:45:49.700 --> 02:45:55.860
[Guest]: no incentive for the manufacturer to look for scale, scale advantages, you know, do

02:45:55.860 --> 02:45:57.860
[Guest]: better quality stuff, because what's the point?

02:45:57.860 --> 02:46:00.660
[Guest]: I mean, you, you are only making that many things.

02:46:00.660 --> 02:46:04.980
[Guest]: There'll be a price for that because there is always going to be, you know, artificial,

02:46:04.980 --> 02:46:10.500
[Guest]: you know, supply constraint and you will make your normal sort of profit out of that.

02:46:10.500 --> 02:46:15.020
[Guest]: Instead what all the businesses did was they kept diversifying.

02:46:15.020 --> 02:46:19.100
[Guest]: So it was completely inefficient allocation of capital instead of, you know, building

02:46:19.100 --> 02:46:23.380
[Guest]: scale, competing, making sure that you are making world class products and then going

02:46:23.380 --> 02:46:25.940
[Guest]: out and fighting in global markets.

02:46:25.940 --> 02:46:31.660
[Guest]: All you were doing was trying to get license for the next industry because you had exhausted

02:46:31.660 --> 02:46:33.260
[Guest]: your licenses on this.

02:46:33.260 --> 02:46:39.180
[Guest]: And now maybe the next industry was not as sort of, you were not as good in the other

02:46:39.180 --> 02:46:41.180
[Guest]: industry as you were in this one.

02:46:41.180 --> 02:46:44.860
[Guest]: And that industry needed completely different skills and different business acumen and things

02:46:44.860 --> 02:46:46.300
[Guest]: of that kind.

02:46:46.300 --> 02:46:49.860
[Guest]: But you know, the capital allocation used to happen on the back of that.

02:46:49.860 --> 02:46:56.060
[Guest]: So the number of ways this actually was bad for the economy is just mind blowing.

02:46:56.060 --> 02:47:01.820
[Guest]: I mean, you know, it's, it's like, basically you write an economics book and then write

02:47:01.820 --> 02:47:04.300
[Guest]: exactly opposite of everything that you should be doing.

02:47:04.300 --> 02:47:11.180
[Guest]: The license permit is that there is no supply demand, you know, price is not a signal, there

02:47:11.180 --> 02:47:16.580
[Guest]: is no real competition, allocation of capital is inefficient, you know, diversification

02:47:16.580 --> 02:47:24.340
[Guest]: of mindless kind, which actually threatens core businesses, no ability to compete in

02:47:24.340 --> 02:47:25.900
[Guest]: market beyond India.

02:47:25.900 --> 02:47:30.860
[Guest]: I think it's just, it's still remarkable that some business houses actually, you know, one

02:47:30.860 --> 02:47:34.260
[Guest]: is some of them thrived because you had to play the license game and you had to play

02:47:34.260 --> 02:47:36.700
[Guest]: the government and the state.

02:47:36.700 --> 02:47:42.220
[Guest]: But even then, once you got the license, the fact that business houses still survive and

02:47:42.220 --> 02:47:46.980
[Guest]: saw through that itself, I find is quite a testimony to the resilience of some of these

02:47:46.980 --> 02:47:47.980
[Guest]: business houses.

02:47:47.980 --> 02:47:49.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, it's quite mind blowing.

02:47:49.540 --> 02:47:53.140
[Amit Varma]: And you know, another consequence of this is that we couldn't develop world class companies

02:47:53.140 --> 02:47:57.580
[Amit Varma]: because how do you become world class, you need scale, you need to specialize and neither

02:47:57.580 --> 02:48:03.100
[Amit Varma]: of these two things were sort of possible within this system.

02:48:03.100 --> 02:48:09.500
[Amit Varma]: So you know, this kind of, there are two aspects of sort of the mindset that is prevalent in

02:48:09.500 --> 02:48:16.100
[Amit Varma]: India today, which I sometimes speculate came from this era and the way our institutions

02:48:16.100 --> 02:48:17.380
[Amit Varma]: were designed.

02:48:17.380 --> 02:48:21.380
[Amit Varma]: And one aspect is, of course, rent seeking rather than profit seeking, which is something

02:48:21.380 --> 02:48:26.400
[Amit Varma]: I've spoken about in this podcast various times before that, you know, Bhagwati had

02:48:26.400 --> 02:48:30.780
[Amit Varma]: pointed out that, you know, while Chinese have more of a profit seeking mindset, the

02:48:30.780 --> 02:48:32.420
[Amit Varma]: Indians are more of a rent seeking mindset.

02:48:32.420 --> 02:48:33.420
[Amit Varma]: What do we mean by that?

02:48:33.420 --> 02:48:39.360
[Amit Varma]: Rent seeking essentially means where you use the coercive power of the state to capture

02:48:39.360 --> 02:48:44.620
[Amit Varma]: some part of the market as it were, which you can do by being part of the state and,

02:48:44.620 --> 02:48:46.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, and extract rent out of that.

02:48:46.840 --> 02:48:51.340
[Amit Varma]: And our mindset somehow has become one of key, how can we exploit others?

02:48:51.340 --> 02:48:56.480
[Amit Varma]: How can we scam others instead of thinking in sort of a positive some way that what can

02:48:56.480 --> 02:49:00.900
[Amit Varma]: I do that creates value for others and I can make a profit out of that, which is how you

02:49:00.900 --> 02:49:03.380
[Amit Varma]: should logically think in a free market.

02:49:03.380 --> 02:49:07.300
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing that strikes me is that this cultural distrust of markets that we

02:49:07.300 --> 02:49:12.780
[Amit Varma]: have, which has also been reflected in our popular culture through the decades, does

02:49:12.780 --> 02:49:16.620
[Amit Varma]: it have something to do with the fact that all that you saw of markets like quite apart

02:49:16.620 --> 02:49:21.220
[Amit Varma]: from the colonial hangover and the East India Company, all that you saw markets in independent

02:49:21.220 --> 02:49:26.140
[Amit Varma]: India, all that you saw of the private sector, were these cronies who are corrupt and connected

02:49:26.140 --> 02:49:29.020
[Amit Varma]: and that's how they were surviving and getting by.

02:49:29.020 --> 02:49:34.620
[Amit Varma]: So could it be a factor that are so much of our mindset and so many aspects of our culture

02:49:34.620 --> 02:49:38.780
[Amit Varma]: was shaped by these institutions that were put in place after independence?

02:49:38.780 --> 02:49:39.780
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:49:39.780 --> 02:49:43.180
[Guest]: So, I mean, I really sometimes, I mean, this is, you know, a conundrum.

02:49:43.180 --> 02:49:47.660
[Guest]: I mean, listen, none of us really saw a businessman while growing up.

02:49:47.660 --> 02:49:48.660
[Guest]: I mean, I didn't.

02:49:48.660 --> 02:49:55.780
[Guest]: I was living in a like a proper public sector unit sort of housing colony, never saw a businessman.

02:49:55.780 --> 02:50:02.620
[Guest]: But you know, this idea that business and businessmen, meaning they were like doing

02:50:02.620 --> 02:50:07.220
[Guest]: something shady was quite deep.

02:50:07.220 --> 02:50:13.580
[Guest]: I don't know whether the popular culture perpetuated that or we sort of, you know, actually had

02:50:13.580 --> 02:50:19.060
[Guest]: that sense of, you know, that these guys were not exactly above board in everything that

02:50:19.060 --> 02:50:20.060
[Guest]: they did.

02:50:20.060 --> 02:50:21.660
[Guest]: I don't know how and where it came from.

02:50:21.660 --> 02:50:27.140
[Guest]: I think, you know, and this is a question that I have asked many people of the previous

02:50:27.140 --> 02:50:31.780
[Guest]: generation also that where did it come from?

02:50:31.780 --> 02:50:35.860
[Guest]: Because many of you never saw any, you know, guy who has come coming out and exploiting

02:50:35.860 --> 02:50:39.620
[Guest]: you or a business guy who was doing something.

02:50:39.620 --> 02:50:47.340
[Guest]: I never got a correct answer except that the state was possibly perpetuating this myth

02:50:47.340 --> 02:50:53.260
[Guest]: in some, you know, one form or the other saying, you know, profits are a negative thing and,

02:50:53.260 --> 02:50:58.900
[Guest]: you know, all those kind of sort of messages across.

02:50:58.900 --> 02:51:05.740
[Guest]: So and then I think what happened is as the license permit raj became deeper, then a lot

02:51:05.740 --> 02:51:10.540
[Guest]: of these instincts that you had, you started seeing them get manifested whenever you had

02:51:10.540 --> 02:51:13.740
[Guest]: the small opportunity to see a private sector at work.

02:51:13.740 --> 02:51:19.660
[Guest]: You know, people would think that you could get by by bribing and you, I mean, basically,

02:51:19.660 --> 02:51:25.300
[Guest]: essentially, if you're in private sector, you are doing all of these things.

02:51:25.300 --> 02:51:30.000
[Guest]: But quite honestly, I don't know what the original sort of sin of the private sector

02:51:30.000 --> 02:51:34.460
[Guest]: was in India, apart from the colonial part.

02:51:34.460 --> 02:51:42.340
[Guest]: Maybe it was some of the, you know, early independence state drive, which gave the state

02:51:42.340 --> 02:51:49.100
[Guest]: such an exalted position that it just became that anyone who even sort of, you know, stands

02:51:49.100 --> 02:51:53.020
[Guest]: up to the state or wants to compete with the state was seen as someone who would actually

02:51:53.020 --> 02:51:55.140
[Guest]: be profiteering.

02:51:55.140 --> 02:51:57.660
[Guest]: It something that I have not understood at all.

02:51:57.660 --> 02:52:00.300
[Guest]: I mean, I can see it all over the popular culture.

02:52:00.300 --> 02:52:08.500
[Guest]: I mean, early 50s, you know, films and everything that was full of these kind of tropes.

02:52:08.500 --> 02:52:11.740
[Guest]: But no idea where it was coming from.

02:52:11.740 --> 02:52:17.180
[Guest]: Some people have told me that the Bengal famine was a huge, you know, sort of a mindset thing

02:52:17.180 --> 02:52:18.180
[Guest]: on people.

02:52:18.180 --> 02:52:25.140
[Guest]: But that was more of sort of a, you know, British Raj sort of dereliction of duty.

02:52:25.140 --> 02:52:30.300
[Guest]: And out of that, yes, there were people who afforded and the whole of hoarding as a thing

02:52:30.300 --> 02:52:34.620
[Guest]: that the rich people do became deeply embedded in our system.

02:52:34.620 --> 02:52:38.820
[Guest]: Some of the farm laws are actually a result of that Bengal famine and the thought process

02:52:38.820 --> 02:52:39.900
[Guest]: around that.

02:52:39.900 --> 02:52:40.900
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:52:40.900 --> 02:52:45.340
[Guest]: It's just some a whole bunch of small things that came together.

02:52:45.340 --> 02:52:47.700
[Guest]: Popular culture definitely perpetuated it.

02:52:47.700 --> 02:52:52.380
[Guest]: I don't think many people ever actually saw a real businessman in their life, but they

02:52:52.380 --> 02:52:54.900
[Guest]: had a view of what businessmen did.

02:52:54.900 --> 02:53:00.300
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, this is very interesting because I was fortunate enough to have a fairly privileged

02:53:00.300 --> 02:53:03.020
[Amit Varma]: childhood where my father was an IAS officer.

02:53:03.020 --> 02:53:05.580
[Amit Varma]: But even I don't remember seeing a businessman in my childhood.

02:53:05.580 --> 02:53:09.620
[Amit Varma]: As you were talking, I was thinking about, wait, who are the businessmen I had met as

02:53:09.620 --> 02:53:10.700
[Amit Varma]: a kid?

02:53:10.700 --> 02:53:16.140
[Amit Varma]: And I can't really think of anything until in post-liberalization India, I was out there

02:53:16.140 --> 02:53:17.140
[Amit Varma]: working and all of that.

02:53:17.140 --> 02:53:21.260
[Amit Varma]: And then I kind of encounter that part of it, maybe where we went shopping.

02:53:21.260 --> 02:53:25.820
[Amit Varma]: I mean, those are the only capitalists you would see who are selling you good things

02:53:25.820 --> 02:53:29.180
[Amit Varma]: and you're perfectly happy to buy from them.

02:53:29.180 --> 02:53:36.020
[Amit Varma]: The other very profound point that forms a TIL for me from all the newsletters of yours

02:53:36.020 --> 02:53:43.020
[Amit Varma]: that I have read was in number 90, where you talk about political versus economic institutions,

02:53:43.020 --> 02:53:48.260
[Amit Varma]: where you say, quote, in my view, a nation has to have its political and economic institutions

02:53:48.260 --> 02:53:49.860
[Amit Varma]: in sync with another.

02:53:49.860 --> 02:53:54.100
[Amit Varma]: It is difficult for it to have its political institutions extractive, exclusionary and

02:53:54.100 --> 02:53:58.740
[Amit Varma]: rent-seeking, while its economic institutions are liberal and inclusive and yet succeed

02:53:58.740 --> 02:54:00.380
[Amit Varma]: in the long run.

02:54:00.380 --> 02:54:04.260
[Amit Varma]: Having an extractive and exclusionary political institution while continuing to work with

02:54:04.260 --> 02:54:09.820
[Amit Varma]: economic institutions that are free and inclusive is an unstable equilibrium, stop quote.

02:54:09.820 --> 02:54:12.740
[Amit Varma]: And you talk more about this sort of unstable equilibrium.

02:54:12.740 --> 02:54:18.180
[Amit Varma]: And I'm fascinated by this because you point out how through the history of India, the

02:54:18.180 --> 02:54:23.500
[Amit Varma]: balance has shifted from one to the other, where first political institutions were inclusive

02:54:23.500 --> 02:54:26.700
[Amit Varma]: and liberal while economic institutions were statist.

02:54:26.700 --> 02:54:29.020
[Amit Varma]: Then under Indira, they both become statist.

02:54:29.020 --> 02:54:34.380
[Amit Varma]: Then the economic institutions reform after 1991, but then there is a bit of an about-turn

02:54:34.380 --> 02:54:39.460
[Amit Varma]: with political institutions and, you know, now they could all sort of turn illiberal.

02:54:39.460 --> 02:54:46.140
[Amit Varma]: So expand a bit on this kind of thinking because I haven't come across this frame anywhere

02:54:46.140 --> 02:54:47.140
[Guest]: else.

02:54:47.140 --> 02:54:52.940
[Guest]: Yes, I again, I mean, I don't exactly recollect what sort of triggered this.

02:54:52.940 --> 02:55:00.260
[Guest]: I think the point that possibly could have triggered is the, you know, just rethinking,

02:55:00.260 --> 02:55:08.820
[Guest]: you know, Darren Acemoglu's, you know, book and about, you know, what actually makes nation

02:55:08.820 --> 02:55:10.980
[Guest]: succeed or fail.

02:55:10.980 --> 02:55:16.100
[Guest]: And his point there was that it is about institutions.

02:55:16.100 --> 02:55:20.080
[Guest]: And he takes us through an entire sort of, you know, journey about, you know, different

02:55:20.080 --> 02:55:26.460
[Guest]: people having views about why nations fail or succeed, eliminates geography, eliminates

02:55:26.460 --> 02:55:30.780
[Guest]: all kinds of things and comes to a conclusion that it is about institutions.

02:55:30.780 --> 02:55:36.180
[Guest]: And my sort of taking off point from there was, okay, what kind of institutions?

02:55:36.180 --> 02:55:38.180
[Guest]: I mean, are you only talking political?

02:55:38.180 --> 02:55:41.020
[Guest]: Are you talking political as well as economic?

02:55:41.020 --> 02:55:46.420
[Guest]: And you know, is there a sort of a difference and then sort of this, you know, analysis

02:55:46.420 --> 02:55:55.300
[Guest]: of how we might have gone out about in the last 70 years on these two institutions and

02:55:55.300 --> 02:55:58.620
[Guest]: is there some, have these been in sync?

02:55:58.620 --> 02:56:03.100
[Guest]: And so that's really how it sort of came about in terms of the thought process.

02:56:03.100 --> 02:56:07.860
[Guest]: And then it sort of followed that, you know, there was a time when our political institutions,

02:56:07.860 --> 02:56:12.420
[Guest]: not that there was a time, I think they were designed to be liberal and inclusive, unlike

02:56:12.420 --> 02:56:19.980
[Guest]: say some of the other, you know, democratic or not so democratic governments or models

02:56:19.980 --> 02:56:22.260
[Guest]: that other countries adopted.

02:56:22.260 --> 02:56:29.760
[Guest]: And when that was happening, the economic institutions were fairly, I would say, different

02:56:29.760 --> 02:56:30.760
[Guest]: from this.

02:56:30.760 --> 02:56:33.140
[Guest]: So they didn't hew to the liberalized lines.

02:56:33.140 --> 02:56:39.820
[Guest]: And then of course, during the 70s, both of them fell in sync, which was a disaster, a

02:56:39.820 --> 02:56:42.060
[Guest]: complete unmitigated disaster.

02:56:42.060 --> 02:56:46.620
[Guest]: And then, you know, then we have had a little bit of a, you know, swing the other way.

02:56:46.620 --> 02:56:50.900
[Guest]: And the hope is, and which is again the point around, you know, what is the hope?

02:56:50.900 --> 02:56:57.620
[Guest]: The hope is somewhere somebody will get the sort of light bulb moment that both should

02:56:57.620 --> 02:57:04.820
[Guest]: be, you know, in sync and, you know, liberal and inclusive because, you know, how many

02:57:04.820 --> 02:57:09.660
[Guest]: ways will you try before figuring out that this is the way that might actually work because

02:57:09.660 --> 02:57:10.920
[Guest]: it's worked everywhere.

02:57:10.920 --> 02:57:16.140
[Guest]: And you've now exhausted all combinations, exhausted one of this and the other.

02:57:16.140 --> 02:57:23.140
[Guest]: So my view is, okay, you try 20 odd years of each, or 25 odd years of each.

02:57:23.140 --> 02:57:29.500
[Guest]: Hopefully now you'll figure out that the next 25, the last 25 of the first century of India's

02:57:29.500 --> 02:57:34.220
[Guest]: independence, you might try the last one, which is the one that possibly in my mind

02:57:34.220 --> 02:57:37.500
[Guest]: is the best, but you'll stumble at your way and reach there.

02:57:37.500 --> 02:57:40.940
[Guest]: I think that's really where that particular thought came from.

02:57:40.940 --> 02:57:44.380
[Amit Varma]: Since you're thinking of the trigger, I think in this particular edition, you were talking

02:57:44.380 --> 02:57:45.820
[Amit Varma]: about the RBI.

02:57:45.820 --> 02:57:49.860
[Amit Varma]: So that was one of the economic institutions you sort of had in mind.

02:57:49.860 --> 02:57:54.020
[Amit Varma]: But you know, to sort of probe a little bit further, if I may double click, if we are

02:57:54.020 --> 02:57:59.360
[Amit Varma]: to sort of demystify that, what do we mean by economic, both political and economic institutions

02:57:59.360 --> 02:58:02.780
[Amit Varma]: becoming more liberal and inclusive?

02:58:02.780 --> 02:58:04.820
[Amit Varma]: What do we mean by that in concrete terms?

02:58:04.820 --> 02:58:05.980
[Guest]: Can you expand on that a bit?

02:58:05.980 --> 02:58:09.500
[Guest]: Yeah, I think so, the economic institutions are the institutions that we have formed over

02:58:09.500 --> 02:58:10.500
[Guest]: the years.

02:58:10.500 --> 02:58:15.820
[Guest]: I mean, there are, of course, regulators, there are various kinds of, you know, bodies

02:58:15.820 --> 02:58:22.340
[Guest]: that are not exactly, I would say, that they're more permanent sort of bodies that are around,

02:58:22.340 --> 02:58:27.740
[Guest]: whether you call it NITI, IOBIRD, Erstwhile Planning Commission, various regulators, various

02:58:27.740 --> 02:58:29.500
[Guest]: commissions that we form.

02:58:29.500 --> 02:58:31.220
[Guest]: And what are the mandates for these?

02:58:31.220 --> 02:58:36.700
[Guest]: I mean, mandates for many of these are even, you know, the kind of earlier we used to have

02:58:36.700 --> 02:58:41.780
[Guest]: these MRTP, you know, the Monopolies and Restricted Trade Practices Act, we've dismantled all

02:58:41.780 --> 02:58:45.300
[Guest]: of them, replaced them with something more benign.

02:58:45.300 --> 02:58:50.980
[Guest]: You know, many, many of these areas, I mean, the forex, the, what used to be called, you

02:58:50.980 --> 02:58:57.020
[Guest]: know, I think there was an act, I forget the full form of that act, which was

02:58:57.020 --> 02:58:58.580
[Guest]: FERA, Foreign Exchange Regulation.

02:58:58.580 --> 02:59:03.940
[Guest]: Now, there was one before FERA, I think, Conservation of Foreign Exchange and Prevention of something,

02:59:03.940 --> 02:59:07.700
[Guest]: smuggling activities, coffee posa, and things of that kind.

02:59:07.700 --> 02:59:13.860
[Guest]: So, all of these have moved towards institutions that we have now created, which actually are

02:59:13.860 --> 02:59:17.940
[Guest]: not as sort of terrible as they were in the past.

02:59:17.940 --> 02:59:22.300
[Guest]: And the political institutions are our usual political institutions, you know, they are,

02:59:22.300 --> 02:59:28.500
[Guest]: you know, the Parliament, the Election Commission, you know, the various bodies of legislation

02:59:28.500 --> 02:59:32.580
[Guest]: and legislatures and administrative machinery of the state.

02:59:32.580 --> 02:59:37.500
[Guest]: So that's where my view was that on the economic front, I think we have moved quite a bit of

02:59:37.500 --> 02:59:43.580
[Guest]: distance and gradually turned more and more inclusive and liberal.

02:59:43.580 --> 02:59:49.300
[Guest]: You might argue that some of the regulators, etc., have disproportionate power, but that's

02:59:49.300 --> 02:59:50.300
[Guest]: fine.

02:59:50.300 --> 02:59:52.500
[Guest]: I mean, I think it's true for most of the regulators in the world.

02:59:52.500 --> 02:59:59.180
[Guest]: But broadly, they are way more forward-looking and forward-thinking than some of the things

02:59:59.180 --> 03:00:02.340
[Guest]: that we have seen happen on the political institution space.

03:00:02.340 --> 03:00:03.340
[Amit Varma]: Right.

03:00:03.340 --> 03:00:05.540
[Amit Varma]: And in terms of political institutions?

03:00:05.540 --> 03:00:06.540
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:00:06.540 --> 03:00:14.580
[Guest]: So, I think on political institutions, if you take, I mean, I would club most of the

03:00:14.580 --> 03:00:22.180
[Guest]: things that we do, you know, most of the institutions that we have of the kind, whether it is, you

03:00:22.180 --> 03:00:28.140
[Guest]: know, Election Commission, or it is, you know, I mean, any of the arm of the state, whether

03:00:28.140 --> 03:00:35.660
[Guest]: it is police or it is judiciary, or some of the things that where we have the governor

03:00:35.660 --> 03:00:43.260
[Guest]: and, you know, many of these sort of things where you expect them to be, you know, and

03:00:43.260 --> 03:00:47.740
[Guest]: we spoke about some of this in terms of where some of these institutions are now taking

03:00:47.740 --> 03:00:51.900
[Guest]: an illiberal turn in the first part of the conversation.

03:00:51.900 --> 03:00:58.740
[Guest]: I think those, we are again seeing that they have continued to remain, I think there was

03:00:58.740 --> 03:01:03.460
[Guest]: a time when it was starting to become somewhat more inclusive and liberal.

03:01:03.460 --> 03:01:07.660
[Guest]: But I think they are again, you know, I would say they have not kept pace with the change

03:01:07.660 --> 03:01:08.940
[Guest]: of the economic institutions.

03:01:08.940 --> 03:01:12.780
[Guest]: I think they have still, you know, in some places remained the same, in some places my

03:01:12.780 --> 03:01:14.780
[Amit Varma]: fear is they are regressing.

03:01:14.780 --> 03:01:18.980
[Amit Varma]: That's a fascinating frame to think about the problem with.

03:01:18.980 --> 03:01:20.460
[Amit Varma]: So I've taken enough of your time.

03:01:20.460 --> 03:01:22.220
[Amit Varma]: I'll ask you a couple of final questions.

03:01:22.220 --> 03:01:27.500
[Amit Varma]: And I think these should be easier and less sort of depressing.

03:01:27.500 --> 03:01:32.820
[Amit Varma]: And one of them is this, that, you know, as you would know, listeners of my show are constantly

03:01:32.820 --> 03:01:36.380
[Amit Varma]: asking me and my guests to recommend books to read.

03:01:36.380 --> 03:01:40.460
[Amit Varma]: You know, what are the foundational books that you feel everyone should read?

03:01:40.460 --> 03:01:44.900
[Amit Varma]: Maybe books that shaped your thinking, or even if you came across some late books that

03:01:44.900 --> 03:01:49.460
[Amit Varma]: you wish you had come across earlier and that, you know, made an impact on who you are and

03:01:49.460 --> 03:01:55.580
[Amit Varma]: even, you know, to add a sort of another element to that books that can help people understand

03:01:55.580 --> 03:01:57.220
[Amit Varma]: India better.

03:01:57.220 --> 03:02:04.420
[Guest]: So in terms of, let's start with books that can help you understand India better.

03:02:04.420 --> 03:02:09.980
[Guest]: I think I would recommend Ram Guha's, a couple of Ram Guha's books.

03:02:09.980 --> 03:02:13.380
[Guest]: I think the India after Gandhi is a fantastic book.

03:02:13.380 --> 03:02:21.460
[Guest]: It's a very sort of a broad, but fairly well sort of researched and thought out book about

03:02:21.460 --> 03:02:26.100
[Guest]: where we are and what brought us here.

03:02:26.100 --> 03:02:31.100
[Guest]: So that's one book that I found quite useful.

03:02:31.100 --> 03:02:36.300
[Guest]: The other book that I think, and a lot of literature that's come out in the last couple

03:02:36.300 --> 03:02:41.060
[Guest]: of years, and you have featured a lot of them on your show, are quite actually fascinating.

03:02:41.060 --> 03:02:47.140
[Guest]: And actually, you know, we are starting to do some good work and some good, you know,

03:02:47.140 --> 03:02:50.100
[Guest]: academic work around this in very accessible form.

03:02:50.100 --> 03:02:59.580
[Guest]: So I think that, I mean, for me, the India's founding moment, which was Madhav Khosla,

03:02:59.580 --> 03:03:01.540
[Guest]: that was again a fantastic book.

03:03:01.540 --> 03:03:07.340
[Guest]: I think I learned a lot from that book, a very well researched book.

03:03:07.340 --> 03:03:09.860
[Guest]: And I think that's again something that I would recommend.

03:03:09.860 --> 03:03:17.580
[Guest]: I would recommend some of the books on history, which, you know, people must just go back

03:03:17.580 --> 03:03:22.500
[Guest]: and read for the medieval India, sort of that kind of time period.

03:03:22.500 --> 03:03:28.700
[Guest]: There is a five volume book of Jadunath Sarkar.

03:03:28.700 --> 03:03:33.980
[Guest]: It's quite an academic book, but the fifth one is just outstanding.

03:03:33.980 --> 03:03:41.580
[Guest]: That's just the post-Mughal, Maratha, British, East India Company sort of the phase.

03:03:41.580 --> 03:03:47.780
[Guest]: And I read it a long time back, maybe 20 plus years back.

03:03:47.780 --> 03:03:51.180
[Guest]: But that again, was very interesting.

03:03:51.180 --> 03:03:57.620
[Guest]: It gives you a very sort of real perspective of all the things that the ferment, which

03:03:57.620 --> 03:04:03.020
[Guest]: sort of led to the British East India Company sort of establishing itself, which I thought

03:04:03.020 --> 03:04:04.900
[Guest]: was quite useful.

03:04:04.900 --> 03:04:13.540
[Guest]: I also, I mean, on economics, I have read both Bhagwati and Sen, and I would recommend

03:04:13.540 --> 03:04:14.540
[Guest]: both.

03:04:14.540 --> 03:04:19.020
[Guest]: You know, I think some of the early Sen, I mean, especially books on where he writes

03:04:19.020 --> 03:04:23.460
[Guest]: on freedom, I think those are very good.

03:04:23.460 --> 03:04:29.700
[Guest]: And I think there is a lot there, which will change your view about how, what Sen really

03:04:29.700 --> 03:04:30.700
[Amit Varma]: believes in.

03:04:30.700 --> 03:04:35.980
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in edition 82 of your newsletter, you write about Amartya Sen and freedom and

03:04:35.980 --> 03:04:38.820
[Amit Varma]: how you began to reconsider some of his ideas.

03:04:38.820 --> 03:04:40.620
[Amit Varma]: So I'll link that from the show notes as well.

03:04:40.620 --> 03:04:45.460
[Amit Varma]: I did plan to ask you about that and about Rawls versus Nozick and all of that.

03:04:45.460 --> 03:04:47.220
[Amit Varma]: But we'll have to save that for some other day.

03:04:47.220 --> 03:04:48.220
[Amit Varma]: But sorry, sorry to interrupt.

03:04:48.220 --> 03:04:49.220
[Amit Varma]: Do continue.

03:04:49.220 --> 03:04:50.220
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:04:50.220 --> 03:04:52.820
[Guest]: So that's, I would recommend both Sen and Bhagwati.

03:04:52.820 --> 03:04:56.660
[Guest]: I think both are very good, very interesting books.

03:04:56.660 --> 03:05:02.780
[Guest]: The Idea of India, which was Sunil Khildani's book in 97, on the 50th anniversary of Indian

03:05:02.780 --> 03:05:03.780
[Guest]: independence.

03:05:03.780 --> 03:05:07.180
[Guest]: Again, fantastic book, very informative.

03:05:07.180 --> 03:05:12.740
[Guest]: And you know, one of the great influences of my life, again, forget the person, read

03:05:12.740 --> 03:05:16.740
[Guest]: his book, kind of a guy, is Naipaul.

03:05:16.740 --> 03:05:23.740
[Guest]: And I find all three of Naipaul's books on India are very, very interesting.

03:05:23.740 --> 03:05:25.980
[Guest]: He was a perceptive observer.

03:05:25.980 --> 03:05:31.580
[Guest]: You know, he was a person who could spend like a day in a place and dig out things that

03:05:31.580 --> 03:05:36.380
[Guest]: you would take ages to ever figure out that this is what is happening there.

03:05:36.380 --> 03:05:39.900
[Guest]: So all three Naipaul books are very, very interesting.

03:05:39.900 --> 03:05:45.260
[Guest]: You can discount some of his ideas about India and you can discount some of the views he

03:05:45.260 --> 03:05:48.340
[Guest]: later had about his political views.

03:05:48.340 --> 03:05:54.620
[Guest]: But I think as just understanding of India, you can't argue that he got it right in all

03:05:54.620 --> 03:05:56.140
[Amit Varma]: the three of the books.

03:05:56.140 --> 03:05:57.140
[Amit Varma]: Fabulous.

03:05:57.140 --> 03:05:58.700
[Amit Varma]: And now my final question for you.

03:05:58.700 --> 03:06:04.580
[Amit Varma]: This is not the hope and despair question, but rather as you, in your news, in the many

03:06:04.580 --> 03:06:10.500
[Amit Varma]: editions of your newsletters, you've sort of made me rethink things that I hadn't thought

03:06:10.500 --> 03:06:14.580
[Amit Varma]: so deeply about and, you know, given me a few TIL moments.

03:06:14.580 --> 03:06:19.700
[Amit Varma]: So can you share with me one or more, but you know, more would be Sone Pe Sohaga.

03:06:19.700 --> 03:06:25.100
[Amit Varma]: But can you share with me one idea that you think everyone should internalize?

03:06:25.100 --> 03:06:28.940
[Amit Varma]: One notion or concept or idea which you think everyone should internalize?

03:06:28.940 --> 03:06:32.020
[Amit Varma]: So obviously something that's not popular right now.

03:06:32.020 --> 03:06:37.780
[Guest]: No, I think on this again, I think we will end the show on a strong note of agreement

03:06:37.780 --> 03:06:45.380
[Guest]: because the one idea that I think everyone should internalize is that spontaneous order

03:06:45.380 --> 03:06:46.380
[Guest]: works.

03:06:46.380 --> 03:06:48.620
[Guest]: I mean, there is something called spontaneous order, boss.

03:06:48.620 --> 03:06:54.220
[Guest]: I mean, let people have individual liberty and freedom, let them choose their things

03:06:54.220 --> 03:07:01.180
[Guest]: if they choose, people do multitudes of these transactions, you know, all of these things

03:07:01.180 --> 03:07:06.140
[Guest]: then together create something where, you know, order comes on its own.

03:07:06.140 --> 03:07:07.900
[Guest]: Nobody needs to direct it.

03:07:07.900 --> 03:07:10.740
[Guest]: Nobody needs to guide it to a certain place.

03:07:10.740 --> 03:07:13.660
[Guest]: It's been proven over and over again.

03:07:13.660 --> 03:07:19.300
[Guest]: And any amount of tinkering with this, shifting this, trying to do something around this with

03:07:19.300 --> 03:07:24.420
[Guest]: all the good intentions actually leads to worse outcomes, proven time and again.

03:07:24.420 --> 03:07:25.420
[Amit Varma]: Excellent.

03:07:25.420 --> 03:07:26.420
[Amit Varma]: That is a note of agreement.

03:07:26.420 --> 03:07:31.260
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, voluntary action, Zindabad, state coercion, Murdabad, and on that adequately

03:07:31.260 --> 03:07:35.780
[Amit Varma]: filmy note, Raghu, let me thank you once again for, you know, sharing your time and your

